-- | Origin access identity configuration. Send a <tt>GET</tt> request to
--   the <tt>/CloudFront API version/CloudFront/identity ID/config</tt>
--   resource.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newCloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityConfig</a> smart
--   constructor.
data CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityConfig
CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityConfig' :: Text -> Text -> CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityConfig

-- | A unique value (for example, a date-time stamp) that ensures that the
--   request can't be replayed.
--   
--   If the value of <tt>CallerReference</tt> is new (regardless of the
--   content of the <tt>CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityConfig</tt> object),
--   a new origin access identity is created.
--   
--   If the <tt>CallerReference</tt> is a value already sent in a previous
--   identity request, and the content of the
--   <tt>CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityConfig</tt> is identical to the
--   original request (ignoring white space), the response includes the
--   same information returned to the original request.
--   
--   If the <tt>CallerReference</tt> is a value you already sent in a
--   previous request to create an identity, but the content of the
--   <tt>CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityConfig</tt> is different from the
--   original request, CloudFront returns a
--   <tt>CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityAlreadyExists</tt> error.
[$sel:callerReference:CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityConfig'] :: CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityConfig -> Text

-- | A comment to describe the origin access identity. The comment cannot
--   be longer than 128 characters.
[$sel:comment:CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityConfig'] :: CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityConfig -> Text

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList

-- | Lists the origin access identities for CloudFront.Send a <tt>GET</tt>
--   request to the <tt>/CloudFront API
--   version/origin-access-identity/cloudfront</tt> resource. The response
--   includes a <tt>CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList</tt> element with
--   zero or more <tt>CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentitySummary</tt> child
--   elements. By default, your entire list of origin access identities is
--   returned in one single page. If the list is long, you can paginate it
--   using the <tt>MaxItems</tt> and <tt>Marker</tt> parameters.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newCloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList</a> smart
--   constructor.
data CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList
CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList' :: Maybe [CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentitySummary] -> Maybe Text -> Text -> Int -> Bool -> Int -> CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList

-- | A complex type that contains one
--   <tt>CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentitySummary</tt> element for each origin
--   access identity that was created by the current account.
[$sel:items:CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList'] :: CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList -> Maybe [CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentitySummary]

-- | If <tt>IsTruncated</tt> is <tt>true</tt>, this element is present and
--   contains the value you can use for the <tt>Marker</tt> request
--   parameter to continue listing your origin access identities where they
--   left off.
[$sel:nextMarker:CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList'] :: CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList -> Maybe Text

-- | Use this when paginating results to indicate where to begin in your
--   list of origin access identities. The results include identities in
--   the list that occur after the marker. To get the next page of results,
--   set the <tt>Marker</tt> to the value of the <tt>NextMarker</tt> from
--   the current page's response (which is also the ID of the last identity
--   on that page).
[$sel:marker:CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList'] :: CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList -> Text

-- | The maximum number of origin access identities you want in the
--   response body.
[$sel:maxItems:CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList'] :: CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList -> Int

-- | A flag that indicates whether more origin access identities remain to
--   be listed. If your results were truncated, you can make a follow-up
--   pagination request using the <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter to
--   retrieve more items in the list.
[$sel:isTruncated:CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList'] :: CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList -> Bool

-- | The number of CloudFront origin access identities that were created by
--   the current account.
[$sel:quantity:CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList'] :: CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>CloudFrontOriginAccessIdentityList</a> with all
--   optional fields omitted.

--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ConflictingAlias

-- | An alias (also called a CNAME) and the CloudFront distribution and
--   Amazon Web Services account ID that it’s associated with. The
--   distribution and account IDs are partially hidden, which allows you to
--   identify the distributions and accounts that you own, but helps to
--   protect the information of ones that you don’t own.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newConflictingAlias</a> smart constructor.
data ConflictingAlias
ConflictingAlias' :: Maybe Text -> Maybe Text -> Maybe Text -> ConflictingAlias

-- | An alias (also called a CNAME).
[$sel:alias:ConflictingAlias'] :: ConflictingAlias -> Maybe Text

-- | The (partially hidden) ID of the Amazon Web Services account that owns
--   the distribution that’s associated with the alias.
[$sel:accountId:ConflictingAlias'] :: ConflictingAlias -> Maybe Text

-- | The (partially hidden) ID of the CloudFront distribution associated
--   with the alias.
[$sel:distributionId:ConflictingAlias'] :: ConflictingAlias -> Maybe Text

-- | Create a value of <a>ConflictingAlias</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:alias:ConflictingAlias'</a>, <a>conflictingAlias_alias</a> -
--   An alias (also called a CNAME).
--   
--   <a>$sel:accountId:ConflictingAlias'</a>,
--   <a>conflictingAlias_accountId</a> - The (partially hidden) ID of the
--   Amazon Web Services account that owns the distribution that’s
--   associated with the alias.
--   
--   <a>$sel:distributionId:ConflictingAlias'</a>,
--   <a>conflictingAlias_distributionId</a> - The (partially hidden) ID of
--   the CloudFront distribution associated with the alias.
newConflictingAlias :: ConflictingAlias

-- | An alias (also called a CNAME).
conflictingAlias_alias :: Lens' ConflictingAlias (Maybe Text)

-- | The (partially hidden) ID of the Amazon Web Services account that owns
--   the distribution that’s associated with the alias.
conflictingAlias_accountId :: Lens' ConflictingAlias (Maybe Text)

-- | The (partially hidden) ID of the CloudFront distribution associated
--   with the alias.
conflictingAlias_distributionId :: Lens' ConflictingAlias (Maybe Text)
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ConflictingAlias.ConflictingAlias
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ConflictingAlias.ConflictingAlias

instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ConflictingAlias.ConflictingAlias

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyCookiesConfig

-- | An object that determines whether any cookies in viewer requests (and
--   if so, which cookies) are included in the cache key and automatically
--   included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newCachePolicyCookiesConfig</a> smart constructor.
data CachePolicyCookiesConfig
CachePolicyCookiesConfig' :: Maybe CookieNames -> CachePolicyCookieBehavior -> CachePolicyCookiesConfig
[$sel:cookies:CachePolicyCookiesConfig'] :: CachePolicyCookiesConfig -> Maybe CookieNames

-- | Determines whether any cookies in viewer requests are included in the
--   cache key and automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends
--   to the origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – Cookies in viewer requests are not included in the
--   cache key and are not automatically included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin. Even when this field is set to
--   <tt>none</tt>, any cookies that are listed in an
--   <tt>OriginRequestPolicy</tt> <i>are</i> included in origin
--   requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The cookies in viewer requests that are
--   listed in the <tt>CookieNames</tt> type are included in the cache key
--   and automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the
--   origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>allExcept</tt> – All cookies in viewer requests that are
--   <i><b>not</b></i> listed in the <tt>CookieNames</tt> type are included
--   in the cache key and automatically included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>all</tt> – All cookies in viewer requests are included in the
--   cache key and are automatically included in requests that CloudFront
--   sends to the origin.</li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:cookieBehavior:CachePolicyCookiesConfig'] :: CachePolicyCookiesConfig -> CachePolicyCookieBehavior

-- | Create a value of <a>CachePolicyCookiesConfig</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:cookies:CachePolicyCookiesConfig'</a>,
--   <a>cachePolicyCookiesConfig_cookies</a> - Undocumented member.
--   
--   <a>$sel:cookieBehavior:CachePolicyCookiesConfig'</a>,
--   <a>cachePolicyCookiesConfig_cookieBehavior</a> - Determines whether
--   any cookies in viewer requests are included in the cache key and
--   automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the
--   origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – Cookies in viewer requests are not included in the
--   cache key and are not automatically included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin. Even when this field is set to
--   <tt>none</tt>, any cookies that are listed in an
--   <tt>OriginRequestPolicy</tt> <i>are</i> included in origin
--   requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The cookies in viewer requests that are
--   listed in the <tt>CookieNames</tt> type are included in the cache key
--   and automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the
--   origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>allExcept</tt> – All cookies in viewer requests that are
--   <i><b>not</b></i> listed in the <tt>CookieNames</tt> type are included
--   in the cache key and automatically included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>all</tt> – All cookies in viewer requests are included in the
--   cache key and are automatically included in requests that CloudFront
--   sends to the origin.</li>
--   </ul>
newCachePolicyCookiesConfig :: CachePolicyCookieBehavior -> CachePolicyCookiesConfig

-- | Undocumented member.
cachePolicyCookiesConfig_cookies :: Lens' CachePolicyCookiesConfig (Maybe CookieNames)

-- | Determines whether any cookies in viewer requests are included in the
--   cache key and automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends
--   to the origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – Cookies in viewer requests are not included in the
--   cache key and are not automatically included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin. Even when this field is set to
--   <tt>none</tt>, any cookies that are listed in an
--   <tt>OriginRequestPolicy</tt> <i>are</i> included in origin
--   requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The cookies in viewer requests that are
--   listed in the <tt>CookieNames</tt> type are included in the cache key
--   and automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the
--   origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>allExcept</tt> – All cookies in viewer requests that are
--   <i><b>not</b></i> listed in the <tt>CookieNames</tt> type are included
--   in the cache key and automatically included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>all</tt> – All cookies in viewer requests are included in the
--   cache key and are automatically included in requests that CloudFront
--   sends to the origin.</li>
--   </ul>
cachePolicyCookiesConfig_cookieBehavior :: Lens' CachePolicyCookiesConfig CachePolicyCookieBehavior
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyCookiesConfig.CachePolicyCookiesConfig
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyCookiesConfig.CachePolicyCookiesConfig
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyCookiesConfig.CachePolicyCookiesConfig
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyCookiesConfig.CachePolicyCookiesConfig
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyCookiesConfig.CachePolicyCookiesConfig
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyCookiesConfig.CachePolicyCookiesConfig
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyCookiesConfig.CachePolicyCookiesConfig
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyCookiesConfig.CachePolicyCookiesConfig


module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponse

-- | A complex type that controls:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>Whether CloudFront replaces HTTP status codes in the 4xx and 5xx
--   range with custom error messages before returning the response to the
--   viewer.</li>
--   <li>How long CloudFront caches HTTP status codes in the 4xx and 5xx
--   range.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For more information about custom error pages, see <a>Customizing
--   Error Responses</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newCustomErrorResponse</a> smart constructor.
data CustomErrorResponse
CustomErrorResponse' :: Maybe Text -> Maybe Text -> Maybe Integer -> Int -> CustomErrorResponse

-- | The path to the custom error page that you want CloudFront to return
--   to a viewer when your origin returns the HTTP status code specified by
--   <tt>ErrorCode</tt>, for example,
--   <tt>/4xx-errors/403-forbidden.html</tt>. If you want to store your
--   objects and your custom error pages in different locations, your
--   distribution must include a cache behavior for which the following is
--   true:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The value of <tt>PathPattern</tt> matches the path to your custom
--   error messages. For example, suppose you saved custom error pages for
--   4xx errors in an Amazon S3 bucket in a directory named
--   <tt>/4xx-errors</tt>. Your distribution must include a cache behavior
--   for which the path pattern routes requests for your custom error pages
--   to that location, for example, <tt>/4xx-errors/*</tt>.</li>
--   <li>The value of <tt>TargetOriginId</tt> specifies the value of the
--   <tt>ID</tt> element for the origin that contains your custom error
--   pages.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If you specify a value for <tt>ResponsePagePath</tt>, you must also
--   specify a value for <tt>ResponseCode</tt>.
--   
--   We recommend that you store custom error pages in an Amazon S3 bucket.
--   If you store custom error pages on an HTTP server and the server
--   starts to return 5xx errors, CloudFront can't get the files that you
--   want to return to viewers because the origin server is unavailable.
[$sel:responsePagePath:CustomErrorResponse'] :: CustomErrorResponse -> Maybe Text

-- | The HTTP status code that you want CloudFront to return to the viewer
--   along with the custom error page. There are a variety of reasons that
--   you might want CloudFront to return a status code different from the
--   status code that your origin returned to CloudFront, for example:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>Some Internet devices (some firewalls and corporate proxies, for
--   example) intercept HTTP 4xx and 5xx and prevent the response from
--   being returned to the viewer. If you substitute <tt>200</tt>, the
--   response typically won't be intercepted.</li>
--   <li>If you don't care about distinguishing among different client
--   errors or server errors, you can specify <tt>400</tt> or <tt>500</tt>
--   as the <tt>ResponseCode</tt> for all 4xx or 5xx errors.</li>
--   <li>You might want to return a <tt>200</tt> status code (OK) and
--   static website so your customers don't know that your website is
--   down.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If you specify a value for <tt>ResponseCode</tt>, you must also
--   specify a value for <tt>ResponsePagePath</tt>.
[$sel:responseCode:CustomErrorResponse'] :: CustomErrorResponse -> Maybe Text

-- | The minimum amount of time, in seconds, that you want CloudFront to
--   cache the HTTP status code specified in <tt>ErrorCode</tt>. When this
--   time period has elapsed, CloudFront queries your origin to see whether
--   the problem that caused the error has been resolved and the requested
--   object is now available.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Customizing Error Responses</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:errorCachingMinTTL:CustomErrorResponse'] :: CustomErrorResponse -> Maybe Integer

-- | The HTTP status code for which you want to specify a custom error page
--   and/or a caching duration.
[$sel:errorCode:CustomErrorResponse'] :: CustomErrorResponse -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>CustomErrorResponse</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:responsePagePath:CustomErrorResponse'</a>,
--   <a>customErrorResponse_responsePagePath</a> - The path to the custom
--   error page that you want CloudFront to return to a viewer when your
--   origin returns the HTTP status code specified by <tt>ErrorCode</tt>,
--   for example, <tt>/4xx-errors/403-forbidden.html</tt>. If you want to
--   store your objects and your custom error pages in different locations,
--   your distribution must include a cache behavior for which the
--   following is true:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The value of <tt>PathPattern</tt> matches the path to your custom
--   error messages. For example, suppose you saved custom error pages for
--   4xx errors in an Amazon S3 bucket in a directory named
--   <tt>/4xx-errors</tt>. Your distribution must include a cache behavior
--   for which the path pattern routes requests for your custom error pages
--   to that location, for example, <tt>/4xx-errors/*</tt>.</li>
--   <li>The value of <tt>TargetOriginId</tt> specifies the value of the
--   <tt>ID</tt> element for the origin that contains your custom error
--   pages.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If you specify a value for <tt>ResponsePagePath</tt>, you must also
--   specify a value for <tt>ResponseCode</tt>.
--   
--   We recommend that you store custom error pages in an Amazon S3 bucket.
--   If you store custom error pages on an HTTP server and the server
--   starts to return 5xx errors, CloudFront can't get the files that you
--   want to return to viewers because the origin server is unavailable.
--   
--   <a>$sel:responseCode:CustomErrorResponse'</a>,
--   <a>customErrorResponse_responseCode</a> - The HTTP status code that
--   you want CloudFront to return to the viewer along with the custom
--   error page. There are a variety of reasons that you might want
--   CloudFront to return a status code different from the status code that
--   your origin returned to CloudFront, for example:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>Some Internet devices (some firewalls and corporate proxies, for
--   example) intercept HTTP 4xx and 5xx and prevent the response from
--   being returned to the viewer. If you substitute <tt>200</tt>, the
--   response typically won't be intercepted.</li>
--   <li>If you don't care about distinguishing among different client
--   errors or server errors, you can specify <tt>400</tt> or <tt>500</tt>
--   as the <tt>ResponseCode</tt> for all 4xx or 5xx errors.</li>
--   <li>You might want to return a <tt>200</tt> status code (OK) and
--   static website so your customers don't know that your website is
--   down.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If you specify a value for <tt>ResponseCode</tt>, you must also
--   specify a value for <tt>ResponsePagePath</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:errorCachingMinTTL:CustomErrorResponse'</a>,
--   <a>customErrorResponse_errorCachingMinTTL</a> - The minimum amount of
--   time, in seconds, that you want CloudFront to cache the HTTP status
--   code specified in <tt>ErrorCode</tt>. When this time period has
--   elapsed, CloudFront queries your origin to see whether the problem
--   that caused the error has been resolved and the requested object is
--   now available.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Customizing Error Responses</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:errorCode:CustomErrorResponse'</a>,
--   <a>customErrorResponse_errorCode</a> - The HTTP status code for which
--   you want to specify a custom error page and/or a caching duration.
newCustomErrorResponse :: Int -> CustomErrorResponse

-- | The path to the custom error page that you want CloudFront to return
--   to a viewer when your origin returns the HTTP status code specified by
--   <tt>ErrorCode</tt>, for example,
--   <tt>/4xx-errors/403-forbidden.html</tt>. If you want to store your
--   objects and your custom error pages in different locations, your
--   distribution must include a cache behavior for which the following is
--   true:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The value of <tt>PathPattern</tt> matches the path to your custom
--   error messages. For example, suppose you saved custom error pages for
--   4xx errors in an Amazon S3 bucket in a directory named
--   <tt>/4xx-errors</tt>. Your distribution must include a cache behavior
--   for which the path pattern routes requests for your custom error pages
--   to that location, for example, <tt>/4xx-errors/*</tt>.</li>
--   <li>The value of <tt>TargetOriginId</tt> specifies the value of the
--   <tt>ID</tt> element for the origin that contains your custom error
--   pages.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If you specify a value for <tt>ResponsePagePath</tt>, you must also
--   specify a value for <tt>ResponseCode</tt>.
--   
--   We recommend that you store custom error pages in an Amazon S3 bucket.
--   If you store custom error pages on an HTTP server and the server
--   starts to return 5xx errors, CloudFront can't get the files that you
--   want to return to viewers because the origin server is unavailable.
customErrorResponse_responsePagePath :: Lens' CustomErrorResponse (Maybe Text)

-- | The HTTP status code that you want CloudFront to return to the viewer
--   along with the custom error page. There are a variety of reasons that
--   you might want CloudFront to return a status code different from the
--   status code that your origin returned to CloudFront, for example:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>Some Internet devices (some firewalls and corporate proxies, for
--   example) intercept HTTP 4xx and 5xx and prevent the response from
--   being returned to the viewer. If you substitute <tt>200</tt>, the
--   response typically won't be intercepted.</li>
--   <li>If you don't care about distinguishing among different client
--   errors or server errors, you can specify <tt>400</tt> or <tt>500</tt>
--   as the <tt>ResponseCode</tt> for all 4xx or 5xx errors.</li>
--   <li>You might want to return a <tt>200</tt> status code (OK) and
--   static website so your customers don't know that your website is
--   down.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If you specify a value for <tt>ResponseCode</tt>, you must also
--   specify a value for <tt>ResponsePagePath</tt>.
customErrorResponse_responseCode :: Lens' CustomErrorResponse (Maybe Text)

-- | The minimum amount of time, in seconds, that you want CloudFront to
--   cache the HTTP status code specified in <tt>ErrorCode</tt>. When this
--   time period has elapsed, CloudFront queries your origin to see whether
--   the problem that caused the error has been resolved and the requested
--   object is now available.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Customizing Error Responses</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
customErrorResponse_errorCachingMinTTL :: Lens' CustomErrorResponse (Maybe Integer)

-- | The HTTP status code for which you want to specify a custom error page
--   and/or a caching duration.
customErrorResponse_errorCode :: Lens' CustomErrorResponse Int
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponse.CustomErrorResponse
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponse.CustomErrorResponse
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponse.CustomErrorResponse
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponse.CustomErrorResponse
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponse.CustomErrorResponse
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponse.CustomErrorResponse
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponse.CustomErrorResponse
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponse.CustomErrorResponse


module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponses

-- | A complex type that controls:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>Whether CloudFront replaces HTTP status codes in the 4xx and 5xx
--   range with custom error messages before returning the response to the
--   viewer.</li>
--   <li>How long CloudFront caches HTTP status codes in the 4xx and 5xx
--   range.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For more information about custom error pages, see <a>Customizing
--   Error Responses</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newCustomErrorResponses</a> smart constructor.
data CustomErrorResponses
CustomErrorResponses' :: Maybe [CustomErrorResponse] -> Int -> CustomErrorResponses

-- | A complex type that contains a <tt>CustomErrorResponse</tt> element
--   for each HTTP status code for which you want to specify a custom error
--   page and/or a caching duration.
[$sel:items:CustomErrorResponses'] :: CustomErrorResponses -> Maybe [CustomErrorResponse]

-- | The number of HTTP status codes for which you want to specify a custom
--   error page and/or a caching duration. If <tt>Quantity</tt> is
--   <tt>0</tt>, you can omit <tt>Items</tt>.
[$sel:quantity:CustomErrorResponses'] :: CustomErrorResponses -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>CustomErrorResponses</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:CustomErrorResponses'</a>,
--   <a>customErrorResponses_items</a> - A complex type that contains a
--   <tt>CustomErrorResponse</tt> element for each HTTP status code for
--   which you want to specify a custom error page and/or a caching
--   duration.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:CustomErrorResponses'</a>,
--   <a>customErrorResponses_quantity</a> - The number of HTTP status codes
--   for which you want to specify a custom error page and/or a caching
--   duration. If <tt>Quantity</tt> is <tt>0</tt>, you can omit
--   <tt>Items</tt>.
newCustomErrorResponses :: Int -> CustomErrorResponses

-- | A complex type that contains a <tt>CustomErrorResponse</tt> element
--   for each HTTP status code for which you want to specify a custom error
--   page and/or a caching duration.
customErrorResponses_items :: Lens' CustomErrorResponses (Maybe [CustomErrorResponse])

-- | The number of HTTP status codes for which you want to specify a custom
--   error page and/or a caching duration. If <tt>Quantity</tt> is
--   <tt>0</tt>, you can omit <tt>Items</tt>.
customErrorResponses_quantity :: Lens' CustomErrorResponses Int
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponses.CustomErrorResponses
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponses.CustomErrorResponses
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponses.CustomErrorResponses
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponses.CustomErrorResponses
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponses.CustomErrorResponses
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponses.CustomErrorResponses
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponses.CustomErrorResponses
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CustomErrorResponses.CustomErrorResponses


module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.DistributionIdList

-- | A list of distribution IDs.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newDistributionIdList</a> smart constructor.
data DistributionIdList
DistributionIdList' :: Maybe [Text] -> Maybe Text -> Text -> Int -> Bool -> Int -> DistributionIdList

-- | Contains the distribution IDs in the list.
[$sel:items:DistributionIdList'] :: DistributionIdList -> Maybe [Text]

-- | Contains the value that you should use in the <tt>Marker</tt> field of
--   a subsequent request to continue listing distribution IDs where you
--   left off.
[$sel:nextMarker:DistributionIdList'] :: DistributionIdList -> Maybe Text

-- | The value provided in the <tt>Marker</tt> request field.
[$sel:marker:DistributionIdList'] :: DistributionIdList -> Text

-- | The maximum number of distribution IDs requested.
[$sel:maxItems:DistributionIdList'] :: DistributionIdList -> Int

-- | A flag that indicates whether more distribution IDs remain to be
--   listed. If your results were truncated, you can make a subsequent
--   request using the <tt>Marker</tt> request field to retrieve more
--   distribution IDs in the list.
[$sel:isTruncated:DistributionIdList'] :: DistributionIdList -> Bool

-- | The total number of distribution IDs returned in the response.
[$sel:quantity:DistributionIdList'] :: DistributionIdList -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>DistributionIdList</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:DistributionIdList'</a>, <a>distributionIdList_items</a>
--   - Contains the distribution IDs in the list.
--   
--   <a>$sel:nextMarker:DistributionIdList'</a>,
--   <a>distributionIdList_nextMarker</a> - Contains the value that you
--   should use in the <tt>Marker</tt> field of a subsequent request to
--   continue listing distribution IDs where you left off.
--   
--   <a>$sel:marker:DistributionIdList'</a>,
--   <a>distributionIdList_marker</a> - The value provided in the
--   <tt>Marker</tt> request field.
--   
--   <a>$sel:maxItems:DistributionIdList'</a>,
--   <a>distributionIdList_maxItems</a> - The maximum number of
--   distribution IDs requested.
--   
--   <a>$sel:isTruncated:DistributionIdList'</a>,
--   <a>distributionIdList_isTruncated</a> - A flag that indicates whether
--   more distribution IDs remain to be listed. If your results were
--   truncated, you can make a subsequent request using the <tt>Marker</tt>
--   request field to retrieve more distribution IDs in the list.

--   IDs returned in the response.
newDistributionIdList :: Text -> Int -> Bool -> Int -> DistributionIdList

distributionIdList_items :: Lens' DistributionIdList (Maybe [Text])

-- | Contains the value that you should use in the <tt>Marker</tt> field of
--   a subsequent request to continue listing distribution IDs where you
--   left off.
distributionIdList_nextMarker :: Lens' DistributionIdList (Maybe Text)

-- | The value provided in the <tt>Marker</tt> request field.
distributionIdList_marker :: Lens' DistributionIdList Text

-- | The maximum number of distribution IDs requested.
distributionIdList_maxItems :: Lens' DistributionIdList Int

-- | A flag that indicates whether more distribution IDs remain to be
--   listed. If your results were truncated, you can make a subsequent
--   request using the <tt>Marker</tt> request field to retrieve more

distributionIdList_isTruncated :: Lens' DistributionIdList Bool

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.EncryptionEntity

-- | Complex data type for field-level encryption profiles that includes
--   the encryption key and field pattern specifications.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newEncryptionEntity</a> smart constructor.
data EncryptionEntity
EncryptionEntity' :: Text -> Text -> FieldPatterns -> EncryptionEntity

-- | The public key associated with a set of field-level encryption
--   patterns, to be used when encrypting the fields that match the
--   patterns.
[$sel:publicKeyId:EncryptionEntity'] :: EncryptionEntity -> Text

-- | The provider associated with the public key being used for encryption.
--   This value must also be provided with the private key for applications
--   to be able to decrypt data.
[$sel:providerId:EncryptionEntity'] :: EncryptionEntity -> Text

-- | Field patterns in a field-level encryption content type profile
--   specify the fields that you want to be encrypted. You can provide the
--   full field name, or any beginning characters followed by a wildcard
--   (*). You can't overlap field patterns. For example, you can't have
--   both ABC* and AB*. Note that field patterns are case-sensitive.
[$sel:fieldPatterns:EncryptionEntity'] :: EncryptionEntity -> FieldPatterns

-- | Create a value of <a>EncryptionEntity</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:publicKeyId:EncryptionEntity'</a>,
--   <a>encryptionEntity_publicKeyId</a> - The public key associated with a
--   set of field-level encryption patterns, to be used when encrypting the
--   fields that match the patterns.
--   
--   <a>$sel:providerId:EncryptionEntity'</a>,
--   <a>encryptionEntity_providerId</a> - The provider associated with the
--   public key being used for encryption. This value must also be provided
--   with the private key for applications to be able to decrypt data.
--   
--   <a>$sel:fieldPatterns:EncryptionEntity'</a>,
--   <a>encryptionEntity_fieldPatterns</a> - Field patterns in a
--   field-level encryption content type profile specify the fields that
--   you want to be encrypted. You can provide the full field name, or any
--   beginning characters followed by a wildcard (*). You can't overlap
--   field patterns. For example, you can't have both ABC* and AB*. Note
--   that field patterns are case-sensitive.
newEncryptionEntity :: Text -> Text -> FieldPatterns -> EncryptionEntity

-- | The public key associated with a set of field-level encryption
--   patterns, to be used when encrypting the fields that match the
--   patterns.
encryptionEntity_publicKeyId :: Lens' EncryptionEntity Text

-- | The provider associated with the public key being used for encryption.
--   This value must also be provided with the private key for applications
--   to be able to decrypt data.
encryptionEntity_providerId :: Lens' EncryptionEntity Text

-- | Field patterns in a field-level encryption content type profile
--   specify the fields that you want to be encrypted. You can provide the
--   full field name, or any beginning characters followed by a wildcard
--   (*). You can't overlap field patterns. For example, you can't have
--   both ABC* and AB*. Note that field patterns are case-sensitive.
encryptionEntity_fieldPatterns :: Lens' EncryptionEntity FieldPatterns
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.EncryptionEntity.EncryptionEntity
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.EncryptionEntity.EncryptionEntity
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.EncryptionEntity.EncryptionEntity
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.EncryptionEntity.EncryptionEntity
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.EncryptionEntity.EncryptionEntity
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.EncryptionEntity.EncryptionEntity
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.EncryptionEntity.EncryptionEntity
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.EncryptionEntity.EncryptionEntity

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary

-- | The field-level encryption profile summary.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newFieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary</a> smart
--   constructor.
data FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary
FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary' :: Maybe Text -> Text -> ISO8601 -> Text -> EncryptionEntities -> FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary

-- | An optional comment for the field-level encryption profile summary.
--   The comment cannot be longer than 128 characters.
[$sel:comment:FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary'] :: FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary -> Maybe Text

-- | ID for the field-level encryption profile summary.
[$sel:id:FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary'] :: FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary -> Text

-- | The time when the the field-level encryption profile summary was last
--   updated.
[$sel:lastModifiedTime:FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary'] :: FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary -> ISO8601

-- | Name for the field-level encryption profile summary.
[$sel:name:FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary'] :: FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary -> Text

-- | A complex data type of encryption entities for the field-level
--   encryption profile that include the public key ID, provider, and field
--   patterns for specifying which fields to encrypt with this key.
[$sel:encryptionEntities:FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary'] :: FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary -> EncryptionEntities

-- | Create a value of <a>FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary</a> with all
--   optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:comment:FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary'</a>,
--   <a>fieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary_comment</a> - An optional
--   comment for the field-level encryption profile summary. The comment
--   cannot be longer than 128 characters.
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary'</a>,
--   <a>fieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary_id</a> - ID for the field-level
--   encryption profile summary.
--   
--   <a>$sel:lastModifiedTime:FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary'</a>,
--   <a>fieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary_lastModifiedTime</a> - The time
--   when the the field-level encryption profile summary was last updated.
--   
--   <a>$sel:name:FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary'</a>,
--   <a>fieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary_name</a> - Name for the
--   field-level encryption profile summary.
--

--   complex data type of encryption entities for the field-level
--   encryption profile that include the public key ID, provider, and field
--   patterns for specifying which fields to encrypt with this key.
newFieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary :: Text -> UTCTime -> Text -> EncryptionEntities -> FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary

--   The comment cannot be longer than 128 characters.
fieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary_comment :: Lens' FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary (Maybe Text)

fieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary_id :: Lens' FieldLevelEncryptionProfileSummary Text

--   updated.

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ContentTypeProfileConfig

-- | The configuration for a field-level encryption content type-profile
--   mapping.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newContentTypeProfileConfig</a> smart constructor.
data ContentTypeProfileConfig

-- | The configuration for a field-level encryption content type-profile.
[$sel:contentTypeProfiles:ContentTypeProfileConfig'] :: ContentTypeProfileConfig -> Maybe ContentTypeProfiles

-- | The setting in a field-level encryption content type-profile mapping
--   that specifies what to do when an unknown content type is provided for
--   the profile. If true, content is forwarded without being encrypted
--   when the content type is unknown. If false (the default), an error is
--   returned when the content type is unknown.
[$sel:forwardWhenContentTypeIsUnknown:ContentTypeProfileConfig'] :: ContentTypeProfileConfig -> Bool

-- | Create a value of <a>ContentTypeProfileConfig</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.

--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:contentTypeProfiles:ContentTypeProfileConfig'</a>,
--   <a>contentTypeProfileConfig_contentTypeProfiles</a> - The
--   configuration for a field-level encryption content type-profile.
--   
--   <a>$sel:forwardWhenContentTypeIsUnknown:ContentTypeProfileConfig'</a>,
--   <a>contentTypeProfileConfig_forwardWhenContentTypeIsUnknown</a> - The
--   setting in a field-level encryption content type-profile mapping that
--   specifies what to do when an unknown content type is provided for the
--   profile. If true, content is forwarded without being encrypted when
--   the content type is unknown. If false (the default), an error is
--   returned when the content type is unknown.
newContentTypeProfileConfig :: Bool -> ContentTypeProfileConfig

-- | The configuration for a field-level encryption content type-profile.
contentTypeProfileConfig_contentTypeProfiles :: Lens' ContentTypeProfileConfig (Maybe ContentTypeProfiles)

-- | The setting in a field-level encryption content type-profile mapping
--   that specifies what to do when an unknown content type is provided for
--   the profile. If true, content is forwarded without being encrypted
--   when the content type is unknown. If false (the default), an error is
--   returned when the content type is unknown.
contentTypeProfileConfig_forwardWhenContentTypeIsUnknown :: Lens' ContentTypeProfileConfig Bool

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociation

-- | A CloudFront function that is associated with a cache behavior in a
--   CloudFront distribution.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newFunctionAssociation</a> smart constructor.
data FunctionAssociation
FunctionAssociation' :: Text -> EventType -> FunctionAssociation

-- | The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the function.
[$sel:functionARN:FunctionAssociation'] :: FunctionAssociation -> Text

-- | The event type of the function, either <tt>viewer-request</tt> or
--   <tt>viewer-response</tt>. You cannot use origin-facing event types
--   (<tt>origin-request</tt> and <tt>origin-response</tt>) with a
--   CloudFront function.
[$sel:eventType:FunctionAssociation'] :: FunctionAssociation -> EventType

-- | Create a value of <a>FunctionAssociation</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:functionARN:FunctionAssociation'</a>,
--   <a>functionAssociation_functionARN</a> - The Amazon Resource Name
--   (ARN) of the function.
--   
--   <a>$sel:eventType:FunctionAssociation'</a>,
--   <a>functionAssociation_eventType</a> - The event type of the function,
--   either <tt>viewer-request</tt> or <tt>viewer-response</tt>. You cannot
--   use origin-facing event types (<tt>origin-request</tt> and
--   <tt>origin-response</tt>) with a CloudFront function.
newFunctionAssociation :: Text -> EventType -> FunctionAssociation

-- | The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the function.
functionAssociation_functionARN :: Lens' FunctionAssociation Text

-- | The event type of the function, either <tt>viewer-request</tt> or
--   <tt>viewer-response</tt>. You cannot use origin-facing event types
--   (<tt>origin-request</tt> and <tt>origin-response</tt>) with a
--   CloudFront function.
functionAssociation_eventType :: Lens' FunctionAssociation EventType
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociation.FunctionAssociation
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociation.FunctionAssociation
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociation.FunctionAssociation
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociation.FunctionAssociation
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociation.FunctionAssociation
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociation.FunctionAssociation

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociations

-- | A list of CloudFront functions that are associated with a cache
--   behavior in a CloudFront distribution. CloudFront functions must be
--   published to the <tt>LIVE</tt> stage to associate them with a cache
--   behavior.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newFunctionAssociations</a> smart constructor.
data FunctionAssociations
FunctionAssociations' :: Maybe [FunctionAssociation] -> Int -> FunctionAssociations

-- | The CloudFront functions that are associated with a cache behavior in
--   a CloudFront distribution. CloudFront functions must be published to
--   the <tt>LIVE</tt> stage to associate them with a cache behavior.
[$sel:items:FunctionAssociations'] :: FunctionAssociations -> Maybe [FunctionAssociation]

-- | The number of CloudFront functions in the list.
[$sel:quantity:FunctionAssociations'] :: FunctionAssociations -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>FunctionAssociations</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:FunctionAssociations'</a>,
--   <a>functionAssociations_items</a> - The CloudFront functions that are
--   associated with a cache behavior in a CloudFront distribution.
--   CloudFront functions must be published to the <tt>LIVE</tt> stage to
--   associate them with a cache behavior.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:FunctionAssociations'</a>,
--   <a>functionAssociations_quantity</a> - The number of CloudFront
--   functions in the list.
newFunctionAssociations :: Int -> FunctionAssociations

-- | The CloudFront functions that are associated with a cache behavior in
--   a CloudFront distribution. CloudFront functions must be published to
--   the <tt>LIVE</tt> stage to associate them with a cache behavior.
functionAssociations_items :: Lens' FunctionAssociations (Maybe [FunctionAssociation])

-- | The number of CloudFront functions in the list.
functionAssociations_quantity :: Lens' FunctionAssociations Int
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociations.FunctionAssociations
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociations.FunctionAssociations
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociations.FunctionAssociations
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociations.FunctionAssociations
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociations.FunctionAssociations
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociations.FunctionAssociations
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociations.FunctionAssociations
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionAssociations.FunctionAssociations

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionMetadata

-- | Contains metadata about a CloudFront function.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newFunctionMetadata</a> smart constructor.
data FunctionMetadata
FunctionMetadata' :: Maybe FunctionStage -> Maybe ISO8601 -> Text -> ISO8601 -> FunctionMetadata

-- | The stage that the function is in, either <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or
--   <tt>LIVE</tt>.
--   
--   When a function is in the <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> stage, you can test the
--   function with <tt>TestFunction</tt>, and update it with
--   <tt>UpdateFunction</tt>.
--   
--   When a function is in the <tt>LIVE</tt> stage, you can attach the
--   function to a distribution’s cache behavior, using the function’s ARN.
[$sel:stage:FunctionMetadata'] :: FunctionMetadata -> Maybe FunctionStage

-- | The date and time when the function was created.
[$sel:createdTime:FunctionMetadata'] :: FunctionMetadata -> Maybe ISO8601

-- | The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the function. The ARN uniquely
--   identifies the function.
[$sel:functionARN:FunctionMetadata'] :: FunctionMetadata -> Text

-- | The date and time when the function was most recently updated.
[$sel:lastModifiedTime:FunctionMetadata'] :: FunctionMetadata -> ISO8601

-- | Create a value of <a>FunctionMetadata</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:stage:FunctionMetadata'</a>, <a>functionMetadata_stage</a> -
--   The stage that the function is in, either <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or
--   <tt>LIVE</tt>.
--   
--   When a function is in the <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> stage, you can test the
--   function with <tt>TestFunction</tt>, and update it with
--   <tt>UpdateFunction</tt>.
--   
--   When a function is in the <tt>LIVE</tt> stage, you can attach the
--   function to a distribution’s cache behavior, using the function’s ARN.
--   
--   <a>$sel:createdTime:FunctionMetadata'</a>,
--   <a>functionMetadata_createdTime</a> - The date and time when the
--   function was created.
--   
--   <a>$sel:functionARN:FunctionMetadata'</a>,
--   <a>functionMetadata_functionARN</a> - The Amazon Resource Name (ARN)
--   of the function. The ARN uniquely identifies the function.
--   
--   <a>$sel:lastModifiedTime:FunctionMetadata'</a>,
--   <a>functionMetadata_lastModifiedTime</a> - The date and time when the
--   function was most recently updated.
newFunctionMetadata :: Text -> UTCTime -> FunctionMetadata

-- | The stage that the function is in, either <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or
--   <tt>LIVE</tt>.
--   
--   When a function is in the <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> stage, you can test the
--   function with <tt>TestFunction</tt>, and update it with
--   <tt>UpdateFunction</tt>.
--   
--   When a function is in the <tt>LIVE</tt> stage, you can attach the
--   function to a distribution’s cache behavior, using the function’s ARN.
functionMetadata_stage :: Lens' FunctionMetadata (Maybe FunctionStage)

-- | The date and time when the function was created.
functionMetadata_createdTime :: Lens' FunctionMetadata (Maybe UTCTime)

-- | The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the function. The ARN uniquely
--   identifies the function.
functionMetadata_functionARN :: Lens' FunctionMetadata Text

-- | The date and time when the function was most recently updated.
functionMetadata_lastModifiedTime :: Lens' FunctionMetadata UTCTime
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionMetadata.FunctionMetadata
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionMetadata.FunctionMetadata
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionMetadata.FunctionMetadata
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionMetadata.FunctionMetadata
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionMetadata.FunctionMetadata
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionMetadata.FunctionMetadata
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionMetadata.FunctionMetadata

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionList

-- | A list of CloudFront functions.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newFunctionList</a> smart constructor.
data FunctionList
FunctionList' :: Maybe [FunctionSummary] -> Maybe Text -> Int -> Int -> FunctionList

-- | Contains the functions in the list.
[$sel:items:FunctionList'] :: FunctionList -> Maybe [FunctionSummary]

-- | If there are more items in the list than are in this response, this
--   element is present. It contains the value that you should use in the
--   <tt>Marker</tt> field of a subsequent request to continue listing
--   functions where you left off.
[$sel:nextMarker:FunctionList'] :: FunctionList -> Maybe Text

-- | The maximum number of functions requested.
[$sel:maxItems:FunctionList'] :: FunctionList -> Int

-- | The number of functions returned in the response.
[$sel:quantity:FunctionList'] :: FunctionList -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>FunctionList</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:FunctionList'</a>, <a>functionList_items</a> - Contains
--   the functions in the list.
--   
--   <a>$sel:nextMarker:FunctionList'</a>, <a>functionList_nextMarker</a> -
--   If there are more items in the list than are in this response, this
--   element is present. It contains the value that you should use in the
--   <tt>Marker</tt> field of a subsequent request to continue listing
--   functions where you left off.
--   
--   <a>$sel:maxItems:FunctionList'</a>, <a>functionList_maxItems</a> - The
--   maximum number of functions requested.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:FunctionList'</a>, <a>functionList_quantity</a> - The
--   number of functions returned in the response.
newFunctionList :: Int -> Int -> FunctionList

-- | Contains the functions in the list.
functionList_items :: Lens' FunctionList (Maybe [FunctionSummary])

-- | If there are more items in the list than are in this response, this
--   element is present. It contains the value that you should use in the
--   <tt>Marker</tt> field of a subsequent request to continue listing
--   functions where you left off.
functionList_nextMarker :: Lens' FunctionList (Maybe Text)

-- | The maximum number of functions requested.
functionList_maxItems :: Lens' FunctionList Int

-- | The number of functions returned in the response.
functionList_quantity :: Lens' FunctionList Int
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionList.FunctionList
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FunctionList.FunctionList

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.GeoRestriction

-- | A complex type that controls the countries in which your content is
--   distributed. CloudFront determines the location of your users using
--   <tt>MaxMind</tt> GeoIP databases.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newGeoRestriction</a> smart constructor.
data GeoRestriction
GeoRestriction' :: Maybe [Text] -> GeoRestrictionType -> Int -> GeoRestriction

-- | A complex type that contains a <tt>Location</tt> element for each
--   country in which you want CloudFront either to distribute your content
--   (<tt>whitelist</tt>) or not distribute your content
--   (<tt>blacklist</tt>).
--   
--   The <tt>Location</tt> element is a two-letter, uppercase country code
--   for a country that you want to include in your <tt>blacklist</tt> or
--   <tt>whitelist</tt>. Include one <tt>Location</tt> element for each
--   country.
--   
--   CloudFront and <tt>MaxMind</tt> both use <tt>ISO 3166</tt> country
--   codes. For the current list of countries and the corresponding codes,
--   see <tt>ISO 3166-1-alpha-2</tt> code on the /International
--   Organization for Standardization/ website. You can also refer to the
--   country list on the CloudFront console, which includes both country
--   names and codes.
[$sel:items:GeoRestriction'] :: GeoRestriction -> Maybe [Text]

-- | The method that you want to use to restrict distribution of your
--   content by country:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt>: No geo restriction is enabled, meaning access to
--   content is not restricted by client geo location.</li>
--   <li><tt>blacklist</tt>: The <tt>Location</tt> elements specify the
--   countries in which you don't want CloudFront to distribute your
--   content.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt>: The <tt>Location</tt> elements specify the
--   countries in which you want CloudFront to distribute your
--   content.</li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:restrictionType:GeoRestriction'] :: GeoRestriction -> GeoRestrictionType

-- | When geo restriction is <tt>enabled</tt>, this is the number of
--   countries in your <tt>whitelist</tt> or <tt>blacklist</tt>. Otherwise,
--   when it is not enabled, <tt>Quantity</tt> is <tt>0</tt>, and you can
--   omit <tt>Items</tt>.
[$sel:quantity:GeoRestriction'] :: GeoRestriction -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>GeoRestriction</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:GeoRestriction'</a>, <a>geoRestriction_items</a> - A
--   complex type that contains a <tt>Location</tt> element for each
--   country in which you want CloudFront either to distribute your content
--   (<tt>whitelist</tt>) or not distribute your content
--   (<tt>blacklist</tt>).
--   
--   The <tt>Location</tt> element is a two-letter, uppercase country code
--   for a country that you want to include in your <tt>blacklist</tt> or
--   <tt>whitelist</tt>. Include one <tt>Location</tt> element for each
--   country.
--   
--   CloudFront and <tt>MaxMind</tt> both use <tt>ISO 3166</tt> country
--   codes. For the current list of countries and the corresponding codes,
--   see <tt>ISO 3166-1-alpha-2</tt> code on the /International
--   Organization for Standardization/ website. You can also refer to the
--   country list on the CloudFront console, which includes both country
--   names and codes.
--   
--   <a>$sel:restrictionType:GeoRestriction'</a>,
--   <a>geoRestriction_restrictionType</a> - The method that you want to
--   use to restrict distribution of your content by country:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt>: No geo restriction is enabled, meaning access to
--   content is not restricted by client geo location.</li>
--   <li><tt>blacklist</tt>: The <tt>Location</tt> elements specify the
--   countries in which you don't want CloudFront to distribute your
--   content.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt>: The <tt>Location</tt> elements specify the
--   countries in which you want CloudFront to distribute your
--   content.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:GeoRestriction'</a>, <a>geoRestriction_quantity</a> -
--   When geo restriction is <tt>enabled</tt>, this is the number of
--   countries in your <tt>whitelist</tt> or <tt>blacklist</tt>. Otherwise,
--   when it is not enabled, <tt>Quantity</tt> is <tt>0</tt>, and you can
--   omit <tt>Items</tt>.
newGeoRestriction :: GeoRestrictionType -> Int -> GeoRestriction

-- | A complex type that contains a <tt>Location</tt> element for each
--   country in which you want CloudFront either to distribute your content
--   (<tt>whitelist</tt>) or not distribute your content
--   (<tt>blacklist</tt>).
--   
--   The <tt>Location</tt> element is a two-letter, uppercase country code
--   for a country that you want to include in your <tt>blacklist</tt> or
--   <tt>whitelist</tt>. Include one <tt>Location</tt> element for each
--   country.
--   
--   CloudFront and <tt>MaxMind</tt> both use <tt>ISO 3166</tt> country
--   codes. For the current list of countries and the corresponding codes,
--   see <tt>ISO 3166-1-alpha-2</tt> code on the /International
--   Organization for Standardization/ website. You can also refer to the
--   country list on the CloudFront console, which includes both country
--   names and codes.
geoRestriction_items :: Lens' GeoRestriction (Maybe [Text])

-- | The method that you want to use to restrict distribution of your
--   content by country:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt>: No geo restriction is enabled, meaning access to
--   content is not restricted by client geo location.</li>
--   <li><tt>blacklist</tt>: The <tt>Location</tt> elements specify the
--   countries in which you don't want CloudFront to distribute your
--   content.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt>: The <tt>Location</tt> elements specify the
--   countries in which you want CloudFront to distribute your
--   content.</li>
--   </ul>
geoRestriction_restrictionType :: Lens' GeoRestriction GeoRestrictionType

-- | When geo restriction is <tt>enabled</tt>, this is the number of
--   countries in your <tt>whitelist</tt> or <tt>blacklist</tt>. Otherwise,
--   when it is not enabled, <tt>Quantity</tt> is <tt>0</tt>, and you can
--   omit <tt>Items</tt>.
geoRestriction_quantity :: Lens' GeoRestriction Int
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.GeoRestriction.GeoRestriction
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.GeoRestriction.GeoRestriction
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.GeoRestriction.GeoRestriction
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.GeoRestriction.GeoRestriction

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyHeadersConfig

-- | An object that determines whether any HTTP headers (and if so, which
--   headers) are included in the cache key and automatically included in
--   requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newCachePolicyHeadersConfig</a> smart constructor.
data CachePolicyHeadersConfig
CachePolicyHeadersConfig' :: Maybe Headers -> CachePolicyHeaderBehavior -> CachePolicyHeadersConfig
[$sel:headers:CachePolicyHeadersConfig'] :: CachePolicyHeadersConfig -> Maybe Headers

-- | Determines whether any HTTP headers are included in the cache key and
--   automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the
--   origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – HTTP headers are not included in the cache key and
--   are not automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to
--   the origin. Even when this field is set to <tt>none</tt>, any headers
--   that are listed in an <tt>OriginRequestPolicy</tt> <i>are</i> included
--   in origin requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The HTTP headers that are listed in the
--   <tt>Headers</tt> type are included in the cache key and are
--   automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the
--   origin.</li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:headerBehavior:CachePolicyHeadersConfig'] :: CachePolicyHeadersConfig -> CachePolicyHeaderBehavior

-- | Create a value of <a>CachePolicyHeadersConfig</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:headers:CachePolicyHeadersConfig'</a>,
--   <a>cachePolicyHeadersConfig_headers</a> - Undocumented member.
--   
--   <a>$sel:headerBehavior:CachePolicyHeadersConfig'</a>,
--   <a>cachePolicyHeadersConfig_headerBehavior</a> - Determines whether
--   any HTTP headers are included in the cache key and automatically
--   included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin. Valid values
--   are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – HTTP headers are not included in the cache key and
--   are not automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to
--   the origin. Even when this field is set to <tt>none</tt>, any headers
--   that are listed in an <tt>OriginRequestPolicy</tt> <i>are</i> included
--   in origin requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The HTTP headers that are listed in the
--   <tt>Headers</tt> type are included in the cache key and are
--   automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the
--   origin.</li>
--   </ul>
newCachePolicyHeadersConfig :: CachePolicyHeaderBehavior -> CachePolicyHeadersConfig

-- | Undocumented member.
cachePolicyHeadersConfig_headers :: Lens' CachePolicyHeadersConfig (Maybe Headers)

-- | Determines whether any HTTP headers are included in the cache key and
--   automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the
--   origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – HTTP headers are not included in the cache key and
--   are not automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to
--   the origin. Even when this field is set to <tt>none</tt>, any headers
--   that are listed in an <tt>OriginRequestPolicy</tt> <i>are</i> included
--   in origin requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The HTTP headers that are listed in the
--   <tt>Headers</tt> type are included in the cache key and are
--   automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to the
--   origin.</li>
--   </ul>
cachePolicyHeadersConfig_headerBehavior :: Lens' CachePolicyHeadersConfig CachePolicyHeaderBehavior
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyHeadersConfig.CachePolicyHeadersConfig
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyHeadersConfig.CachePolicyHeadersConfig
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyHeadersConfig.CachePolicyHeadersConfig
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyHeadersConfig.CachePolicyHeadersConfig
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyHeadersConfig.CachePolicyHeadersConfig
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyHeadersConfig.CachePolicyHeadersConfig
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyHeadersConfig.CachePolicyHeadersConfig
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachePolicyHeadersConfig.CachePolicyHeadersConfig

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AliasICPRecordal

-- | Amazon Web Services services in China customers must file for an
--   Internet Content Provider (ICP) recordal if they want to serve content
--   publicly on an alternate domain name, also known as a CNAME, that
--   they've added to CloudFront. AliasICPRecordal provides the ICP
--   recordal status for CNAMEs associated with distributions. The status
--   is returned in the CloudFront response; you can't configure it
--   yourself.
--   
--   For more information about ICP recordals, see <a>Signup, Accounts, and
--   Credentials</a> in <i>Getting Started with Amazon Web Services
--   services in China</i>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newAliasICPRecordal</a> smart constructor.
data AliasICPRecordal
AliasICPRecordal' :: Maybe Text -> Maybe ICPRecordalStatus -> AliasICPRecordal

-- | A domain name associated with a distribution.
[$sel:cname:AliasICPRecordal'] :: AliasICPRecordal -> Maybe Text

-- | The Internet Content Provider (ICP) recordal status for a CNAME. The
--   ICPRecordalStatus is set to APPROVED for all CNAMEs (aliases) in
--   regions outside of China.
--   
--   The status values returned are the following:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><b>APPROVED</b> indicates that the associated CNAME has a valid
--   ICP recordal number. Multiple CNAMEs can be associated with a
--   distribution, and CNAMEs can correspond to different ICP recordals. To
--   be marked as APPROVED, that is, valid to use with China region, a
--   CNAME must have one ICP recordal number associated with it.</li>
--   <li><b>SUSPENDED</b> indicates that the associated CNAME does not have
--   a valid ICP recordal number.</li>
--   <li><b>PENDING</b> indicates that CloudFront can't determine the ICP
--   recordal status of the CNAME associated with the distribution because
--   there was an error in trying to determine the status. You can try
--   again to see if the error is resolved in which case CloudFront returns
--   an APPROVED or SUSPENDED status.</li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:iCPRecordalStatus:AliasICPRecordal'] :: AliasICPRecordal -> Maybe ICPRecordalStatus

-- | Create a value of <a>AliasICPRecordal</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:cname:AliasICPRecordal'</a>, <a>aliasICPRecordal_cname</a> - A
--   domain name associated with a distribution.
--   
--   <a>$sel:iCPRecordalStatus:AliasICPRecordal'</a>,
--   <a>aliasICPRecordal_iCPRecordalStatus</a> - The Internet Content
--   Provider (ICP) recordal status for a CNAME. The ICPRecordalStatus is
--   set to APPROVED for all CNAMEs (aliases) in regions outside of China.
--   
--   The status values returned are the following:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><b>APPROVED</b> indicates that the associated CNAME has a valid
--   ICP recordal number. Multiple CNAMEs can be associated with a
--   distribution, and CNAMEs can correspond to different ICP recordals. To
--   be marked as APPROVED, that is, valid to use with China region, a
--   CNAME must have one ICP recordal number associated with it.</li>
--   <li><b>SUSPENDED</b> indicates that the associated CNAME does not have
--   a valid ICP recordal number.</li>
--   <li><b>PENDING</b> indicates that CloudFront can't determine the ICP
--   recordal status of the CNAME associated with the distribution because
--   there was an error in trying to determine the status. You can try
--   again to see if the error is resolved in which case CloudFront returns
--   an APPROVED or SUSPENDED status.</li>
--   </ul>
newAliasICPRecordal :: AliasICPRecordal

-- | A domain name associated with a distribution.
aliasICPRecordal_cname :: Lens' AliasICPRecordal (Maybe Text)

-- | The Internet Content Provider (ICP) recordal status for a CNAME. The
--   ICPRecordalStatus is set to APPROVED for all CNAMEs (aliases) in
--   regions outside of China.
--   
--   The status values returned are the following:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><b>APPROVED</b> indicates that the associated CNAME has a valid
--   ICP recordal number. Multiple CNAMEs can be associated with a
--   distribution, and CNAMEs can correspond to different ICP recordals. To
--   be marked as APPROVED, that is, valid to use with China region, a
--   CNAME must have one ICP recordal number associated with it.</li>
--   <li><b>SUSPENDED</b> indicates that the associated CNAME does not have
--   a valid ICP recordal number.</li>
--   <li><b>PENDING</b> indicates that CloudFront can't determine the ICP
--   recordal status of the CNAME associated with the distribution because
--   there was an error in trying to determine the status. You can try
--   again to see if the error is resolved in which case CloudFront returns
--   an APPROVED or SUSPENDED status.</li>
--   </ul>
aliasICPRecordal_iCPRecordalStatus :: Lens' AliasICPRecordal (Maybe ICPRecordalStatus)
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AliasICPRecordal.AliasICPRecordal
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AliasICPRecordal.AliasICPRecordal
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AliasICPRecordal.AliasICPRecordal
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AliasICPRecordal.AliasICPRecordal
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AliasICPRecordal.AliasICPRecordal
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AliasICPRecordal.AliasICPRecordal
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AliasICPRecordal.AliasICPRecordal


module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationSummary

-- | A summary of an invalidation request.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newInvalidationSummary</a> smart constructor.
data InvalidationSummary
InvalidationSummary' :: Text -> ISO8601 -> Text -> InvalidationSummary

-- | The unique ID for an invalidation request.
[$sel:id:InvalidationSummary'] :: InvalidationSummary -> Text

-- | The time that an invalidation request was created.
[$sel:createTime:InvalidationSummary'] :: InvalidationSummary -> ISO8601

-- | The status of an invalidation request.
[$sel:status:InvalidationSummary'] :: InvalidationSummary -> Text

-- | Create a value of <a>InvalidationSummary</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--

--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:InvalidationSummary'</a>, <a>invalidationSummary_id</a> -
--   The unique ID for an invalidation request.
--   
--   <a>$sel:createTime:InvalidationSummary'</a>,
--   <a>invalidationSummary_createTime</a> - The time that an invalidation
--   request was created.
--   
--   <a>$sel:status:InvalidationSummary'</a>,
--   <a>invalidationSummary_status</a> - The status of an invalidation
--   request.
newInvalidationSummary :: Text -> UTCTime -> Text -> InvalidationSummary

-- | The unique ID for an invalidation request.
invalidationSummary_id :: Lens' InvalidationSummary Text

-- | The time that an invalidation request was created.
invalidationSummary_createTime :: Lens' InvalidationSummary UTCTime

-- | The status of an invalidation request.
invalidationSummary_status :: Lens' InvalidationSummary Text

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationList

-- | The <tt>InvalidationList</tt> complex type describes the list of
--   invalidation objects. For more information about invalidation, see
--   <a>Invalidating Objects (Web Distributions Only)</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newInvalidationList</a> smart constructor.
data InvalidationList
InvalidationList' :: Maybe [InvalidationSummary] -> Maybe Text -> Text -> Int -> Bool -> Int -> InvalidationList

-- | A complex type that contains one <tt>InvalidationSummary</tt> element
--   for each invalidation batch created by the current account.
[$sel:items:InvalidationList'] :: InvalidationList -> Maybe [InvalidationSummary]

-- | If <tt>IsTruncated</tt> is <tt>true</tt>, this element is present and
--   contains the value that you can use for the <tt>Marker</tt> request
--   parameter to continue listing your invalidation batches where they
--   left off.
[$sel:nextMarker:InvalidationList'] :: InvalidationList -> Maybe Text

-- | The value that you provided for the <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter.
[$sel:marker:InvalidationList'] :: InvalidationList -> Text

-- | The value that you provided for the <tt>MaxItems</tt> request
--   parameter.
[$sel:maxItems:InvalidationList'] :: InvalidationList -> Int

-- | A flag that indicates whether more invalidation batch requests remain
--   to be listed. If your results were truncated, you can make a follow-up
--   pagination request using the <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter to
--   retrieve more invalidation batches in the list.
[$sel:isTruncated:InvalidationList'] :: InvalidationList -> Bool

-- | The number of invalidation batches that were created by the current
--   account.
[$sel:quantity:InvalidationList'] :: InvalidationList -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>InvalidationList</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:InvalidationList'</a>, <a>invalidationList_items</a> - A
--   complex type that contains one <tt>InvalidationSummary</tt> element
--   for each invalidation batch created by the current account.
--   
--   <a>$sel:nextMarker:InvalidationList'</a>,
--   <a>invalidationList_nextMarker</a> - If <tt>IsTruncated</tt> is
--   <tt>true</tt>, this element is present and contains the value that you
--   can use for the <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter to continue listing
--   your invalidation batches where they left off.
--   
--   <a>$sel:marker:InvalidationList'</a>, <a>invalidationList_marker</a> -
--   The value that you provided for the <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter.
--   
--   <a>$sel:maxItems:InvalidationList'</a>,
--   <a>invalidationList_maxItems</a> - The value that you provided for the
--   <tt>MaxItems</tt> request parameter.
--   
--   <a>$sel:isTruncated:InvalidationList'</a>,
--   <a>invalidationList_isTruncated</a> - A flag that indicates whether
--   more invalidation batch requests remain to be listed. If your results
--   were truncated, you can make a follow-up pagination request using the
--   <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter to retrieve more invalidation
--   batches in the list.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:InvalidationList'</a>,
--   <a>invalidationList_quantity</a> - The number of invalidation batches
--   that were created by the current account.
newInvalidationList :: Text -> Int -> Bool -> Int -> InvalidationList

-- | A complex type that contains one <tt>InvalidationSummary</tt> element
--   for each invalidation batch created by the current account.
invalidationList_items :: Lens' InvalidationList (Maybe [InvalidationSummary])

-- | If <tt>IsTruncated</tt> is <tt>true</tt>, this element is present and
--   contains the value that you can use for the <tt>Marker</tt> request
--   parameter to continue listing your invalidation batches where they
--   left off.
invalidationList_nextMarker :: Lens' InvalidationList (Maybe Text)

-- | The value that you provided for the <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter.
invalidationList_marker :: Lens' InvalidationList Text

-- | The value that you provided for the <tt>MaxItems</tt> request
--   parameter.
invalidationList_maxItems :: Lens' InvalidationList Int

-- | A flag that indicates whether more invalidation batch requests remain
--   to be listed. If your results were truncated, you can make a follow-up
--   pagination request using the <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter to
--   retrieve more invalidation batches in the list.
invalidationList_isTruncated :: Lens' InvalidationList Bool

-- | The number of invalidation batches that were created by the current
--   account.
invalidationList_quantity :: Lens' InvalidationList Int
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationList.InvalidationList
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationList.InvalidationList
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationList.InvalidationList
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationList.InvalidationList
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationList.InvalidationList
