module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CookiePreference

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy or
--   an origin request policy instead of this field.
--   
--   If you want to include cookies in the cache key, use
--   <tt>CookiesConfig</tt> in a cache policy. See <tt>CachePolicy</tt>.
--   
--   If you want to send cookies to the origin but not include them in the
--   cache key, use <tt>CookiesConfig</tt> in an origin request policy. See
--   <tt>OriginRequestPolicy</tt>.
--   
--   A complex type that specifies whether you want CloudFront to forward
--   cookies to the origin and, if so, which ones. For more information
--   about forwarding cookies to the origin, see <a>Caching Content Based
--   on Cookies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newCookiePreference</a> smart constructor.
data CookiePreference
CookiePreference' :: Maybe CookieNames -> ItemSelection -> CookiePreference

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy or
--   an origin request policy instead of this field.
--   
--   If you want to include cookies in the cache key, use a cache policy.
--   For more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to send cookies to the origin but not include them in the
--   cache key, use an origin request policy. For more information, see
--   <a>Creating origin request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   Required if you specify <tt>whitelist</tt> for the value of
--   <tt>Forward</tt>. A complex type that specifies how many different
--   cookies you want CloudFront to forward to the origin for this cache
--   behavior and, if you want to forward selected cookies, the names of
--   those cookies.
--   
--   If you specify <tt>all</tt> or <tt>none</tt> for the value of
--   <tt>Forward</tt>, omit <tt>WhitelistedNames</tt>. If you change the
--   value of <tt>Forward</tt> from <tt>whitelist</tt> to <tt>all</tt> or
--   <tt>none</tt> and you don't delete the <tt>WhitelistedNames</tt>
--   element and its child elements, CloudFront deletes them automatically.
--   
--   For the current limit on the number of cookie names that you can
--   whitelist for each cache behavior, see <a>CloudFront Limits</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon Web Services General Reference</i>.
[$sel:whitelistedNames:CookiePreference'] :: CookiePreference -> Maybe CookieNames

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy or
--   an origin request policy instead of this field.
--   
--   If you want to include cookies in the cache key, use a cache policy.
--   For more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to send cookies to the origin but not include them in the
--   cache key, use origin request policy. For more information, see
--   <a>Creating origin request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   Specifies which cookies to forward to the origin for this cache
--   behavior: all, none, or the list of cookies specified in the
--   <tt>WhitelistedNames</tt> complex type.
--   
--   Amazon S3 doesn't process cookies. When the cache behavior is
--   forwarding requests to an Amazon S3 origin, specify none for the
--   <tt>Forward</tt> element.
[$sel:forward:CookiePreference'] :: CookiePreference -> ItemSelection

-- | Create a value of <a>CookiePreference</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:whitelistedNames:CookiePreference'</a>,
--   <a>cookiePreference_whitelistedNames</a> - This field is deprecated.
--   We recommend that you use a cache policy or an origin request policy
--   instead of this field.
--   
--   If you want to include cookies in the cache key, use a cache policy.
--   For more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to send cookies to the origin but not include them in the
--   cache key, use an origin request policy. For more information, see
--   <a>Creating origin request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   Required if you specify <tt>whitelist</tt> for the value of
--   <tt>Forward</tt>. A complex type that specifies how many different
--   cookies you want CloudFront to forward to the origin for this cache
--   behavior and, if you want to forward selected cookies, the names of
--   those cookies.
--   
--   If you specify <tt>all</tt> or <tt>none</tt> for the value of
--   <tt>Forward</tt>, omit <tt>WhitelistedNames</tt>. If you change the
--   value of <tt>Forward</tt> from <tt>whitelist</tt> to <tt>all</tt> or
--   <tt>none</tt> and you don't delete the <tt>WhitelistedNames</tt>
--   element and its child elements, CloudFront deletes them automatically.
--   
--   For the current limit on the number of cookie names that you can
--   whitelist for each cache behavior, see <a>CloudFront Limits</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon Web Services General Reference</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:forward:CookiePreference'</a>, <a>cookiePreference_forward</a>
--   - This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy
--   or an origin request policy instead of this field.
--   
--   If you want to include cookies in the cache key, use a cache policy.
--   For more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to send cookies to the origin but not include them in the
--   cache key, use origin request policy. For more information, see
--   <a>Creating origin request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   Specifies which cookies to forward to the origin for this cache
--   behavior: all, none, or the list of cookies specified in the
--   <tt>WhitelistedNames</tt> complex type.
--   
--   Amazon S3 doesn't process cookies. When the cache behavior is
--   forwarding requests to an Amazon S3 origin, specify none for the
--   <tt>Forward</tt> element.
newCookiePreference :: ItemSelection -> CookiePreference

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy or
--   an origin request policy instead of this field.
--   
--   If you want to include cookies in the cache key, use a cache policy.
--   For more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to send cookies to the origin but not include them in the
--   cache key, use an origin request policy. For more information, see
--   <a>Creating origin request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   Required if you specify <tt>whitelist</tt> for the value of
--   <tt>Forward</tt>. A complex type that specifies how many different
--   cookies you want CloudFront to forward to the origin for this cache
--   behavior and, if you want to forward selected cookies, the names of
--   those cookies.
--   
--   If you specify <tt>all</tt> or <tt>none</tt> for the value of
--   <tt>Forward</tt>, omit <tt>WhitelistedNames</tt>. If you change the
--   value of <tt>Forward</tt> from <tt>whitelist</tt> to <tt>all</tt> or
--   <tt>none</tt> and you don't delete the <tt>WhitelistedNames</tt>
--   element and its child elements, CloudFront deletes them automatically.
--   
--   For the current limit on the number of cookie names that you can
--   whitelist for each cache behavior, see <a>CloudFront Limits</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon Web Services General Reference</i>.
cookiePreference_whitelistedNames :: Lens' CookiePreference (Maybe CookieNames)

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy or
--   an origin request policy instead of this field.
--

--   If you want to send cookies to the origin but not include them in the
--   cache key, use origin request policy. For more information, see
--   <a>Creating origin request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   Specifies which cookies to forward to the origin for this cache
--   behavior: all, none, or the list of cookies specified in the
--   <tt>WhitelistedNames</tt> complex type.
--   
--   Amazon S3 doesn't process cookies. When the cache behavior is
--   forwarding requests to an Amazon S3 origin, specify none for the
--   <tt>Forward</tt> element.
cookiePreference_forward :: Lens' CookiePreference ItemSelection

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.KeyGroupConfig

-- | A key group configuration.
--   
--   A key group contains a list of public keys that you can use with
--   <a>CloudFront signed URLs and signed cookies</a>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newKeyGroupConfig</a> smart constructor.
data KeyGroupConfig
KeyGroupConfig' :: Maybe Text -> Text -> [Text] -> KeyGroupConfig

-- | A comment to describe the key group. The comment cannot be longer than
--   128 characters.
[$sel:comment:KeyGroupConfig'] :: KeyGroupConfig -> Maybe Text

-- | A name to identify the key group.
[$sel:name:KeyGroupConfig'] :: KeyGroupConfig -> Text

-- | A list of the identifiers of the public keys in the key group.
[$sel:items:KeyGroupConfig'] :: KeyGroupConfig -> [Text]

-- | Create a value of <a>KeyGroupConfig</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:comment:KeyGroupConfig'</a>, <a>keyGroupConfig_comment</a> - A
--   comment to describe the key group. The comment cannot be longer than
--   128 characters.
--   
--   <a>$sel:name:KeyGroupConfig'</a>, <a>keyGroupConfig_name</a> - A name
--   to identify the key group.
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:KeyGroupConfig'</a>, <a>keyGroupConfig_items</a> - A
--   list of the identifiers of the public keys in the key group.
newKeyGroupConfig :: Text -> KeyGroupConfig

-- | A comment to describe the key group. The comment cannot be longer than
--   128 characters.
keyGroupConfig_comment :: Lens' KeyGroupConfig (Maybe Text)

-- | A name to identify the key group.
keyGroupConfig_name :: Lens' KeyGroupConfig Text

-- | A list of the identifiers of the public keys in the key group.
keyGroupConfig_items :: Lens' KeyGroupConfig [Text]

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ActiveTrustedKeyGroups

-- | A list of key groups, and the public keys in each key group, that
--   CloudFront can use to verify the signatures of signed URLs and signed
--   cookies.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newActiveTrustedKeyGroups</a> smart constructor.
data ActiveTrustedKeyGroups
ActiveTrustedKeyGroups' :: Maybe [KGKeyPairIds] -> Bool -> Int -> ActiveTrustedKeyGroups

-- | A list of key groups, including the identifiers of the public keys in
--   each key group that CloudFront can use to verify the signatures of
--   signed URLs and signed cookies.
[$sel:items:ActiveTrustedKeyGroups'] :: ActiveTrustedKeyGroups -> Maybe [KGKeyPairIds]

-- | This field is <tt>true</tt> if any of the key groups have public keys
--   that CloudFront can use to verify the signatures of signed URLs and
--   signed cookies. If not, this field is <tt>false</tt>.
[$sel:enabled:ActiveTrustedKeyGroups'] :: ActiveTrustedKeyGroups -> Bool

-- | The number of key groups in the list.
[$sel:quantity:ActiveTrustedKeyGroups'] :: ActiveTrustedKeyGroups -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>ActiveTrustedKeyGroups</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:ActiveTrustedKeyGroups'</a>,
--   <a>activeTrustedKeyGroups_items</a> - A list of key groups, including
--   the identifiers of the public keys in each key group that CloudFront
--   can use to verify the signatures of signed URLs and signed cookies.
--   
--   <a>$sel:enabled:ActiveTrustedKeyGroups'</a>,
--   <a>activeTrustedKeyGroups_enabled</a> - This field is <tt>true</tt> if
--   any of the key groups have public keys that CloudFront can use to
--   verify the signatures of signed URLs and signed cookies. If not, this
--   field is <tt>false</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:ActiveTrustedKeyGroups'</a>,
--   <a>activeTrustedKeyGroups_quantity</a> - The number of key groups in
--   the list.
newActiveTrustedKeyGroups :: Bool -> Int -> ActiveTrustedKeyGroups

-- | A list of key groups, including the identifiers of the public keys in
--   each key group that CloudFront can use to verify the signatures of
--   signed URLs and signed cookies.
activeTrustedKeyGroups_items :: Lens' ActiveTrustedKeyGroups (Maybe [KGKeyPairIds])

-- | This field is <tt>true</tt> if any of the key groups have public keys
--   that CloudFront can use to verify the signatures of signed URLs and
--   signed cookies. If not, this field is <tt>false</tt>.
activeTrustedKeyGroups_enabled :: Lens' ActiveTrustedKeyGroups Bool

-- | The number of key groups in the list.
activeTrustedKeyGroups_quantity :: Lens' ActiveTrustedKeyGroups Int
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ActiveTrustedKeyGroups.ActiveTrustedKeyGroups
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ActiveTrustedKeyGroups.ActiveTrustedKeyGroups

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociation

-- | A complex type that contains a Lambda@Edge function association.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newLambdaFunctionAssociation</a> smart constructor.
data LambdaFunctionAssociation
LambdaFunctionAssociation' :: Maybe Bool -> Text -> EventType -> LambdaFunctionAssociation

-- | A flag that allows a Lambda@Edge function to have read access to the
--   body content. For more information, see <a>Accessing the Request Body
--   by Choosing the Include Body Option</a> in the Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide.
[$sel:includeBody:LambdaFunctionAssociation'] :: LambdaFunctionAssociation -> Maybe Bool

-- | The ARN of the Lambda@Edge function. You must specify the ARN of a
--   function version; you can't specify an alias or $LATEST.
[$sel:lambdaFunctionARN:LambdaFunctionAssociation'] :: LambdaFunctionAssociation -> Text

-- | Specifies the event type that triggers a Lambda@Edge function
--   invocation. You can specify the following values:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>viewer-request</tt>: The function executes when CloudFront
--   receives a request from a viewer and before it checks to see whether
--   the requested object is in the edge cache.</li>
--   <li><tt>origin-request</tt>: The function executes only when
--   CloudFront sends a request to your origin. When the requested object
--   is in the edge cache, the function doesn't execute.</li>
--   <li><tt>origin-response</tt>: The function executes after CloudFront
--   receives a response from the origin and before it caches the object in
--   the response. When the requested object is in the edge cache, the
--   function doesn't execute.</li>
--   <li><tt>viewer-response</tt>: The function executes before CloudFront
--   returns the requested object to the viewer. The function executes
--   regardless of whether the object was already in the edge cache.If the
--   origin returns an HTTP status code other than HTTP 200 (OK), the
--   function doesn't execute.</li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:eventType:LambdaFunctionAssociation'] :: LambdaFunctionAssociation -> EventType

-- | Create a value of <a>LambdaFunctionAssociation</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:includeBody:LambdaFunctionAssociation'</a>,
--   <a>lambdaFunctionAssociation_includeBody</a> - A flag that allows a
--   Lambda@Edge function to have read access to the body content. For more
--   information, see <a>Accessing the Request Body by Choosing the Include
--   Body Option</a> in the Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide.
--   
--   <a>$sel:lambdaFunctionARN:LambdaFunctionAssociation'</a>,
--   <a>lambdaFunctionAssociation_lambdaFunctionARN</a> - The ARN of the
--   Lambda@Edge function. You must specify the ARN of a function version;
--   you can't specify an alias or $LATEST.
--   
--   <a>$sel:eventType:LambdaFunctionAssociation'</a>,
--   <a>lambdaFunctionAssociation_eventType</a> - Specifies the event type
--   that triggers a Lambda@Edge function invocation. You can specify the
--   following values:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>viewer-request</tt>: The function executes when CloudFront
--   receives a request from a viewer and before it checks to see whether
--   the requested object is in the edge cache.</li>
--   <li><tt>origin-request</tt>: The function executes only when
--   CloudFront sends a request to your origin. When the requested object
--   is in the edge cache, the function doesn't execute.</li>
--   <li><tt>origin-response</tt>: The function executes after CloudFront
--   receives a response from the origin and before it caches the object in
--   the response. When the requested object is in the edge cache, the
--   function doesn't execute.</li>
--   <li><tt>viewer-response</tt>: The function executes before CloudFront
--   returns the requested object to the viewer. The function executes
--   regardless of whether the object was already in the edge cache.If the
--   origin returns an HTTP status code other than HTTP 200 (OK), the
--   function doesn't execute.</li>
--   </ul>
newLambdaFunctionAssociation :: Text -> EventType -> LambdaFunctionAssociation

-- | A flag that allows a Lambda@Edge function to have read access to the
--   body content. For more information, see <a>Accessing the Request Body
--   by Choosing the Include Body Option</a> in the Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide.
lambdaFunctionAssociation_includeBody :: Lens' LambdaFunctionAssociation (Maybe Bool)

-- | The ARN of the Lambda@Edge function. You must specify the ARN of a
--   function version; you can't specify an alias or $LATEST.
lambdaFunctionAssociation_lambdaFunctionARN :: Lens' LambdaFunctionAssociation Text

-- | Specifies the event type that triggers a Lambda@Edge function
--   invocation. You can specify the following values:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>viewer-request</tt>: The function executes when CloudFront
--   receives a request from a viewer and before it checks to see whether
--   the requested object is in the edge cache.</li>
--   <li><tt>origin-request</tt>: The function executes only when
--   CloudFront sends a request to your origin. When the requested object
--   is in the edge cache, the function doesn't execute.</li>
--   <li><tt>origin-response</tt>: The function executes after CloudFront
--   receives a response from the origin and before it caches the object in
--   the response. When the requested object is in the edge cache, the
--   function doesn't execute.</li>
--   <li><tt>viewer-response</tt>: The function executes before CloudFront
--   returns the requested object to the viewer. The function executes
--   regardless of whether the object was already in the edge cache.If the
--   origin returns an HTTP status code other than HTTP 200 (OK), the
--   function doesn't execute.</li>
--   </ul>
lambdaFunctionAssociation_eventType :: Lens' LambdaFunctionAssociation EventType
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociation.LambdaFunctionAssociation
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociation.LambdaFunctionAssociation
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociation.LambdaFunctionAssociation
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociation.LambdaFunctionAssociation
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociation.LambdaFunctionAssociation
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociation.LambdaFunctionAssociation
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociation.LambdaFunctionAssociation
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociation.LambdaFunctionAssociation


module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociations

-- | A complex type that specifies a list of Lambda@Edge functions
--   associations for a cache behavior.
--   
--   If you want to invoke one or more Lambda@Edge functions triggered by
--   requests that match the <tt>PathPattern</tt> of the cache behavior,
--   specify the applicable values for <tt>Quantity</tt> and
--   <tt>Items</tt>. Note that there can be up to 4
--   <tt>LambdaFunctionAssociation</tt> items in this list (one for each
--   possible value of <tt>EventType</tt>) and each <tt>EventType</tt> can
--   be associated with only one function.
--   
--   If you don't want to invoke any Lambda@Edge functions for the requests
--   that match <tt>PathPattern</tt>, specify <tt>0</tt> for
--   <tt>Quantity</tt> and omit <tt>Items</tt>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newLambdaFunctionAssociations</a> smart constructor.
data LambdaFunctionAssociations
LambdaFunctionAssociations' :: Maybe [LambdaFunctionAssociation] -> Int -> LambdaFunctionAssociations

-- | <b>Optional</b>: A complex type that contains
--   <tt>LambdaFunctionAssociation</tt> items for this cache behavior. If
--   <tt>Quantity</tt> is <tt>0</tt>, you can omit <tt>Items</tt>.
[$sel:items:LambdaFunctionAssociations'] :: LambdaFunctionAssociations -> Maybe [LambdaFunctionAssociation]

-- | The number of Lambda@Edge function associations for this cache
--   behavior.
[$sel:quantity:LambdaFunctionAssociations'] :: LambdaFunctionAssociations -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>LambdaFunctionAssociations</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:LambdaFunctionAssociations'</a>,
--   <a>lambdaFunctionAssociations_items</a> - <b>Optional</b>: A complex
--   type that contains <tt>LambdaFunctionAssociation</tt> items for this
--   cache behavior. If <tt>Quantity</tt> is <tt>0</tt>, you can omit
--   <tt>Items</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:LambdaFunctionAssociations'</a>,
--   <a>lambdaFunctionAssociations_quantity</a> - The number of Lambda@Edge
--   function associations for this cache behavior.
newLambdaFunctionAssociations :: Int -> LambdaFunctionAssociations

-- | <b>Optional</b>: A complex type that contains
--   <tt>LambdaFunctionAssociation</tt> items for this cache behavior. If
--   <tt>Quantity</tt> is <tt>0</tt>, you can omit <tt>Items</tt>.
lambdaFunctionAssociations_items :: Lens' LambdaFunctionAssociations (Maybe [LambdaFunctionAssociation])

-- | The number of Lambda@Edge function associations for this cache
--   behavior.
lambdaFunctionAssociations_quantity :: Lens' LambdaFunctionAssociations Int
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociations.LambdaFunctionAssociations
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociations.LambdaFunctionAssociations
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociations.LambdaFunctionAssociations
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociations.LambdaFunctionAssociations
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociations.LambdaFunctionAssociations
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociations.LambdaFunctionAssociations
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociations.LambdaFunctionAssociations
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LambdaFunctionAssociations.LambdaFunctionAssociations


module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LoggingConfig

-- | A complex type that controls whether access logs are written for the
--   distribution.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newLoggingConfig</a> smart constructor.
data LoggingConfig
LoggingConfig' :: Bool -> Bool -> Text -> Text -> LoggingConfig

-- | Specifies whether you want CloudFront to save access logs to an Amazon
--   S3 bucket. If you don't want to enable logging when you create a
--   distribution or if you want to disable logging for an existing
--   distribution, specify <tt>false</tt> for <tt>Enabled</tt>, and specify
--   empty <tt>Bucket</tt> and <tt>Prefix</tt> elements. If you specify
--   <tt>false</tt> for <tt>Enabled</tt> but you specify values for
--   <tt>Bucket</tt>, <tt>prefix</tt>, and <tt>IncludeCookies</tt>, the
--   values are automatically deleted.
[$sel:enabled:LoggingConfig'] :: LoggingConfig -> Bool

-- | Specifies whether you want CloudFront to include cookies in access
--   logs, specify <tt>true</tt> for <tt>IncludeCookies</tt>. If you choose
--   to include cookies in logs, CloudFront logs all cookies regardless of
--   how you configure the cache behaviors for this distribution. If you
--   don't want to include cookies when you create a distribution or if you
--   want to disable include cookies for an existing distribution, specify
--   <tt>false</tt> for <tt>IncludeCookies</tt>.
[$sel:includeCookies:LoggingConfig'] :: LoggingConfig -> Bool

-- | The Amazon S3 bucket to store the access logs in, for example,
--   <tt>myawslogbucket.s3.amazonaws.com</tt>.
[$sel:bucket:LoggingConfig'] :: LoggingConfig -> Text

-- | An optional string that you want CloudFront to prefix to the access
--   log <tt>filenames</tt> for this distribution, for example,
--   <tt>myprefix/</tt>. If you want to enable logging, but you don't want
--   to specify a prefix, you still must include an empty <tt>Prefix</tt>
--   element in the <tt>Logging</tt> element.
[$sel:prefix:LoggingConfig'] :: LoggingConfig -> Text

-- | Create a value of <a>LoggingConfig</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:enabled:LoggingConfig'</a>, <a>loggingConfig_enabled</a> -
--   Specifies whether you want CloudFront to save access logs to an Amazon
--   S3 bucket. If you don't want to enable logging when you create a
--   distribution or if you want to disable logging for an existing
--   distribution, specify <tt>false</tt> for <tt>Enabled</tt>, and specify
--   empty <tt>Bucket</tt> and <tt>Prefix</tt> elements. If you specify
--   <tt>false</tt> for <tt>Enabled</tt> but you specify values for
--   <tt>Bucket</tt>, <tt>prefix</tt>, and <tt>IncludeCookies</tt>, the
--   values are automatically deleted.
--   
--   <a>$sel:includeCookies:LoggingConfig'</a>,
--   <a>loggingConfig_includeCookies</a> - Specifies whether you want
--   CloudFront to include cookies in access logs, specify <tt>true</tt>
--   for <tt>IncludeCookies</tt>. If you choose to include cookies in logs,
--   CloudFront logs all cookies regardless of how you configure the cache
--   behaviors for this distribution. If you don't want to include cookies
--   when you create a distribution or if you want to disable include
--   cookies for an existing distribution, specify <tt>false</tt> for
--   <tt>IncludeCookies</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:bucket:LoggingConfig'</a>, <a>loggingConfig_bucket</a> - The
--   Amazon S3 bucket to store the access logs in, for example,
--   <tt>myawslogbucket.s3.amazonaws.com</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:prefix:LoggingConfig'</a>, <a>loggingConfig_prefix</a> - An
--   optional string that you want CloudFront to prefix to the access log
--   <tt>filenames</tt> for this distribution, for example,
--   <tt>myprefix/</tt>. If you want to enable logging, but you don't want
--   to specify a prefix, you still must include an empty <tt>Prefix</tt>
--   element in the <tt>Logging</tt> element.
newLoggingConfig :: Bool -> Bool -> Text -> Text -> LoggingConfig

-- | Specifies whether you want CloudFront to save access logs to an Amazon
--   S3 bucket. If you don't want to enable logging when you create a
--   distribution or if you want to disable logging for an existing
--   distribution, specify <tt>false</tt> for <tt>Enabled</tt>, and specify
--   empty <tt>Bucket</tt> and <tt>Prefix</tt> elements. If you specify
--   <tt>false</tt> for <tt>Enabled</tt> but you specify values for
--   <tt>Bucket</tt>, <tt>prefix</tt>, and <tt>IncludeCookies</tt>, the
--   values are automatically deleted.
loggingConfig_enabled :: Lens' LoggingConfig Bool

-- | Specifies whether you want CloudFront to include cookies in access
--   logs, specify <tt>true</tt> for <tt>IncludeCookies</tt>. If you choose
--   to include cookies in logs, CloudFront logs all cookies regardless of
--   how you configure the cache behaviors for this distribution. If you
--   don't want to include cookies when you create a distribution or if you
--   want to disable include cookies for an existing distribution, specify
--   <tt>false</tt> for <tt>IncludeCookies</tt>.
loggingConfig_includeCookies :: Lens' LoggingConfig Bool

-- | The Amazon S3 bucket to store the access logs in, for example,
--   <tt>myawslogbucket.s3.amazonaws.com</tt>.
loggingConfig_bucket :: Lens' LoggingConfig Text

-- | An optional string that you want CloudFront to prefix to the access
--   log <tt>filenames</tt> for this distribution, for example,
--   <tt>myprefix/</tt>. If you want to enable logging, but you don't want
--   to specify a prefix, you still must include an empty <tt>Prefix</tt>
--   element in the <tt>Logging</tt> element.
loggingConfig_prefix :: Lens' LoggingConfig Text
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LoggingConfig.LoggingConfig
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LoggingConfig.LoggingConfig
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LoggingConfig.LoggingConfig
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LoggingConfig.LoggingConfig
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LoggingConfig.LoggingConfig
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LoggingConfig.LoggingConfig
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LoggingConfig.LoggingConfig
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.LoggingConfig.LoggingConfig

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachedMethods

-- | A complex type that controls whether CloudFront caches the response to
--   requests using the specified HTTP methods. There are two choices:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>CloudFront caches responses to <tt>GET</tt> and <tt>HEAD</tt>
--   requests.</li>
--   <li>CloudFront caches responses to <tt>GET</tt>, <tt>HEAD</tt>, and
--   <tt>OPTIONS</tt> requests.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If you pick the second choice for your Amazon S3 Origin, you may need
--   to forward Access-Control-Request-Method,
--   Access-Control-Request-Headers, and Origin headers for the responses
--   to be cached correctly.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newCachedMethods</a> smart constructor.
data CachedMethods
CachedMethods' :: Int -> [Method] -> CachedMethods

-- | The number of HTTP methods for which you want CloudFront to cache
--   responses. Valid values are <tt>2</tt> (for caching responses to
--   <tt>GET</tt> and <tt>HEAD</tt> requests) and <tt>3</tt> (for caching
--   responses to <tt>GET</tt>, <tt>HEAD</tt>, and <tt>OPTIONS</tt>
--   requests).
[$sel:quantity:CachedMethods'] :: CachedMethods -> Int

-- | A complex type that contains the HTTP methods that you want CloudFront
--   to cache responses to.
[$sel:items:CachedMethods'] :: CachedMethods -> [Method]

-- | Create a value of <a>CachedMethods</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:CachedMethods'</a>, <a>cachedMethods_quantity</a> -
--   The number of HTTP methods for which you want CloudFront to cache
--   responses. Valid values are <tt>2</tt> (for caching responses to
--   <tt>GET</tt> and <tt>HEAD</tt> requests) and <tt>3</tt> (for caching
--   responses to <tt>GET</tt>, <tt>HEAD</tt>, and <tt>OPTIONS</tt>
--   requests).
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:CachedMethods'</a>, <a>cachedMethods_items</a> - A
--   complex type that contains the HTTP methods that you want CloudFront
--   to cache responses to.
newCachedMethods :: Int -> CachedMethods

-- | The number of HTTP methods for which you want CloudFront to cache
--   responses. Valid values are <tt>2</tt> (for caching responses to
--   <tt>GET</tt> and <tt>HEAD</tt> requests) and <tt>3</tt> (for caching
--   responses to <tt>GET</tt>, <tt>HEAD</tt>, and <tt>OPTIONS</tt>
--   requests).
cachedMethods_quantity :: Lens' CachedMethods Int

-- | A complex type that contains the HTTP methods that you want CloudFront
--   to cache responses to.
cachedMethods_items :: Lens' CachedMethods [Method]
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachedMethods.CachedMethods
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachedMethods.CachedMethods
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachedMethods.CachedMethods
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachedMethods.CachedMethods
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachedMethods.CachedMethods
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachedMethods.CachedMethods
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachedMethods.CachedMethods
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.CachedMethods.CachedMethods


module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AllowedMethods

-- | A complex type that controls which HTTP methods CloudFront processes
--   and forwards to your Amazon S3 bucket or your custom origin. There are
--   three choices:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>CloudFront forwards only <tt>GET</tt> and <tt>HEAD</tt>
--   requests.</li>
--   <li>CloudFront forwards only <tt>GET</tt>, <tt>HEAD</tt>, and
--   <tt>OPTIONS</tt> requests.</li>
--   <li>CloudFront forwards <tt>GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, PUT, PATCH, POST</tt>,
--   and <tt>DELETE</tt> requests.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If you pick the third choice, you may need to restrict access to your
--   Amazon S3 bucket or to your custom origin so users can't perform
--   operations that you don't want them to. For example, you might not
--   want users to have permissions to delete objects from your origin.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newAllowedMethods</a> smart constructor.
data AllowedMethods
AllowedMethods' :: Maybe CachedMethods -> Int -> [Method] -> AllowedMethods
[$sel:cachedMethods:AllowedMethods'] :: AllowedMethods -> Maybe CachedMethods

-- | The number of HTTP methods that you want CloudFront to forward to your
--   origin. Valid values are 2 (for <tt>GET</tt> and <tt>HEAD</tt>
--   requests), 3 (for <tt>GET</tt>, <tt>HEAD</tt>, and <tt>OPTIONS</tt>
--   requests) and 7 (for <tt>GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, PUT, PATCH, POST</tt>,
--   and <tt>DELETE</tt> requests).
[$sel:quantity:AllowedMethods'] :: AllowedMethods -> Int

-- | A complex type that contains the HTTP methods that you want CloudFront
--   to process and forward to your origin.
[$sel:items:AllowedMethods'] :: AllowedMethods -> [Method]

-- | Create a value of <a>AllowedMethods</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:cachedMethods:AllowedMethods'</a>,
--   <a>allowedMethods_cachedMethods</a> - Undocumented member.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:AllowedMethods'</a>, <a>allowedMethods_quantity</a> -
--   The number of HTTP methods that you want CloudFront to forward to your
--   origin. Valid values are 2 (for <tt>GET</tt> and <tt>HEAD</tt>
--   requests), 3 (for <tt>GET</tt>, <tt>HEAD</tt>, and <tt>OPTIONS</tt>
--   requests) and 7 (for <tt>GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, PUT, PATCH, POST</tt>,
--   and <tt>DELETE</tt> requests).
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:AllowedMethods'</a>, <a>allowedMethods_items</a> - A
--   complex type that contains the HTTP methods that you want CloudFront
--   to process and forward to your origin.
newAllowedMethods :: Int -> AllowedMethods

-- | Undocumented member.
allowedMethods_cachedMethods :: Lens' AllowedMethods (Maybe CachedMethods)

-- | The number of HTTP methods that you want CloudFront to forward to your
--   origin. Valid values are 2 (for <tt>GET</tt> and <tt>HEAD</tt>
--   requests), 3 (for <tt>GET</tt>, <tt>HEAD</tt>, and <tt>OPTIONS</tt>
--   requests) and 7 (for <tt>GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, PUT, PATCH, POST</tt>,
--   and <tt>DELETE</tt> requests).
allowedMethods_quantity :: Lens' AllowedMethods Int

-- | A complex type that contains the HTTP methods that you want CloudFront
--   to process and forward to your origin.
allowedMethods_items :: Lens' AllowedMethods [Method]
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AllowedMethods.AllowedMethods
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AllowedMethods.AllowedMethods
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AllowedMethods.AllowedMethods
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AllowedMethods.AllowedMethods
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AllowedMethods.AllowedMethods
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AllowedMethods.AllowedMethods
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AllowedMethods.AllowedMethods
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.AllowedMethods.AllowedMethods

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig

-- | An object that determines whether any cookies in viewer requests (and
--   if so, which cookies) are included in requests that CloudFront sends
--   to the origin.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newOriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig</a> smart
--   constructor.
data OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig
OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig' :: Maybe CookieNames -> OriginRequestPolicyCookieBehavior -> OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig
[$sel:cookies:OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig'] :: OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig -> Maybe CookieNames

-- | Determines whether cookies in viewer requests are included in requests
--   that CloudFront sends to the origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – Cookies in viewer requests are not included in
--   requests that CloudFront sends to the origin. Even when this field is
--   set to <tt>none</tt>, any cookies that are listed in a
--   <tt>CachePolicy</tt> <i>are</i> included in origin requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The cookies in viewer requests that are
--   listed in the <tt>CookieNames</tt> type are included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>all</tt> – All cookies in viewer requests are included in
--   requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:cookieBehavior:OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig'] :: OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig -> OriginRequestPolicyCookieBehavior

-- | Create a value of <a>OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig</a> with all
--   optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:cookies:OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyCookiesConfig_cookies</a> - Undocumented member.
--   
--   <a>$sel:cookieBehavior:OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyCookiesConfig_cookieBehavior</a> - Determines
--   whether cookies in viewer requests are included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – Cookies in viewer requests are not included in
--   requests that CloudFront sends to the origin. Even when this field is
--   set to <tt>none</tt>, any cookies that are listed in a
--   <tt>CachePolicy</tt> <i>are</i> included in origin requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The cookies in viewer requests that are
--   listed in the <tt>CookieNames</tt> type are included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>all</tt> – All cookies in viewer requests are included in
--   requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   </ul>
newOriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig :: OriginRequestPolicyCookieBehavior -> OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig

-- | Undocumented member.
originRequestPolicyCookiesConfig_cookies :: Lens' OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig (Maybe CookieNames)

-- | Determines whether cookies in viewer requests are included in requests
--   that CloudFront sends to the origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – Cookies in viewer requests are not included in
--   requests that CloudFront sends to the origin. Even when this field is
--   set to <tt>none</tt>, any cookies that are listed in a
--   <tt>CachePolicy</tt> <i>are</i> included in origin requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The cookies in viewer requests that are
--   listed in the <tt>CookieNames</tt> type are included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>all</tt> – All cookies in viewer requests are included in
--   requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   </ul>
originRequestPolicyCookiesConfig_cookieBehavior :: Lens' OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig OriginRequestPolicyCookieBehavior
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig.OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig.OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig.OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig.OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig

-- | An object that determines whether any HTTP headers (and if so, which
--   headers) are included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newOriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig</a> smart
--   constructor.
data OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig
OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig' :: Maybe Headers -> OriginRequestPolicyHeaderBehavior -> OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig
[$sel:headers:OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig'] :: OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig -> Maybe Headers

-- | Determines whether any HTTP headers are included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – HTTP headers are not included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin. Even when this field is set to
--   <tt>none</tt>, any headers that are listed in a <tt>CachePolicy</tt>
--   <i>are</i> included in origin requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The HTTP headers that are listed in the
--   <tt>Headers</tt> type are included in requests that CloudFront sends
--   to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>allViewer</tt> – All HTTP headers in viewer requests are
--   included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>allViewerAndWhitelistCloudFront</tt> – All HTTP headers in
--   viewer requests and the additional CloudFront headers that are listed
--   in the <tt>Headers</tt> type are included in requests that CloudFront
--   sends to the origin. The additional headers are added by
--   CloudFront.</li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:headerBehavior:OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig'] :: OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig -> OriginRequestPolicyHeaderBehavior

-- | Create a value of <a>OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig</a> with all
--   optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:headers:OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyHeadersConfig_headers</a> - Undocumented member.
--   
--   <a>$sel:headerBehavior:OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyHeadersConfig_headerBehavior</a> - Determines
--   whether any HTTP headers are included in requests that CloudFront
--   sends to the origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – HTTP headers are not included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin. Even when this field is set to
--   <tt>none</tt>, any headers that are listed in a <tt>CachePolicy</tt>
--   <i>are</i> included in origin requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The HTTP headers that are listed in the
--   <tt>Headers</tt> type are included in requests that CloudFront sends
--   to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>allViewer</tt> – All HTTP headers in viewer requests are
--   included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>allViewerAndWhitelistCloudFront</tt> – All HTTP headers in
--   viewer requests and the additional CloudFront headers that are listed
--   in the <tt>Headers</tt> type are included in requests that CloudFront
--   sends to the origin. The additional headers are added by
--   CloudFront.</li>
--   </ul>
newOriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig :: OriginRequestPolicyHeaderBehavior -> OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig

-- | Undocumented member.
originRequestPolicyHeadersConfig_headers :: Lens' OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig (Maybe Headers)

-- | Determines whether any HTTP headers are included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – HTTP headers are not included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin. Even when this field is set to
--   <tt>none</tt>, any headers that are listed in a <tt>CachePolicy</tt>
--   <i>are</i> included in origin requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The HTTP headers that are listed in the
--   <tt>Headers</tt> type are included in requests that CloudFront sends
--   to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>allViewer</tt> – All HTTP headers in viewer requests are
--   included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>allViewerAndWhitelistCloudFront</tt> – All HTTP headers in
--   viewer requests and the additional CloudFront headers that are listed
--   in the <tt>Headers</tt> type are included in requests that CloudFront
--   sends to the origin. The additional headers are added by
--   CloudFront.</li>
--   </ul>
originRequestPolicyHeadersConfig_headerBehavior :: Lens' OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig OriginRequestPolicyHeaderBehavior
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig.OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig.OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginShield

-- | CloudFront Origin Shield.
--   
--   Using Origin Shield can help reduce the load on your origin. For more
--   information, see <a>Using Origin Shield</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newOriginShield</a> smart constructor.
data OriginShield
OriginShield' :: Maybe Text -> Bool -> OriginShield

-- | The Region for Origin Shield.
--   
--   Specify the Region that has the lowest latency to your origin. To
--   specify a region, use the region code, not the region name. For
--   example, specify the US East (Ohio) region as <tt>us-east-2</tt>.
--   
--   When you enable CloudFront Origin Shield, you must specify the Region
--   for Origin Shield. For the list of Regions that you can specify, and
--   for help choosing the best Region for your origin, see <a>Choosing the
--   Region for Origin Shield</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
[$sel:originShieldRegion:OriginShield'] :: OriginShield -> Maybe Text

-- | A flag that specifies whether Origin Shield is enabled.
--   
--   When it’s enabled, CloudFront routes all requests through Origin
--   Shield, which can help protect your origin. When it’s disabled,
--   CloudFront might send requests directly to your origin from multiple
--   edge locations or regional edge caches.
[$sel:enabled:OriginShield'] :: OriginShield -> Bool

-- | Create a value of <a>OriginShield</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:originShieldRegion:OriginShield'</a>,
--   <a>originShield_originShieldRegion</a> - The Region for Origin Shield.
--   
--   Specify the Region that has the lowest latency to your origin. To
--   specify a region, use the region code, not the region name. For
--   example, specify the US East (Ohio) region as <tt>us-east-2</tt>.
--   
--   When you enable CloudFront Origin Shield, you must specify the Region
--   for Origin Shield. For the list of Regions that you can specify, and
--   for help choosing the best Region for your origin, see <a>Choosing the
--   Region for Origin Shield</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:enabled:OriginShield'</a>, <a>originShield_enabled</a> - A
--   flag that specifies whether Origin Shield is enabled.
--   
--   When it’s enabled, CloudFront routes all requests through Origin
--   Shield, which can help protect your origin. When it’s disabled,
--   CloudFront might send requests directly to your origin from multiple
--   edge locations or regional edge caches.
newOriginShield :: Bool -> OriginShield

-- | The Region for Origin Shield.
--   
--   Specify the Region that has the lowest latency to your origin. To
--   specify a region, use the region code, not the region name. For
--   example, specify the US East (Ohio) region as <tt>us-east-2</tt>.
--   
--   When you enable CloudFront Origin Shield, you must specify the Region
--   for Origin Shield. For the list of Regions that you can specify, and
--   for help choosing the best Region for your origin, see <a>Choosing the
--   Region for Origin Shield</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
originShield_originShieldRegion :: Lens' OriginShield (Maybe Text)

-- | A flag that specifies whether Origin Shield is enabled.
--   
--   When it’s enabled, CloudFront routes all requests through Origin
--   Shield, which can help protect your origin. When it’s disabled,
--   CloudFront might send requests directly to your origin from multiple
--   edge locations or regional edge caches.
originShield_enabled :: Lens' OriginShield Bool
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginShield.OriginShield
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginShield.OriginShield
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginShield.OriginShield
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.OriginShield.OriginShield

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationBatch

-- | An invalidation batch.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newInvalidationBatch</a> smart constructor.
data InvalidationBatch
InvalidationBatch' :: Paths -> Text -> InvalidationBatch

-- | A complex type that contains information about the objects that you
--   want to invalidate. For more information, see <a>Specifying the
--   Objects to Invalidate</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
[$sel:paths:InvalidationBatch'] :: InvalidationBatch -> Paths

-- | A value that you specify to uniquely identify an invalidation request.
--   CloudFront uses the value to prevent you from accidentally
--   resubmitting an identical request. Whenever you create a new
--   invalidation request, you must specify a new value for
--   <tt>CallerReference</tt> and change other values in the request as
--   applicable. One way to ensure that the value of
--   <tt>CallerReference</tt> is unique is to use a <tt>timestamp</tt>, for
--   example, <tt>20120301090000</tt>.
--   
--   If you make a second invalidation request with the same value for
--   <tt>CallerReference</tt>, and if the rest of the request is the same,
--   CloudFront doesn't create a new invalidation request. Instead,
--   CloudFront returns information about the invalidation request that you
--   previously created with the same <tt>CallerReference</tt>.
--   
--   If <tt>CallerReference</tt> is a value you already sent in a previous
--   invalidation batch request but the content of any <tt>Path</tt> is
--   different from the original request, CloudFront returns an
--   <tt>InvalidationBatchAlreadyExists</tt> error.
[$sel:callerReference:InvalidationBatch'] :: InvalidationBatch -> Text

-- | Create a value of <a>InvalidationBatch</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:paths:InvalidationBatch'</a>, <a>invalidationBatch_paths</a> -
--   A complex type that contains information about the objects that you
--   want to invalidate. For more information, see <a>Specifying the
--   Objects to Invalidate</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:callerReference:InvalidationBatch'</a>,
--   <a>invalidationBatch_callerReference</a> - A value that you specify to
--   uniquely identify an invalidation request. CloudFront uses the value
--   to prevent you from accidentally resubmitting an identical request.
--   Whenever you create a new invalidation request, you must specify a new
--   value for <tt>CallerReference</tt> and change other values in the
--   request as applicable. One way to ensure that the value of
--   <tt>CallerReference</tt> is unique is to use a <tt>timestamp</tt>, for
--   example, <tt>20120301090000</tt>.
--   
--   If you make a second invalidation request with the same value for
--   <tt>CallerReference</tt>, and if the rest of the request is the same,
--   CloudFront doesn't create a new invalidation request. Instead,
--   CloudFront returns information about the invalidation request that you
--   previously created with the same <tt>CallerReference</tt>.
--   
--   If <tt>CallerReference</tt> is a value you already sent in a previous
--   invalidation batch request but the content of any <tt>Path</tt> is
--   different from the original request, CloudFront returns an
--   <tt>InvalidationBatchAlreadyExists</tt> error.
newInvalidationBatch :: Paths -> Text -> InvalidationBatch

-- | A complex type that contains information about the objects that you
--   want to invalidate. For more information, see <a>Specifying the
--   Objects to Invalidate</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
invalidationBatch_paths :: Lens' InvalidationBatch Paths

-- | A value that you specify to uniquely identify an invalidation request.
--   CloudFront uses the value to prevent you from accidentally
--   resubmitting an identical request. Whenever you create a new
--   invalidation request, you must specify a new value for
--   <tt>CallerReference</tt> and change other values in the request as
--   applicable. One way to ensure that the value of
--   <tt>CallerReference</tt> is unique is to use a <tt>timestamp</tt>, for
--   example, <tt>20120301090000</tt>.
--   
--   If you make a second invalidation request with the same value for
--   <tt>CallerReference</tt>, and if the rest of the request is the same,
--   CloudFront doesn't create a new invalidation request. Instead,
--   CloudFront returns information about the invalidation request that you
--   previously created with the same <tt>CallerReference</tt>.
--   
--   If <tt>CallerReference</tt> is a value you already sent in a previous
--   invalidation batch request but the content of any <tt>Path</tt> is
--   different from the original request, CloudFront returns an
--   <tt>InvalidationBatchAlreadyExists</tt> error.
invalidationBatch_callerReference :: Lens' InvalidationBatch Text
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationBatch.InvalidationBatch
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationBatch.InvalidationBatch
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationBatch.InvalidationBatch
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationBatch.InvalidationBatch
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationBatch.InvalidationBatch
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationBatch.InvalidationBatch

instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.InvalidationBatch.InvalidationBatch


module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.Invalidation

-- | An invalidation.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newInvalidation</a> smart constructor.
data Invalidation
Invalidation' :: Text -> Text -> ISO8601 -> InvalidationBatch -> Invalidation

-- | The identifier for the invalidation request. For example:
--   <tt>IDFDVBD632BHDS5</tt>.
[$sel:id:Invalidation'] :: Invalidation -> Text

-- | The status of the invalidation request. When the invalidation batch is
--   finished, the status is <tt>Completed</tt>.
[$sel:status:Invalidation'] :: Invalidation -> Text

-- | The date and time the invalidation request was first made.
[$sel:createTime:Invalidation'] :: Invalidation -> ISO8601

-- | The current invalidation information for the batch request.
[$sel:invalidationBatch:Invalidation'] :: Invalidation -> InvalidationBatch

-- | Create a value of <a>Invalidation</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:Invalidation'</a>, <a>invalidation_id</a> - The identifier
--   for the invalidation request. For example: <tt>IDFDVBD632BHDS5</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:status:Invalidation'</a>, <a>invalidation_status</a> - The
--   status of the invalidation request. When the invalidation batch is
--   finished, the status is <tt>Completed</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:createTime:Invalidation'</a>, <a>invalidation_createTime</a> -
--   The date and time the invalidation request was first made.
--   
--   <a>$sel:invalidationBatch:Invalidation'</a>,
--   <a>invalidation_invalidationBatch</a> - The current invalidation
--   information for the batch request.
newInvalidation :: Text -> Text -> UTCTime -> InvalidationBatch -> Invalidation

-- | The identifier for the invalidation request. For example:
--   <tt>IDFDVBD632BHDS5</tt>.
invalidation_id :: Lens' Invalidation Text

-- | The status of the invalidation request. When the invalidation batch is
--   finished, the status is <tt>Completed</tt>.
invalidation_status :: Lens' Invalidation Text

-- | The date and time the invalidation request was first made.
invalidation_createTime :: Lens' Invalidation UTCTime

-- | The current invalidation information for the batch request.
invalidation_invalidationBatch :: Lens' Invalidation InvalidationBatch
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.Invalidation.Invalidation
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.Invalidation.Invalidation
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.Invalidation.Invalidation
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.Invalidation.Invalidation
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.Invalidation.Invalidation
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.Invalidation.Invalidation
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.Invalidation.Invalidation

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.PublicKeyConfig

-- | Configuration information about a public key that you can use with
--   <a>signed URLs and signed cookies</a>, or with <a>field-level
--   encryption</a>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newPublicKeyConfig</a> smart constructor.
data PublicKeyConfig
PublicKeyConfig' :: Maybe Text -> Text -> Text -> Text -> PublicKeyConfig

-- | A comment to describe the public key. The comment cannot be longer
--   than 128 characters.
[$sel:comment:PublicKeyConfig'] :: PublicKeyConfig -> Maybe Text

-- | A string included in the request to help make sure that the request
--   can’t be replayed.
[$sel:callerReference:PublicKeyConfig'] :: PublicKeyConfig -> Text

-- | A name to help identify the public key.
[$sel:name:PublicKeyConfig'] :: PublicKeyConfig -> Text

-- | The public key that you can use with <a>signed URLs and signed
--   cookies</a>, or with <a>field-level encryption</a>.
[$sel:encodedKey:PublicKeyConfig'] :: PublicKeyConfig -> Text

-- | Create a value of <a>PublicKeyConfig</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:comment:PublicKeyConfig'</a>, <a>publicKeyConfig_comment</a> -
--   A comment to describe the public key. The comment cannot be longer
--   than 128 characters.
--   
--   <a>$sel:callerReference:PublicKeyConfig'</a>,
--   <a>publicKeyConfig_callerReference</a> - A string included in the
--   request to help make sure that the request can’t be replayed.
--   
--   <a>$sel:name:PublicKeyConfig'</a>, <a>publicKeyConfig_name</a> - A
--   name to help identify the public key.
--   
--   <a>$sel:encodedKey:PublicKeyConfig'</a>,
--   <a>publicKeyConfig_encodedKey</a> - The public key that you can use
--   with <a>signed URLs and signed cookies</a>, or with <a>field-level
--   encryption</a>.
newPublicKeyConfig :: Text -> Text -> Text -> PublicKeyConfig

-- | A comment to describe the public key. The comment cannot be longer
--   than 128 characters.
publicKeyConfig_comment :: Lens' PublicKeyConfig (Maybe Text)

-- | A string included in the request to help make sure that the request
--   can’t be replayed.
publicKeyConfig_callerReference :: Lens' PublicKeyConfig Text

-- | A name to help identify the public key.
publicKeyConfig_name :: Lens' PublicKeyConfig Text

-- | The public key that you can use with <a>signed URLs and signed
--   cookies</a>, or with <a>field-level encryption</a>.
publicKeyConfig_encodedKey :: Lens' PublicKeyConfig Text
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.PublicKeyConfig.PublicKeyConfig
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.PublicKeyConfig.PublicKeyConfig
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.PublicKeyConfig.PublicKeyConfig
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.PublicKeyConfig.PublicKeyConfig
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.PublicKeyConfig.PublicKeyConfig
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.PublicKeyConfig.PublicKeyConfig
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.PublicKeyConfig.PublicKeyConfig

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.PublicKey

--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newPublicKey</a> smart constructor.

[$sel:createdTime:PublicKey'] :: PublicKey -> ISO8601

--   <a>signed URLs and signed cookies</a>, or with <a>field-level
--   encryption</a>.

--   public key.

--   date and time when the public key was uploaded.
--   
--   <a>$sel:publicKeyConfig:PublicKey'</a>,
--   <a>publicKey_publicKeyConfig</a> - Configuration information about a
--   public key that you can use with <a>signed URLs and signed
--   cookies</a>, or with <a>field-level encryption</a>.
newPublicKey :: Text -> UTCTime -> PublicKeyConfig -> PublicKey

-- | The identifier of the public key.
publicKey_id :: Lens' PublicKey Text

-- | The date and time when the public key was uploaded.

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.PublicKeyList

--   cookies</a>, or with <a>field-level encryption</a>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newPublicKeyList</a> smart constructor.
data PublicKeyList
PublicKeyList' :: Maybe [PublicKeySummary] -> Maybe Text -> Int -> Int -> PublicKeyList

-- | A list of public keys.
[$sel:items:PublicKeyList'] :: PublicKeyList -> Maybe [PublicKeySummary]

-- | If there are more elements to be listed, this element is present and
--   contains the value that you can use for the <tt>Marker</tt> request
--   parameter to continue listing your public keys where you left off.
[$sel:nextMarker:PublicKeyList'] :: PublicKeyList -> Maybe Text

-- | The maximum number of public keys you want in the response.
[$sel:maxItems:PublicKeyList'] :: PublicKeyList -> Int

-- | The number of public keys in the list.
[$sel:quantity:PublicKeyList'] :: PublicKeyList -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>PublicKeyList</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:PublicKeyList'</a>, <a>publicKeyList_items</a> - A list
--   of public keys.
--   
--   <a>$sel:nextMarker:PublicKeyList'</a>, <a>publicKeyList_nextMarker</a>
--   - If there are more elements to be listed, this element is present and
--   contains the value that you can use for the <tt>Marker</tt> request
--   parameter to continue listing your public keys where you left off.
--   
--   <a>$sel:maxItems:PublicKeyList'</a>, <a>publicKeyList_maxItems</a> -
--   The maximum number of public keys you want in the response.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:PublicKeyList'</a>, <a>publicKeyList_quantity</a> -
--   The number of public keys in the list.
newPublicKeyList :: Int -> Int -> PublicKeyList

-- | A list of public keys.
publicKeyList_items :: Lens' PublicKeyList (Maybe [PublicKeySummary])

-- | If there are more elements to be listed, this element is present and
--   contains the value that you can use for the <tt>Marker</tt> request
--   parameter to continue listing your public keys where you left off.
publicKeyList_nextMarker :: Lens' PublicKeyList (Maybe Text)

-- | The maximum number of public keys you want in the response.
publicKeyList_maxItems :: Lens' PublicKeyList Int

-- | The number of public keys in the list.
publicKeyList_quantity :: Lens' PublicKeyList Int

instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.PublicKeyList.PublicKeyList

--   
--   
--   <a>$sel:forwardWhenQueryArgProfileIsUnknown:QueryArgProfileConfig'</a>,

--   Flag to set if you want a request to be forwarded to the origin even

--   fle-profile, is unknown.

--   encryption.

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FieldLevelEncryptionSummary

-- | A summary of a field-level encryption item.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newFieldLevelEncryptionSummary</a> smart constructor.
data FieldLevelEncryptionSummary
FieldLevelEncryptionSummary' :: Maybe QueryArgProfileConfig -> Maybe ContentTypeProfileConfig -> Maybe Text -> Text -> ISO8601 -> FieldLevelEncryptionSummary

-- | A summary of a query argument-profile mapping.
[$sel:queryArgProfileConfig:FieldLevelEncryptionSummary'] :: FieldLevelEncryptionSummary -> Maybe QueryArgProfileConfig

-- | A summary of a content type-profile mapping.
[$sel:contentTypeProfileConfig:FieldLevelEncryptionSummary'] :: FieldLevelEncryptionSummary -> Maybe ContentTypeProfileConfig

-- | An optional comment about the field-level encryption item. The comment
--   cannot be longer than 128 characters.
[$sel:comment:FieldLevelEncryptionSummary'] :: FieldLevelEncryptionSummary -> Maybe Text

-- | The unique ID of a field-level encryption item.
[$sel:id:FieldLevelEncryptionSummary'] :: FieldLevelEncryptionSummary -> Text

-- | The last time that the summary of field-level encryption items was
--   modified.
[$sel:lastModifiedTime:FieldLevelEncryptionSummary'] :: FieldLevelEncryptionSummary -> ISO8601

-- | Create a value of <a>FieldLevelEncryptionSummary</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:queryArgProfileConfig:FieldLevelEncryptionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>fieldLevelEncryptionSummary_queryArgProfileConfig</a> - A summary
--   of a query argument-profile mapping.
--   
--   <a>$sel:contentTypeProfileConfig:FieldLevelEncryptionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>fieldLevelEncryptionSummary_contentTypeProfileConfig</a> - A
--   summary of a content type-profile mapping.
--   
--   <a>$sel:comment:FieldLevelEncryptionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>fieldLevelEncryptionSummary_comment</a> - An optional comment about
--   the field-level encryption item. The comment cannot be longer than 128
--   characters.
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:FieldLevelEncryptionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>fieldLevelEncryptionSummary_id</a> - The unique ID of a field-level
--   encryption item.
--   
--   <a>$sel:lastModifiedTime:FieldLevelEncryptionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>fieldLevelEncryptionSummary_lastModifiedTime</a> - The last time
--   that the summary of field-level encryption items was modified.
newFieldLevelEncryptionSummary :: Text -> UTCTime -> FieldLevelEncryptionSummary

-- | A summary of a query argument-profile mapping.
fieldLevelEncryptionSummary_queryArgProfileConfig :: Lens' FieldLevelEncryptionSummary (Maybe QueryArgProfileConfig)

-- | A summary of a content type-profile mapping.
fieldLevelEncryptionSummary_contentTypeProfileConfig :: Lens' FieldLevelEncryptionSummary (Maybe ContentTypeProfileConfig)

-- | An optional comment about the field-level encryption item. The comment
--   cannot be longer than 128 characters.
fieldLevelEncryptionSummary_comment :: Lens' FieldLevelEncryptionSummary (Maybe Text)

-- | The unique ID of a field-level encryption item.
fieldLevelEncryptionSummary_id :: Lens' FieldLevelEncryptionSummary Text

-- | The last time that the summary of field-level encryption items was
--   modified.

--   argument in a request.

--   longer than 128 characters.

-- | A unique number that ensures the request can't be replayed.

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.FieldLevelEncryption

-- | A complex data type that includes the profile configurations and other

--   includes a set of profiles that specify certain selected data fields
--   to be encrypted by specific public keys.

--   to be encrypted by specific public keys.

--   field-level encryption configuration was changed.
--   
--   <a>$sel:fieldLevelEncryptionConfig:FieldLevelEncryption'</a>,

--   data type that includes the profile configurations specified for
--   field-level encryption.
newFieldLevelEncryption :: Text -> UTCTime -> FieldLevelEncryptionConfig -> FieldLevelEncryption

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.QueryStringCacheKeys

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy or
--   an origin request policy instead of this field.
--   
--   If you want to include query strings in the cache key, use
--   <tt>QueryStringsConfig</tt> in a cache policy. See
--   <tt>CachePolicy</tt>.
--   
--   If you want to send query strings to the origin but not include them
--   in the cache key, use <tt>QueryStringsConfig</tt> in an origin request
--   policy. See <tt>OriginRequestPolicy</tt>.
--   
--   A complex type that contains information about the query string
--   parameters that you want CloudFront to use for caching for a cache
--   behavior.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newQueryStringCacheKeys</a> smart constructor.
data QueryStringCacheKeys
QueryStringCacheKeys' :: Maybe [Text] -> Int -> QueryStringCacheKeys

-- | A list that contains the query string parameters that you want
--   CloudFront to use as a basis for caching for a cache behavior. If
--   <tt>Quantity</tt> is 0, you can omit <tt>Items</tt>.
[$sel:items:QueryStringCacheKeys'] :: QueryStringCacheKeys -> Maybe [Text]

-- | The number of <tt>whitelisted</tt> query string parameters for a cache
--   behavior.
[$sel:quantity:QueryStringCacheKeys'] :: QueryStringCacheKeys -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>QueryStringCacheKeys</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:QueryStringCacheKeys'</a>,
--   <a>queryStringCacheKeys_items</a> - A list that contains the query
--   string parameters that you want CloudFront to use as a basis for
--   caching for a cache behavior. If <tt>Quantity</tt> is 0, you can omit
--   <tt>Items</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:QueryStringCacheKeys'</a>,
--   <a>queryStringCacheKeys_quantity</a> - The number of
--   <tt>whitelisted</tt> query string parameters for a cache behavior.
newQueryStringCacheKeys :: Int -> QueryStringCacheKeys

-- | A list that contains the query string parameters that you want
--   CloudFront to use as a basis for caching for a cache behavior. If
--   <tt>Quantity</tt> is 0, you can omit <tt>Items</tt>.
queryStringCacheKeys_items :: Lens' QueryStringCacheKeys (Maybe [Text])

-- | The number of <tt>whitelisted</tt> query string parameters for a cache
--   behavior.
queryStringCacheKeys_quantity :: Lens' QueryStringCacheKeys Int

instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.QueryStringCacheKeys.QueryStringCacheKeys

instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.QueryStringCacheKeys.QueryStringCacheKeys
