instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.StreamingDistributionConfigWithTags.StreamingDistributionConfigWithTags


module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.StreamingDistribution

-- | A streaming distribution tells CloudFront where you want RTMP content
--   to be delivered from, and the details about how to track and manage
--   content delivery.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newStreamingDistribution</a> smart constructor.
data StreamingDistribution
StreamingDistribution' :: Maybe ISO8601 -> Text -> Text -> Text -> Text -> ActiveTrustedSigners -> StreamingDistributionConfig -> StreamingDistribution

-- | The date and time that the distribution was last modified.
[$sel:lastModifiedTime:StreamingDistribution'] :: StreamingDistribution -> Maybe ISO8601

-- | The identifier for the RTMP distribution. For example:
--   <tt>EGTXBD79EXAMPLE</tt>.
[$sel:id:StreamingDistribution'] :: StreamingDistribution -> Text

-- | The ARN (Amazon Resource Name) for the distribution. For example:
--   <tt>arn:aws:cloudfront::123456789012:distribution/EDFDVBD632BHDS5</tt>,
--   where <tt>123456789012</tt> is your account ID.
[$sel:arn:StreamingDistribution'] :: StreamingDistribution -> Text

-- | The current status of the RTMP distribution. When the status is
--   <tt>Deployed</tt>, the distribution's information is propagated to all
--   CloudFront edge locations.
[$sel:status:StreamingDistribution'] :: StreamingDistribution -> Text

-- | The domain name that corresponds to the streaming distribution, for
--   example, <tt>s5c39gqb8ow64r.cloudfront.net</tt>.
[$sel:domainName:StreamingDistribution'] :: StreamingDistribution -> Text

-- | A complex type that lists the accounts, if any, that you included in
--   the <tt>TrustedSigners</tt> complex type for this distribution. These
--   are the accounts that you want to allow to create signed URLs for
--   private content.
--   
--   The <tt>Signer</tt> complex type lists the account number of the
--   trusted signer or <tt>self</tt> if the signer is the account that
--   created the distribution. The <tt>Signer</tt> element also includes
--   the IDs of any active CloudFront key pairs that are associated with
--   the trusted signer's account. If no <tt>KeyPairId</tt> element appears
--   for a <tt>Signer</tt>, that signer can't create signed URLs.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Serving Private Content through
--   CloudFront</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:activeTrustedSigners:StreamingDistribution'] :: StreamingDistribution -> ActiveTrustedSigners

-- | The current configuration information for the RTMP distribution.
[$sel:streamingDistributionConfig:StreamingDistribution'] :: StreamingDistribution -> StreamingDistributionConfig

-- | Create a value of <a>StreamingDistribution</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:lastModifiedTime:StreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistribution_lastModifiedTime</a> - The date and time that
--   the distribution was last modified.
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:StreamingDistribution'</a>, <a>streamingDistribution_id</a>
--   - The identifier for the RTMP distribution. For example:
--   <tt>EGTXBD79EXAMPLE</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:arn:StreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistribution_arn</a> - The ARN (Amazon Resource Name) for
--   the distribution. For example:
--   <tt>arn:aws:cloudfront::123456789012:distribution/EDFDVBD632BHDS5</tt>,
--   where <tt>123456789012</tt> is your account ID.
--   
--   <a>$sel:status:StreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistribution_status</a> - The current status of the RTMP
--   distribution. When the status is <tt>Deployed</tt>, the distribution's
--   information is propagated to all CloudFront edge locations.
--   
--   <a>$sel:domainName:StreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistribution_domainName</a> - The domain name that
--   corresponds to the streaming distribution, for example,
--   <tt>s5c39gqb8ow64r.cloudfront.net</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:activeTrustedSigners:StreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistribution_activeTrustedSigners</a> - A complex type
--   that lists the accounts, if any, that you included in the
--   <tt>TrustedSigners</tt> complex type for this distribution. These are
--   the accounts that you want to allow to create signed URLs for private
--   content.
--   
--   The <tt>Signer</tt> complex type lists the account number of the
--   trusted signer or <tt>self</tt> if the signer is the account that
--   created the distribution. The <tt>Signer</tt> element also includes
--   the IDs of any active CloudFront key pairs that are associated with
--   the trusted signer's account. If no <tt>KeyPairId</tt> element appears
--   for a <tt>Signer</tt>, that signer can't create signed URLs.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Serving Private Content through
--   CloudFront</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:streamingDistributionConfig:StreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistribution_streamingDistributionConfig</a> - The current
--   configuration information for the RTMP distribution.
newStreamingDistribution :: Text -> Text -> Text -> Text -> ActiveTrustedSigners -> StreamingDistributionConfig -> StreamingDistribution

-- | The date and time that the distribution was last modified.
streamingDistribution_lastModifiedTime :: Lens' StreamingDistribution (Maybe UTCTime)

-- | The identifier for the RTMP distribution. For example:
--   <tt>EGTXBD79EXAMPLE</tt>.
streamingDistribution_id :: Lens' StreamingDistribution Text

-- | The ARN (Amazon Resource Name) for the distribution. For example:
--   <tt>arn:aws:cloudfront::123456789012:distribution/EDFDVBD632BHDS5</tt>,
--   where <tt>123456789012</tt> is your account ID.
streamingDistribution_arn :: Lens' StreamingDistribution Text

-- | The current status of the RTMP distribution. When the status is
--   <tt>Deployed</tt>, the distribution's information is propagated to all
--   CloudFront edge locations.
streamingDistribution_status :: Lens' StreamingDistribution Text

-- | The domain name that corresponds to the streaming distribution, for
--   example, <tt>s5c39gqb8ow64r.cloudfront.net</tt>.
streamingDistribution_domainName :: Lens' StreamingDistribution Text

-- | A complex type that lists the accounts, if any, that you included in
--   the <tt>TrustedSigners</tt> complex type for this distribution. These
--   are the accounts that you want to allow to create signed URLs for
--   private content.
--   
--   The <tt>Signer</tt> complex type lists the account number of the
--   trusted signer or <tt>self</tt> if the signer is the account that
--   created the distribution. The <tt>Signer</tt> element also includes
--   the IDs of any active CloudFront key pairs that are associated with
--   the trusted signer's account. If no <tt>KeyPairId</tt> element appears
--   for a <tt>Signer</tt>, that signer can't create signed URLs.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Serving Private Content through
--   CloudFront</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
streamingDistribution_activeTrustedSigners :: Lens' StreamingDistribution ActiveTrustedSigners

-- | The current configuration information for the RTMP distribution.
streamingDistribution_streamingDistributionConfig :: Lens' StreamingDistribution StreamingDistributionConfig
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.StreamingDistribution.StreamingDistribution
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.StreamingDistribution.StreamingDistribution
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.StreamingDistribution.StreamingDistribution
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.StreamingDistribution.StreamingDistribution
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.StreamingDistribution.StreamingDistribution
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.StreamingDistribution.StreamingDistribution
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.StreamingDistribution.StreamingDistribution


module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ViewerCertificate

-- | A complex type that determines the distribution’s SSL/TLS
--   configuration for communicating with viewers.
--   
--   If the distribution doesn’t use <tt>Aliases</tt> (also known as
--   alternate domain names or CNAMEs)—that is, if the distribution uses
--   the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>—set
--   <tt>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</tt> to <tt>true</tt> and leave all
--   other fields empty.
--   
--   If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), use the fields in this type to specify the following
--   settings:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>Which viewers the distribution accepts HTTPS connections from:
--   only viewers that support <a>server name indication (SNI)</a>
--   (recommended), or all viewers including those that don’t support
--   SNI.<ul><li>To accept HTTPS connections from only viewers that support
--   SNI, set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to <tt>sni-only</tt>. This is
--   recommended. Most browsers and clients support SNI.</li><li>To accept
--   HTTPS connections from all viewers, including those that don’t support
--   SNI, set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to <tt>vip</tt>. This is not
--   recommended, and results in additional monthly charges from
--   CloudFront.</li></ul></li>
--   <li>The minimum SSL/TLS protocol version that the distribution can use
--   to communicate with viewers. To specify a minimum version, choose a
--   value for <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt>. For more information, see
--   <a>Security Policy</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.</li>
--   <li>The location of the SSL/TLS certificate, <a>Certificate Manager
--   (ACM)</a> (recommended) or <a>Identity and Access Management
--   (IAM)</a>. You specify the location by setting a value in one of the
--   following fields (not
--   both):<ul><li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li><li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li></ul></li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   All distributions support HTTPS connections from viewers. To require
--   viewers to use HTTPS only, or to redirect them from HTTP to HTTPS, use
--   <tt>ViewerProtocolPolicy</tt> in the <tt>CacheBehavior</tt> or
--   <tt>DefaultCacheBehavior</tt>. To specify how CloudFront should use
--   SSL/TLS to communicate with your custom origin, use
--   <tt>CustomOriginConfig</tt>.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Using HTTPS with CloudFront</a> and
--   <a>Using Alternate Domain Names and HTTPS</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newViewerCertificate</a> smart constructor.
data ViewerCertificate
ViewerCertificate' :: Maybe SSLSupportMethod -> Maybe Text -> Maybe CertificateSource -> Maybe MinimumProtocolVersion -> Maybe Text -> Maybe Text -> Maybe Bool -> ViewerCertificate

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), specify which viewers the distribution accepts HTTPS
--   connections from.
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>sni-only</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections
--   from only viewers that support <a>server name indication (SNI)</a>.
--   This is recommended. Most browsers and clients support SNI.</li>
--   <li><tt>vip</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections from all
--   viewers including those that don’t support SNI. This is not
--   recommended, and results in additional monthly charges from
--   CloudFront.</li>
--   <li><tt>static-ip</tt> - Do not specify this value unless your
--   distribution has been enabled for this feature by the CloudFront team.
--   If you have a use case that requires static IP addresses for a
--   distribution, contact CloudFront through the <a>Amazon Web Services
--   Support Center</a>.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, don’t set a value for this
--   field.
[$sel:sSLSupportMethod:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe SSLSupportMethod

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS certificate is stored in <a>Certificate
--   Manager (ACM)</a>, provide the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the ACM
--   certificate. CloudFront only supports ACM certificates in the US East
--   (N. Virginia) Region (<tt>us-east-1</tt>).
--   
--   If you specify an ACM certificate ARN, you must also specify values
--   for <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
[$sel:aCMCertificateArn:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe Text

-- | This field is deprecated. Use one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:certificateSource:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe CertificateSource

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), specify the security policy that you want CloudFront to use
--   for HTTPS connections with viewers. The security policy determines two
--   settings:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The minimum SSL/TLS protocol that CloudFront can use to
--   communicate with viewers.</li>
--   <li>The ciphers that CloudFront can use to encrypt the content that it
--   returns to viewers.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Security Policy</a> and <a>Supported
--   Protocols and Ciphers Between Viewers and CloudFront</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   On the CloudFront console, this setting is called <b>Security
--   Policy</b>.
--   
--   When you’re using SNI only (you set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to
--   <tt>sni-only</tt>), you must specify <tt>TLSv1</tt> or higher.
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt> (you set
--   <tt>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</tt> to <tt>true</tt>), CloudFront
--   automatically sets the security policy to <tt>TLSv1</tt> regardless of
--   the value that you set here.
[$sel:minimumProtocolVersion:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe MinimumProtocolVersion

-- | This field is deprecated. Use one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:certificate:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe Text

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS certificate is stored in <a>Identity and
--   Access Management (IAM)</a>, provide the ID of the IAM certificate.
--   
--   If you specify an IAM certificate ID, you must also specify values for
--   <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
[$sel:iAMCertificateId:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe Text

-- | If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, set this field to
--   <tt>true</tt>.
--   
--   If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), set this field to <tt>false</tt> and specify values for the
--   following fields:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>ACMCertificateArn</tt> or <tt>IAMCertificateId</tt> (specify a
--   value for one, not both)</li>
--   <li><pre>MinimumProtocolVersion</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>SSLSupportMethod</pre></li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:cloudFrontDefaultCertificate:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe Bool

-- | Create a value of <a>ViewerCertificate</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:sSLSupportMethod:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_sSLSupportMethod</a> - If the distribution uses
--   <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or CNAMEs), specify which
--   viewers the distribution accepts HTTPS connections from.
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>sni-only</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections
--   from only viewers that support <a>server name indication (SNI)</a>.
--   This is recommended. Most browsers and clients support SNI.</li>
--   <li><tt>vip</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections from all
--   viewers including those that don’t support SNI. This is not
--   recommended, and results in additional monthly charges from
--   CloudFront.</li>
--   <li><tt>static-ip</tt> - Do not specify this value unless your
--   distribution has been enabled for this feature by the CloudFront team.
--   If you have a use case that requires static IP addresses for a
--   distribution, contact CloudFront through the <a>Amazon Web Services
--   Support Center</a>.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, don’t set a value for this
--   field.
--   
--   <a>$sel:aCMCertificateArn:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_aCMCertificateArn</a> - If the distribution uses
--   <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS
--   certificate is stored in <a>Certificate Manager (ACM)</a>, provide the
--   Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the ACM certificate. CloudFront only
--   supports ACM certificates in the US East (N. Virginia) Region
--   (<tt>us-east-1</tt>).
--   
--   If you specify an ACM certificate ARN, you must also specify values
--   for <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:certificateSource:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_certificateSource</a> - This field is deprecated.
--   Use one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   <a>$sel:minimumProtocolVersion:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_minimumProtocolVersion</a> - If the distribution
--   uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or CNAMEs), specify the
--   security policy that you want CloudFront to use for HTTPS connections
--   with viewers. The security policy determines two settings:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The minimum SSL/TLS protocol that CloudFront can use to
--   communicate with viewers.</li>
--   <li>The ciphers that CloudFront can use to encrypt the content that it
--   returns to viewers.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Security Policy</a> and <a>Supported
--   Protocols and Ciphers Between Viewers and CloudFront</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   On the CloudFront console, this setting is called <b>Security
--   Policy</b>.
--   
--   When you’re using SNI only (you set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to
--   <tt>sni-only</tt>), you must specify <tt>TLSv1</tt> or higher.
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt> (you set
--   <tt>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</tt> to <tt>true</tt>), CloudFront
--   automatically sets the security policy to <tt>TLSv1</tt> regardless of
--   the value that you set here.
--   
--   <a>$sel:certificate:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_certificate</a> - This field is deprecated. Use
--   one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   <a>$sel:iAMCertificateId:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_iAMCertificateId</a> - If the distribution uses
--   <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS
--   certificate is stored in <a>Identity and Access Management (IAM)</a>,
--   provide the ID of the IAM certificate.
--   
--   If you specify an IAM certificate ID, you must also specify values for
--   <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:cloudFrontDefaultCertificate:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_cloudFrontDefaultCertificate</a> - If the
--   distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, set this field to
--   <tt>true</tt>.
--   
--   If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), set this field to <tt>false</tt> and specify values for the
--   following fields:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>ACMCertificateArn</tt> or <tt>IAMCertificateId</tt> (specify a
--   value for one, not both)</li>
--   <li><pre>MinimumProtocolVersion</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>SSLSupportMethod</pre></li>
--   </ul>
newViewerCertificate :: ViewerCertificate

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), specify which viewers the distribution accepts HTTPS
--   connections from.
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>sni-only</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections
--   from only viewers that support <a>server name indication (SNI)</a>.
--   This is recommended. Most browsers and clients support SNI.</li>
--   <li><tt>vip</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections from all
--   viewers including those that don’t support SNI. This is not
--   recommended, and results in additional monthly charges from
--   CloudFront.</li>
--   <li><tt>static-ip</tt> - Do not specify this value unless your
--   distribution has been enabled for this feature by the CloudFront team.
--   If you have a use case that requires static IP addresses for a
--   distribution, contact CloudFront through the <a>Amazon Web Services
--   Support Center</a>.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, don’t set a value for this
--   field.
viewerCertificate_sSLSupportMethod :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe SSLSupportMethod)

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS certificate is stored in <a>Certificate
--   Manager (ACM)</a>, provide the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the ACM
--   certificate. CloudFront only supports ACM certificates in the US East
--   (N. Virginia) Region (<tt>us-east-1</tt>).
--   
--   If you specify an ACM certificate ARN, you must also specify values
--   for <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
viewerCertificate_aCMCertificateArn :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe Text)

-- | This field is deprecated. Use one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
viewerCertificate_certificateSource :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe CertificateSource)

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), specify the security policy that you want CloudFront to use
--   for HTTPS connections with viewers. The security policy determines two
--   settings:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The minimum SSL/TLS protocol that CloudFront can use to
--   communicate with viewers.</li>
--   <li>The ciphers that CloudFront can use to encrypt the content that it
--   returns to viewers.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Security Policy</a> and <a>Supported
--   Protocols and Ciphers Between Viewers and CloudFront</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   On the CloudFront console, this setting is called <b>Security
--   Policy</b>.
--   
--   When you’re using SNI only (you set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to
--   <tt>sni-only</tt>), you must specify <tt>TLSv1</tt> or higher.
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt> (you set
--   <tt>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</tt> to <tt>true</tt>), CloudFront
--   automatically sets the security policy to <tt>TLSv1</tt> regardless of
--   the value that you set here.
viewerCertificate_minimumProtocolVersion :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe MinimumProtocolVersion)

-- | This field is deprecated. Use one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
viewerCertificate_certificate :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe Text)

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS certificate is stored in <a>Identity and
--   Access Management (IAM)</a>, provide the ID of the IAM certificate.
--   
--   If you specify an IAM certificate ID, you must also specify values for
--   <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
viewerCertificate_iAMCertificateId :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe Text)

-- | If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, set this field to
--   <tt>true</tt>.
--   
--   If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), set this field to <tt>false</tt> and specify values for the
--   following fields:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>ACMCertificateArn</tt> or <tt>IAMCertificateId</tt> (specify a
--   value for one, not both)</li>
--   <li><pre>MinimumProtocolVersion</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>SSLSupportMethod</pre></li>
--   </ul>
viewerCertificate_cloudFrontDefaultCertificate :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe Bool)
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ViewerCertificate.ViewerCertificate
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ViewerCertificate.ViewerCertificate
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ViewerCertificate.ViewerCertificate
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ViewerCertificate.ViewerCertificate
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.FromXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ViewerCertificate.ViewerCertificate
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ViewerCertificate.ViewerCertificate
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ViewerCertificate.ViewerCertificate
instance Network.AWS.Data.XML.ToXML Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ViewerCertificate.ViewerCertificate


module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.ViewerProtocolPolicy

ViewerProtocolPolicy' :: Text -> ViewerProtocolPolicy
[fromViewerProtocolPolicy] :: ViewerProtocolPolicy -> Text
pattern ViewerProtocolPolicy_Allow_all :: ViewerProtocolPolicy
pattern ViewerProtocolPolicy_Https_only :: ViewerProtocolPolicy
pattern ViewerProtocolPolicy_Redirect_to_https :: ViewerProtocolPolicy

module Network.AWS.CloudFront.Types.DefaultCacheBehavior

-- | A complex type that describes the default cache behavior if you don’t
--   specify a <tt>CacheBehavior</tt> element or if request URLs don’t
--   match any of the values of <tt>PathPattern</tt> in
--   <tt>CacheBehavior</tt> elements. You must create exactly one default
--   cache behavior.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newDefaultCacheBehavior</a> smart constructor.
data DefaultCacheBehavior
DefaultCacheBehavior' :: Maybe AllowedMethods -> Maybe LambdaFunctionAssociations -> Maybe Integer -> Maybe Integer -> Maybe Bool -> Maybe Bool -> Maybe TrustedKeyGroups -> Maybe Text -> Maybe Integer -> Maybe ForwardedValues -> Maybe TrustedSigners -> Maybe FunctionAssociations -> Maybe Text -> Maybe Text -> Maybe Text -> Text -> ViewerProtocolPolicy -> DefaultCacheBehavior
[$sel:allowedMethods:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe AllowedMethods

-- | A complex type that contains zero or more Lambda@Edge function
--   associations for a cache behavior.
[$sel:lambdaFunctionAssociations:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe LambdaFunctionAssociations

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use the
--   <tt>MaxTTL</tt> field in a cache policy instead of this field. For
--   more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> or <a>Using the
--   managed cache policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   The maximum amount of time that you want objects to stay in CloudFront
--   caches before CloudFront forwards another request to your origin to
--   determine whether the object has been updated. The value that you
--   specify applies only when your origin adds HTTP headers such as
--   <tt>Cache-Control max-age</tt>, <tt>Cache-Control s-maxage</tt>, and
--   <tt>Expires</tt> to objects. For more information, see <a>Managing How
--   Long Content Stays in an Edge Cache (Expiration)</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:maxTTL:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe Integer

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use the
--   <tt>MinTTL</tt> field in a cache policy instead of this field. For
--   more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> or <a>Using the
--   managed cache policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   The minimum amount of time that you want objects to stay in CloudFront
--   caches before CloudFront forwards another request to your origin to
--   determine whether the object has been updated. For more information,
--   see <a>Managing How Long Content Stays in an Edge Cache
--   (Expiration)</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   You must specify <tt>0</tt> for <tt>MinTTL</tt> if you configure
--   CloudFront to forward all headers to your origin (under
--   <tt>Headers</tt>, if you specify <tt>1</tt> for <tt>Quantity</tt> and
--   <tt>*</tt> for <tt>Name</tt>).
[$sel:minTTL:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe Integer

-- | Whether you want CloudFront to automatically compress certain files
--   for this cache behavior. If so, specify <tt>true</tt>; if not, specify
--   <tt>false</tt>. For more information, see <a>Serving Compressed
--   Files</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:compress:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe Bool

-- | Indicates whether you want to distribute media files in the Microsoft
--   Smooth Streaming format using the origin that is associated with this
--   cache behavior. If so, specify <tt>true</tt>; if not, specify
--   <tt>false</tt>. If you specify <tt>true</tt> for
--   <tt>SmoothStreaming</tt>, you can still distribute other content using
--   this cache behavior if the content matches the value of
--   <tt>PathPattern</tt>.
[$sel:smoothStreaming:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe Bool

-- | A list of key groups that CloudFront can use to validate signed URLs
--   or signed cookies.
--   
--   When a cache behavior contains trusted key groups, CloudFront requires
--   signed URLs or signed cookies for all requests that match the cache
--   behavior. The URLs or cookies must be signed with a private key whose
--   corresponding public key is in the key group. The signed URL or cookie
--   contains information about which public key CloudFront should use to
--   verify the signature. For more information, see <a>Serving private
--   content</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:trustedKeyGroups:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe TrustedKeyGroups

-- | The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the real-time log configuration that
--   is attached to this cache behavior. For more information, see
--   <a>Real-time logs</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:realtimeLogConfigArn:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe Text

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use the
--   <tt>DefaultTTL</tt> field in a cache policy instead of this field. For
--   more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> or <a>Using the
--   managed cache policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   The default amount of time that you want objects to stay in CloudFront
--   caches before CloudFront forwards another request to your origin to
--   determine whether the object has been updated. The value that you
--   specify applies only when your origin does not add HTTP headers such
--   as <tt>Cache-Control max-age</tt>, <tt>Cache-Control s-maxage</tt>,
--   and <tt>Expires</tt> to objects. For more information, see <a>Managing
--   How Long Content Stays in an Edge Cache (Expiration)</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:defaultTTL:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe Integer

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy or
--   an origin request policy instead of this field. For more information,
--   see <a>Working with policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to include values in the cache key, use a cache policy.
--   For more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> or <a>Using
--   the managed cache policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to send values to the origin but not include them in the
--   cache key, use an origin request policy. For more information, see
--   <a>Creating origin request policies</a> or <a>Using the managed origin
--   request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   A <tt>DefaultCacheBehavior</tt> must include either a
--   <tt>CachePolicyId</tt> or <tt>ForwardedValues</tt>. We recommend that
--   you use a <tt>CachePolicyId</tt>.
--   
--   A complex type that specifies how CloudFront handles query strings,
--   cookies, and HTTP headers.
[$sel:forwardedValues:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe ForwardedValues

-- | We recommend using <tt>TrustedKeyGroups</tt> instead of
--   <tt>TrustedSigners</tt>.
--   
--   A list of account IDs whose public keys CloudFront can use to validate
--   signed URLs or signed cookies.
--   
--   When a cache behavior contains trusted signers, CloudFront requires
--   signed URLs or signed cookies for all requests that match the cache
--   behavior. The URLs or cookies must be signed with the private key of a
--   CloudFront key pair in a trusted signer’s account. The signed URL or
--   cookie contains information about which public key CloudFront should
--   use to verify the signature. For more information, see <a>Serving
--   private content</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:trustedSigners:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe TrustedSigners

-- | A list of CloudFront functions that are associated with this cache
--   behavior. CloudFront functions must be published to the <tt>LIVE</tt>
--   stage to associate them with a cache behavior.
[$sel:functionAssociations:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe FunctionAssociations

-- | The unique identifier of the origin request policy that is attached to
--   the default cache behavior. For more information, see <a>Creating
--   origin request policies</a> or <a>Using the managed origin request
--   policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:originRequestPolicyId:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe Text

-- | The value of <tt>ID</tt> for the field-level encryption configuration
--   that you want CloudFront to use for encrypting specific fields of data
--   for the default cache behavior.
[$sel:fieldLevelEncryptionId:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe Text

-- | The unique identifier of the cache policy that is attached to the
--   default cache behavior. For more information, see <a>Creating cache
--   policies</a> or <a>Using the managed cache policies</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   A <tt>DefaultCacheBehavior</tt> must include either a
--   <tt>CachePolicyId</tt> or <tt>ForwardedValues</tt>. We recommend that
--   you use a <tt>CachePolicyId</tt>.
[$sel:cachePolicyId:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Maybe Text

-- | The value of <tt>ID</tt> for the origin that you want CloudFront to
--   route requests to when they use the default cache behavior.
[$sel:targetOriginId:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> Text

-- | The protocol that viewers can use to access the files in the origin
--   specified by <tt>TargetOriginId</tt> when a request matches the path
--   pattern in <tt>PathPattern</tt>. You can specify the following
--   options:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>allow-all</tt>: Viewers can use HTTP or HTTPS.</li>
--   <li><tt>redirect-to-https</tt>: If a viewer submits an HTTP request,
--   CloudFront returns an HTTP status code of 301 (Moved Permanently) to
--   the viewer along with the HTTPS URL. The viewer then resubmits the
--   request using the new URL.</li>
--   <li><tt>https-only</tt>: If a viewer sends an HTTP request, CloudFront
--   returns an HTTP status code of 403 (Forbidden).</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For more information about requiring the HTTPS protocol, see
--   <a>Requiring HTTPS Between Viewers and CloudFront</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   The only way to guarantee that viewers retrieve an object that was
--   fetched from the origin using HTTPS is never to use any other protocol
--   to fetch the object. If you have recently changed from HTTP to HTTPS,
--   we recommend that you clear your objects’ cache because cached objects
--   are protocol agnostic. That means that an edge location will return an
--   object from the cache regardless of whether the current request
--   protocol matches the protocol used previously. For more information,
--   see <a>Managing Cache Expiration</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:viewerProtocolPolicy:DefaultCacheBehavior'] :: DefaultCacheBehavior -> ViewerProtocolPolicy

-- | Create a value of <a>DefaultCacheBehavior</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:allowedMethods:DefaultCacheBehavior'</a>,
--   <a>defaultCacheBehavior_allowedMethods</a> - Undocumented member.
--   
--   <a>$sel:lambdaFunctionAssociations:DefaultCacheBehavior'</a>,
--   <a>defaultCacheBehavior_lambdaFunctionAssociations</a> - A complex
--   type that contains zero or more Lambda@Edge function associations for
--   a cache behavior.
--   
--   <a>$sel:maxTTL:DefaultCacheBehavior'</a>,
--   <a>defaultCacheBehavior_maxTTL</a> - This field is deprecated. We
--   recommend that you use the <tt>MaxTTL</tt> field in a cache policy
--   instead of this field. For more information, see <a>Creating cache
--   policies</a> or <a>Using the managed cache policies</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   The maximum amount of time that you want objects to stay in CloudFront
--   caches before CloudFront forwards another request to your origin to
--   determine whether the object has been updated. The value that you
--   specify applies only when your origin adds HTTP headers such as
--   <tt>Cache-Control max-age</tt>, <tt>Cache-Control s-maxage</tt>, and
--   <tt>Expires</tt> to objects. For more information, see <a>Managing How
--   Long Content Stays in an Edge Cache (Expiration)</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:minTTL:DefaultCacheBehavior'</a>,
--   <a>defaultCacheBehavior_minTTL</a> - This field is deprecated. We
--   recommend that you use the <tt>MinTTL</tt> field in a cache policy
--   instead of this field. For more information, see <a>Creating cache
--   policies</a> or <a>Using the managed cache policies</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   The minimum amount of time that you want objects to stay in CloudFront
--   caches before CloudFront forwards another request to your origin to
--   determine whether the object has been updated. For more information,
--   see <a>Managing How Long Content Stays in an Edge Cache
--   (Expiration)</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   You must specify <tt>0</tt> for <tt>MinTTL</tt> if you configure
--   CloudFront to forward all headers to your origin (under
--   <tt>Headers</tt>, if you specify <tt>1</tt> for <tt>Quantity</tt> and
--   <tt>*</tt> for <tt>Name</tt>).
--   
--   <a>$sel:compress:DefaultCacheBehavior'</a>,
--   <a>defaultCacheBehavior_compress</a> - Whether you want CloudFront to
--   automatically compress certain files for this cache behavior. If so,
--   specify <tt>true</tt>; if not, specify <tt>false</tt>. For more
--   information, see <a>Serving Compressed Files</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:smoothStreaming:DefaultCacheBehavior'</a>,
--   <a>defaultCacheBehavior_smoothStreaming</a> - Indicates whether you
--   want to distribute media files in the Microsoft Smooth Streaming
--   format using the origin that is associated with this cache behavior.
--   If so, specify <tt>true</tt>; if not, specify <tt>false</tt>. If you
--   specify <tt>true</tt> for <tt>SmoothStreaming</tt>, you can still
--   distribute other content using this cache behavior if the content
--   matches the value of <tt>PathPattern</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:trustedKeyGroups:DefaultCacheBehavior'</a>,
--   <a>defaultCacheBehavior_trustedKeyGroups</a> - A list of key groups
--   that CloudFront can use to validate signed URLs or signed cookies.
--   
--   When a cache behavior contains trusted key groups, CloudFront requires
--   signed URLs or signed cookies for all requests that match the cache
--   behavior. The URLs or cookies must be signed with a private key whose
--   corresponding public key is in the key group. The signed URL or cookie
--   contains information about which public key CloudFront should use to
--   verify the signature. For more information, see <a>Serving private
--   content</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:realtimeLogConfigArn:DefaultCacheBehavior'</a>,
--   <a>defaultCacheBehavior_realtimeLogConfigArn</a> - The Amazon Resource
--   Name (ARN) of the real-time log configuration that is attached to this
--   cache behavior. For more information, see <a>Real-time logs</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:defaultTTL:DefaultCacheBehavior'</a>,
--   <a>defaultCacheBehavior_defaultTTL</a> - This field is deprecated. We
--   recommend that you use the <tt>DefaultTTL</tt> field in a cache policy
--   instead of this field. For more information, see <a>Creating cache
--   policies</a> or <a>Using the managed cache policies</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   The default amount of time that you want objects to stay in CloudFront
--   caches before CloudFront forwards another request to your origin to
--   determine whether the object has been updated. The value that you
--   specify applies only when your origin does not add HTTP headers such
--   as <tt>Cache-Control max-age</tt>, <tt>Cache-Control s-maxage</tt>,
--   and <tt>Expires</tt> to objects. For more information, see <a>Managing
--   How Long Content Stays in an Edge Cache (Expiration)</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:forwardedValues:DefaultCacheBehavior'</a>,
--   <a>defaultCacheBehavior_forwardedValues</a> - This field is
--   deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy or an origin
--   request policy instead of this field. For more information, see
--   <a>Working with policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to include values in the cache key, use a cache policy.
--   For more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> or <a>Using
--   the managed cache policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to send values to the origin but not include them in the
--   cache key, use an origin request policy. For more information, see
--   <a>Creating origin request policies</a> or <a>Using the managed origin
--   request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   A <tt>DefaultCacheBehavior</tt> must include either a
--   <tt>CachePolicyId</tt> or <tt>ForwardedValues</tt>. We recommend that
--   you use a <tt>CachePolicyId</tt>.
--   
--   A complex type that specifies how CloudFront handles query strings,
--   cookies, and HTTP headers.
--   
--   <a>$sel:trustedSigners:DefaultCacheBehavior'</a>,
--   <a>defaultCacheBehavior_trustedSigners</a> - We recommend using
--   <tt>TrustedKeyGroups</tt> instead of <tt>TrustedSigners</tt>.
--   
--   A list of account IDs whose public keys CloudFront can use to validate
--   signed URLs or signed cookies.
