--   <a>$sel:items:TrustedSigners'</a>, <a>trustedSigners_items</a> - A
--   list of account identifiers.
--   
--   <a>$sel:enabled:TrustedSigners'</a>, <a>trustedSigners_enabled</a> -
--   This field is <tt>true</tt> if any of the accounts have public keys
--   that CloudFront can use to verify the signatures of signed URLs and
--   signed cookies. If not, this field is <tt>false</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:TrustedSigners'</a>, <a>trustedSigners_quantity</a> -
--   The number of accounts in the list.
newTrustedSigners :: Bool -> Int -> TrustedSigners

-- | A list of account identifiers.
trustedSigners_items :: Lens' TrustedSigners (Maybe [Text])

-- | This field is <tt>true</tt> if any of the accounts have public keys
--   that CloudFront can use to verify the signatures of signed URLs and
--   signed cookies. If not, this field is <tt>false</tt>.
trustedSigners_enabled :: Lens' TrustedSigners Bool

-- | The number of accounts in the list.
trustedSigners_quantity :: Lens' TrustedSigners Int

-- | A complex type that determines the distribution’s SSL/TLS
--   configuration for communicating with viewers.
--   
--   If the distribution doesn’t use <tt>Aliases</tt> (also known as
--   alternate domain names or CNAMEs)—that is, if the distribution uses
--   the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>—set
--   <tt>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</tt> to <tt>true</tt> and leave all
--   other fields empty.
--   
--   If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), use the fields in this type to specify the following
--   settings:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>Which viewers the distribution accepts HTTPS connections from:
--   only viewers that support <a>server name indication (SNI)</a>
--   (recommended), or all viewers including those that don’t support
--   SNI.<ul><li>To accept HTTPS connections from only viewers that support
--   SNI, set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to <tt>sni-only</tt>. This is
--   recommended. Most browsers and clients support SNI.</li><li>To accept
--   HTTPS connections from all viewers, including those that don’t support
--   SNI, set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to <tt>vip</tt>. This is not
--   recommended, and results in additional monthly charges from
--   CloudFront.</li></ul></li>
--   <li>The minimum SSL/TLS protocol version that the distribution can use
--   to communicate with viewers. To specify a minimum version, choose a
--   value for <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt>. For more information, see
--   <a>Security Policy</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.</li>
--   <li>The location of the SSL/TLS certificate, <a>Certificate Manager
--   (ACM)</a> (recommended) or <a>Identity and Access Management
--   (IAM)</a>. You specify the location by setting a value in one of the
--   following fields (not
--   both):<ul><li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li><li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li></ul></li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   All distributions support HTTPS connections from viewers. To require
--   viewers to use HTTPS only, or to redirect them from HTTP to HTTPS, use
--   <tt>ViewerProtocolPolicy</tt> in the <tt>CacheBehavior</tt> or
--   <tt>DefaultCacheBehavior</tt>. To specify how CloudFront should use
--   SSL/TLS to communicate with your custom origin, use
--   <tt>CustomOriginConfig</tt>.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Using HTTPS with CloudFront</a> and
--   <a>Using Alternate Domain Names and HTTPS</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newViewerCertificate</a> smart constructor.
data ViewerCertificate
ViewerCertificate' :: Maybe SSLSupportMethod -> Maybe Text -> Maybe CertificateSource -> Maybe MinimumProtocolVersion -> Maybe Text -> Maybe Text -> Maybe Bool -> ViewerCertificate

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), specify which viewers the distribution accepts HTTPS
--   connections from.
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>sni-only</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections
--   from only viewers that support <a>server name indication (SNI)</a>.
--   This is recommended. Most browsers and clients support SNI.</li>
--   <li><tt>vip</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections from all
--   viewers including those that don’t support SNI. This is not
--   recommended, and results in additional monthly charges from
--   CloudFront.</li>
--   <li><tt>static-ip</tt> - Do not specify this value unless your
--   distribution has been enabled for this feature by the CloudFront team.
--   If you have a use case that requires static IP addresses for a
--   distribution, contact CloudFront through the <a>Amazon Web Services
--   Support Center</a>.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, don’t set a value for this
--   field.
[$sel:sSLSupportMethod:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe SSLSupportMethod

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS certificate is stored in <a>Certificate
--   Manager (ACM)</a>, provide the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the ACM
--   certificate. CloudFront only supports ACM certificates in the US East
--   (N. Virginia) Region (<tt>us-east-1</tt>).
--   
--   If you specify an ACM certificate ARN, you must also specify values
--   for <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
[$sel:aCMCertificateArn:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe Text

-- | This field is deprecated. Use one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:certificateSource:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe CertificateSource

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), specify the security policy that you want CloudFront to use
--   for HTTPS connections with viewers. The security policy determines two
--   settings:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The minimum SSL/TLS protocol that CloudFront can use to
--   communicate with viewers.</li>
--   <li>The ciphers that CloudFront can use to encrypt the content that it
--   returns to viewers.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Security Policy</a> and <a>Supported
--   Protocols and Ciphers Between Viewers and CloudFront</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   On the CloudFront console, this setting is called <b>Security
--   Policy</b>.
--   
--   When you’re using SNI only (you set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to
--   <tt>sni-only</tt>), you must specify <tt>TLSv1</tt> or higher.
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt> (you set
--   <tt>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</tt> to <tt>true</tt>), CloudFront
--   automatically sets the security policy to <tt>TLSv1</tt> regardless of
--   the value that you set here.
[$sel:minimumProtocolVersion:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe MinimumProtocolVersion

-- | This field is deprecated. Use one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:certificate:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe Text

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS certificate is stored in <a>Identity and
--   Access Management (IAM)</a>, provide the ID of the IAM certificate.
--   
--   If you specify an IAM certificate ID, you must also specify values for
--   <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
[$sel:iAMCertificateId:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe Text

-- | If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, set this field to
--   <tt>true</tt>.
--   
--   If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), set this field to <tt>false</tt> and specify values for the
--   following fields:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>ACMCertificateArn</tt> or <tt>IAMCertificateId</tt> (specify a
--   value for one, not both)</li>
--   <li><pre>MinimumProtocolVersion</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>SSLSupportMethod</pre></li>
--   </ul>
[$sel:cloudFrontDefaultCertificate:ViewerCertificate'] :: ViewerCertificate -> Maybe Bool

-- | Create a value of <a>ViewerCertificate</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:sSLSupportMethod:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_sSLSupportMethod</a> - If the distribution uses
--   <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or CNAMEs), specify which
--   viewers the distribution accepts HTTPS connections from.
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>sni-only</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections
--   from only viewers that support <a>server name indication (SNI)</a>.
--   This is recommended. Most browsers and clients support SNI.</li>
--   <li><tt>vip</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections from all
--   viewers including those that don’t support SNI. This is not
--   recommended, and results in additional monthly charges from
--   CloudFront.</li>
--   <li><tt>static-ip</tt> - Do not specify this value unless your
--   distribution has been enabled for this feature by the CloudFront team.
--   If you have a use case that requires static IP addresses for a
--   distribution, contact CloudFront through the <a>Amazon Web Services
--   Support Center</a>.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, don’t set a value for this
--   field.
--   
--   <a>$sel:aCMCertificateArn:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_aCMCertificateArn</a> - If the distribution uses
--   <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS
--   certificate is stored in <a>Certificate Manager (ACM)</a>, provide the
--   Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the ACM certificate. CloudFront only
--   supports ACM certificates in the US East (N. Virginia) Region
--   (<tt>us-east-1</tt>).
--   
--   If you specify an ACM certificate ARN, you must also specify values
--   for <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:certificateSource:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_certificateSource</a> - This field is deprecated.
--   Use one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   <a>$sel:minimumProtocolVersion:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_minimumProtocolVersion</a> - If the distribution
--   uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or CNAMEs), specify the
--   security policy that you want CloudFront to use for HTTPS connections
--   with viewers. The security policy determines two settings:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The minimum SSL/TLS protocol that CloudFront can use to
--   communicate with viewers.</li>
--   <li>The ciphers that CloudFront can use to encrypt the content that it
--   returns to viewers.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Security Policy</a> and <a>Supported
--   Protocols and Ciphers Between Viewers and CloudFront</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   On the CloudFront console, this setting is called <b>Security
--   Policy</b>.
--   
--   When you’re using SNI only (you set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to
--   <tt>sni-only</tt>), you must specify <tt>TLSv1</tt> or higher.
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt> (you set
--   <tt>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</tt> to <tt>true</tt>), CloudFront
--   automatically sets the security policy to <tt>TLSv1</tt> regardless of
--   the value that you set here.
--   
--   <a>$sel:certificate:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_certificate</a> - This field is deprecated. Use
--   one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   <a>$sel:iAMCertificateId:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_iAMCertificateId</a> - If the distribution uses
--   <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS
--   certificate is stored in <a>Identity and Access Management (IAM)</a>,
--   provide the ID of the IAM certificate.
--   
--   If you specify an IAM certificate ID, you must also specify values for
--   <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:cloudFrontDefaultCertificate:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_cloudFrontDefaultCertificate</a> - If the
--   distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, set this field to
--   <tt>true</tt>.
--   
--   If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), set this field to <tt>false</tt> and specify values for the
--   following fields:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>ACMCertificateArn</tt> or <tt>IAMCertificateId</tt> (specify a
--   value for one, not both)</li>
--   <li><pre>MinimumProtocolVersion</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>SSLSupportMethod</pre></li>
--   </ul>
newViewerCertificate :: ViewerCertificate

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), specify which viewers the distribution accepts HTTPS
--   connections from.
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>sni-only</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections
--   from only viewers that support <a>server name indication (SNI)</a>.
--   This is recommended. Most browsers and clients support SNI.</li>
--   <li><tt>vip</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections from all
--   viewers including those that don’t support SNI. This is not
--   recommended, and results in additional monthly charges from
--   CloudFront.</li>
--   <li><tt>static-ip</tt> - Do not specify this value unless your
--   distribution has been enabled for this feature by the CloudFront team.
--   If you have a use case that requires static IP addresses for a
--   distribution, contact CloudFront through the <a>Amazon Web Services
--   Support Center</a>.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, don’t set a value for this
--   field.
viewerCertificate_sSLSupportMethod :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe SSLSupportMethod)

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS certificate is stored in <a>Certificate
--   Manager (ACM)</a>, provide the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the ACM
--   certificate. CloudFront only supports ACM certificates in the US East
--   (N. Virginia) Region (<tt>us-east-1</tt>).
--   
--   If you specify an ACM certificate ARN, you must also specify values
--   for <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
viewerCertificate_aCMCertificateArn :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe Text)

-- | This field is deprecated. Use one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
viewerCertificate_certificateSource :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe CertificateSource)

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), specify the security policy that you want CloudFront to use
--   for HTTPS connections with viewers. The security policy determines two
--   settings:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The minimum SSL/TLS protocol that CloudFront can use to
--   communicate with viewers.</li>
--   <li>The ciphers that CloudFront can use to encrypt the content that it
--   returns to viewers.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Security Policy</a> and <a>Supported
--   Protocols and Ciphers Between Viewers and CloudFront</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   On the CloudFront console, this setting is called <b>Security
--   Policy</b>.
--   
--   When you’re using SNI only (you set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to
--   <tt>sni-only</tt>), you must specify <tt>TLSv1</tt> or higher.
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt> (you set
--   <tt>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</tt> to <tt>true</tt>), CloudFront
--   automatically sets the security policy to <tt>TLSv1</tt> regardless of
--   the value that you set here.
viewerCertificate_minimumProtocolVersion :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe MinimumProtocolVersion)

-- | This field is deprecated. Use one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
viewerCertificate_certificate :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe Text)

-- | If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS certificate is stored in <a>Identity and
--   Access Management (IAM)</a>, provide the ID of the IAM certificate.
--   
--   If you specify an IAM certificate ID, you must also specify values for
--   <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
viewerCertificate_iAMCertificateId :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe Text)

-- | If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, set this field to
--   <tt>true</tt>.
--   
--   If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), set this field to <tt>false</tt> and specify values for the
--   following fields:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>ACMCertificateArn</tt> or <tt>IAMCertificateId</tt> (specify a
--   value for one, not both)</li>
--   <li><pre>MinimumProtocolVersion</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>SSLSupportMethod</pre></li>
--   </ul>
viewerCertificate_cloudFrontDefaultCertificate :: Lens' ViewerCertificate (Maybe Bool)


-- | Tests a CloudFront function.
--   
--   To test a function, you provide an <i>event object</i> that represents
--   an HTTP request or response that your CloudFront distribution could
--   receive in production. CloudFront runs the function, passing it the
--   event object that you provided, and returns the function’s result (the
--   modified event object) in the response. The response also contains
--   function logs and error messages, if any exist. For more information
--   about testing functions, see <a>Testing functions</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   To test a function, you provide the function’s name and version
--   (<tt>ETag</tt> value) along with the event object. To get the
--   function’s name and version, you can use <tt>ListFunctions</tt> and
--   <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.TestFunction

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newTestFunction</a> smart constructor.
data TestFunction
TestFunction' :: Maybe FunctionStage -> Text -> Text -> Sensitive Base64 -> TestFunction

-- | The stage of the function that you are testing, either
--   <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or <tt>LIVE</tt>.
[$sel:stage:TestFunction'] :: TestFunction -> Maybe FunctionStage

-- | The name of the function that you are testing.
[$sel:name:TestFunction'] :: TestFunction -> Text

-- | The current version (<tt>ETag</tt> value) of the function that you are
--   testing, which you can get using <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.
[$sel:ifMatch:TestFunction'] :: TestFunction -> Text

-- | The event object to test the function with. For more information about
--   the structure of the event object, see <a>Testing functions</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:eventObject:TestFunction'] :: TestFunction -> Sensitive Base64

-- | Create a value of <a>TestFunction</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:stage:TestFunction'</a>, <a>testFunction_stage</a> - The stage
--   of the function that you are testing, either <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or
--   <tt>LIVE</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:name:TestFunction'</a>, <a>testFunction_name</a> - The name of
--   the function that you are testing.
--   
--   <a>$sel:ifMatch:TestFunction'</a>, <a>testFunction_ifMatch</a> - The
--   current version (<tt>ETag</tt> value) of the function that you are
--   testing, which you can get using <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:eventObject:TestFunction'</a>, <a>testFunction_eventObject</a>
--   - The event object to test the function with. For more information
--   about the structure of the event object, see <a>Testing functions</a>
--   in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.-- -- <i>Note:</i>
--   This <tt>Lens</tt> automatically encodes and decodes Base64 data. --
--   The underlying isomorphism will encode to Base64 representation during
--   -- serialisation, and decode from Base64 representation during
--   deserialisation. -- This <tt>Lens</tt> accepts and returns only raw
--   unencoded data.
newTestFunction :: Text -> Text -> ByteString -> TestFunction

-- | The stage of the function that you are testing, either
--   <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or <tt>LIVE</tt>.
testFunction_stage :: Lens' TestFunction (Maybe FunctionStage)

-- | The name of the function that you are testing.
testFunction_name :: Lens' TestFunction Text

-- | The current version (<tt>ETag</tt> value) of the function that you are
--   testing, which you can get using <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.
testFunction_ifMatch :: Lens' TestFunction Text

-- | The event object to test the function with. For more information about
--   the structure of the event object, see <a>Testing functions</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.-- -- <i>Note:</i> This
--   <tt>Lens</tt> automatically encodes and decodes Base64 data. -- The
--   underlying isomorphism will encode to Base64 representation during --
--   serialisation, and decode from Base64 representation during
--   deserialisation. -- This <tt>Lens</tt> accepts and returns only raw
--   unencoded data.
testFunction_eventObject :: Lens' TestFunction ByteString

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newTestFunctionResponse</a> smart constructor.
data TestFunctionResponse
TestFunctionResponse' :: Maybe TestResult -> Int -> TestFunctionResponse

-- | An object that represents the result of running the function with the
--   provided event object.
[$sel:testResult:TestFunctionResponse'] :: TestFunctionResponse -> Maybe TestResult

-- | The response's http status code.
[$sel:httpStatus:TestFunctionResponse'] :: TestFunctionResponse -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>TestFunctionResponse</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:testResult:TestFunctionResponse'</a>,
--   <a>testFunctionResponse_testResult</a> - An object that represents the
--   result of running the function with the provided event object.
--   
--   <a>$sel:httpStatus:TestFunctionResponse'</a>,
--   <a>testFunctionResponse_httpStatus</a> - The response's http status
--   code.
newTestFunctionResponse :: Int -> TestFunctionResponse

-- | An object that represents the result of running the function with the
--   provided event object.
testFunctionResponse_testResult :: Lens' TestFunctionResponse (Maybe TestResult)

-- | The response's http status code.
testFunctionResponse_httpStatus :: Lens' TestFunctionResponse Int

instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.TestFunction.TestFunction

-- | Publishes a CloudFront function by copying the function code from the
--   <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> stage to <tt>LIVE</tt>. This automatically
--   updates all cache behaviors that are using this function to use the
--   newly published copy in the <tt>LIVE</tt> stage.
--   
--   When a function is published to the <tt>LIVE</tt> stage, you can
--   attach the function to a distribution’s cache behavior, using the
--   function’s Amazon Resource Name (ARN).
--   
--   To publish a function, you must provide the function’s name and
--   version (<tt>ETag</tt> value). To get these values, you can use
--   <tt>ListFunctions</tt> and <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.PublishFunction

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newPublishFunction</a> smart constructor.
data PublishFunction
PublishFunction' :: Text -> Text -> PublishFunction

-- | The name of the function that you are publishing.
[$sel:name:PublishFunction'] :: PublishFunction -> Text

-- | The current version (<tt>ETag</tt> value) of the function that you are
--   publishing, which you can get using <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.
[$sel:ifMatch:PublishFunction'] :: PublishFunction -> Text

-- | Create a value of <a>PublishFunction</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:name:PublishFunction'</a>, <a>publishFunction_name</a> - The
--   name of the function that you are publishing.
--   
--   <a>$sel:ifMatch:PublishFunction'</a>, <a>publishFunction_ifMatch</a> -
--   The current version (<tt>ETag</tt> value) of the function that you are
--   publishing, which you can get using <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.
newPublishFunction :: Text -> Text -> PublishFunction

-- | The name of the function that you are publishing.
publishFunction_name :: Lens' PublishFunction Text

-- | The current version (<tt>ETag</tt> value) of the function that you are
--   publishing, which you can get using <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.
publishFunction_ifMatch :: Lens' PublishFunction Text

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newPublishFunctionResponse</a> smart constructor.
data PublishFunctionResponse
PublishFunctionResponse' :: Maybe FunctionSummary -> Int -> PublishFunctionResponse

-- | Contains configuration information and metadata about a CloudFront
--   function.
[$sel:functionSummary:PublishFunctionResponse'] :: PublishFunctionResponse -> Maybe FunctionSummary

-- | The response's http status code.
[$sel:httpStatus:PublishFunctionResponse'] :: PublishFunctionResponse -> Int

-- | Create a value of <a>PublishFunctionResponse</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:functionSummary:PublishFunctionResponse'</a>,
--   <a>publishFunctionResponse_functionSummary</a> - Contains
--   configuration information and metadata about a CloudFront function.
--   
--   <a>$sel:httpStatus:PublishFunctionResponse'</a>,
--   <a>publishFunctionResponse_httpStatus</a> - The response's http status
--   code.
newPublishFunctionResponse :: Int -> PublishFunctionResponse

-- | Contains configuration information and metadata about a CloudFront
--   function.
publishFunctionResponse_functionSummary :: Lens' PublishFunctionResponse (Maybe FunctionSummary)

-- | The response's http status code.
publishFunctionResponse_httpStatus :: Lens' PublishFunctionResponse Int
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.PublishFunction.PublishFunction
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.PublishFunction.PublishFunction
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.PublishFunction.PublishFunction
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.PublishFunction.PublishFunction
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.PublishFunction.PublishFunctionResponse
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.PublishFunction.PublishFunctionResponse
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.PublishFunction.PublishFunctionResponse
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.PublishFunction.PublishFunctionResponse

-- | List streaming distributions.
--   
--   This operation returns paginated results.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.ListStreamingDistributions

-- | The request to list your streaming distributions.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newListStreamingDistributions</a> smart constructor.
data ListStreamingDistributions

--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--

--   for the <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter.

--   <a>$sel:maxItems:ListStreamingDistributions'</a>,

--   provided for the <tt>MaxItems</tt> request parameter.

-- | Lists invalidation batches.
--   
--   This operation returns paginated results.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.ListInvalidations

-- | The request to list invalidations.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newListInvalidations</a> smart constructor.
data ListInvalidations
ListInvalidations' :: Maybe Text -> Maybe Text -> Text -> ListInvalidations

-- | Use this parameter when paginating results to indicate where to begin
--   in your list of invalidation batches. Because the results are returned
--   in decreasing order from most recent to oldest, the most recent
--   results are on the first page, the second page will contain earlier
--   results, and so on. To get the next page of results, set
--   <tt>Marker</tt> to the value of the <tt>NextMarker</tt> from the
--   current page's response. This value is the same as the ID of the last
--   invalidation batch on that page.

--   response body.

--   <a>listInvalidations_distributionId</a> - The distribution's ID.

-- | Gets a list of all CloudFront functions in your account.
--   
--   You can optionally apply a filter to return only the functions that
--   are in the specified stage, either <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or
--   <tt>LIVE</tt>.
--   
--   You can optionally specify the maximum number of items to receive in
--   the response. If the total number of items in the list exceeds the
--   maximum that you specify, or the default maximum, the response is
--   paginated. To get the next page of items, send a subsequent request
--   that specifies the <tt>NextMarker</tt> value from the current response
--   as the <tt>Marker</tt> value in the subsequent request.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.ListFunctions

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newListFunctions</a> smart constructor.
data ListFunctions
ListFunctions' :: Maybe FunctionStage -> Maybe Text -> Maybe Text -> ListFunctions

-- | An optional filter to return only the functions that are in the
--   specified stage, either <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or <tt>LIVE</tt>.
[$sel:stage:ListFunctions'] :: ListFunctions -> Maybe FunctionStage

-- | Use this field when paginating results to indicate where to begin in
--   your list of functions. The response includes functions in the list
--   that occur after the marker. To get the next page of the list, set
--   this field’s value to the value of <tt>NextMarker</tt> from the
--   current page’s response.
[$sel:marker:ListFunctions'] :: ListFunctions -> Maybe Text

-- | The maximum number of functions that you want in the response.
[$sel:maxItems:ListFunctions'] :: ListFunctions -> Maybe Text

-- | Create a value of <a>ListFunctions</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:stage:ListFunctions'</a>, <a>listFunctions_stage</a> - An
--   optional filter to return only the functions that are in the specified
--   stage, either <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or <tt>LIVE</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:marker:ListFunctions'</a>, <a>listFunctions_marker</a> - Use
--   this field when paginating results to indicate where to begin in your
--   list of functions. The response includes functions in the list that
--   occur after the marker. To get the next page of the list, set this
--   field’s value to the value of <tt>NextMarker</tt> from the current
--   page’s response.
--   
--   <a>$sel:maxItems:ListFunctions'</a>, <a>listFunctions_maxItems</a> -
--   The maximum number of functions that you want in the response.
newListFunctions :: ListFunctions

-- | An optional filter to return only the functions that are in the
--   specified stage, either <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or <tt>LIVE</tt>.
listFunctions_stage :: Lens' ListFunctions (Maybe FunctionStage)

-- | Use this field when paginating results to indicate where to begin in

--   current page’s response.

--   WAF web ACL.
--

--   satisfy the request, the response includes a <tt>NextMarker</tt>
--   element. To get the next page of results, submit another request. For
--   the value of <tt>Marker</tt>, specify the value of <tt>NextMarker</tt>
--   from the last response. (For the first request, omit <tt>Marker</tt>.)
[$sel:marker:ListDistributionsByWebACLId'] :: ListDistributionsByWebACLId -> Maybe Text

-- | The maximum number of distributions that you want CloudFront to return
--   in the response body. The maximum and default values are both 100.

--   distributions. If you specify "null" for the ID, the request returns a
--   list of the distributions that aren't associated with a web ACL.

--   response includes a <tt>NextMarker</tt> element. To get the next page
--   of results, submit another request. For the value of <tt>Marker</tt>,
--   specify the value of <tt>NextMarker</tt> from the last response. (For
--   the first request, omit <tt>Marker</tt>.)

--   <a>$sel:maxItems:ListDistributionsByWebACLId'</a>,

-- | Gets a list of aliases (also called CNAMEs or alternate domain names)
--   that conflict or overlap with the provided alias, and the associated
--   CloudFront distributions and Amazon Web Services accounts for each
--   conflicting alias. In the returned list, the distribution and account
--   IDs are partially hidden, which allows you to identify the
--   distributions and accounts that you own, but helps to protect the
--   information of ones that you don’t own.
--   
--   Use this operation to find aliases that are in use in CloudFront that
--   conflict or overlap with the provided alias. For example, if you
--   provide <tt>www.example.com</tt> as input, the returned list can
--   include <tt>www.example.com</tt> and the overlapping wildcard
--   alternate domain name (<tt>*.example.com</tt>), if they exist. If you
--   provide <tt>*.example.com</tt> as input, the returned list can include
--   <tt>*.example.com</tt> and any alternate domain names covered by that
--   wildcard (for example, <tt>www.example.com</tt>,
--   <tt>test.example.com</tt>, <tt>dev.example.com</tt>, and so on), if
--   they exist.
--   
--   To list conflicting aliases, you provide the alias to search and the
--   ID of a distribution in your account that has an attached SSL/TLS
--   certificate that includes the provided alias. For more information,
--   including how to set up the distribution and certificate, see
--   <a>Moving an alternate domain name to a different distribution</a> in
--   the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   You can optionally specify the maximum number of items to receive in
--   the response. If the total number of items in the list exceeds the
--   maximum that you specify, or the default maximum, the response is
--   paginated. To get the next page of items, send a subsequent request
--   that specifies the <tt>NextMarker</tt> value from the current response
--   as the <tt>Marker</tt> value in the subsequent request.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.ListConflictingAliases

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newListConflictingAliases</a> smart constructor.
data ListConflictingAliases
ListConflictingAliases' :: Maybe Text -> Maybe Int -> Text -> Text -> ListConflictingAliases

-- | Use this field when paginating results to indicate where to begin in
--   the list of conflicting aliases. The response includes conflicting
--   aliases in the list that occur after the marker. To get the next page
--   of the list, set this field’s value to the value of
--   <tt>NextMarker</tt> from the current page’s response.
[$sel:marker:ListConflictingAliases'] :: ListConflictingAliases -> Maybe Text

-- | The maximum number of conflicting aliases that you want in the
--   response.
[$sel:maxItems:ListConflictingAliases'] :: ListConflictingAliases -> Maybe Int

-- | The ID of a distribution in your account that has an attached SSL/TLS
--   certificate that includes the provided alias.
[$sel:distributionId:ListConflictingAliases'] :: ListConflictingAliases -> Text

-- | The alias (also called a CNAME) to search for conflicting aliases.

-- | Gets a list of cache policies.
--   
--   You can optionally apply a filter to return only the managed policies
--   created by Amazon Web Services, or only the custom policies created in
--   your account.
--   
--   You can optionally specify the maximum number of items to receive in
--   the response. If the total number of items in the list exceeds the
--   maximum that you specify, or the default maximum, the response is
--   paginated. To get the next page of items, send a subsequent request
--   that specifies the <tt>NextMarker</tt> value from the current response
--   as the <tt>Marker</tt> value in the subsequent request.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.ListCachePolicies

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newListCachePolicies</a> smart constructor.
data ListCachePolicies
ListCachePolicies' :: Maybe Text -> Maybe Text -> Maybe CachePolicyType -> ListCachePolicies

-- | Use this field when paginating results to indicate where to begin in
--   your list of cache policies. The response includes cache policies in
--   the list that occur after the marker. To get the next page of the
--   list, set this field’s value to the value of <tt>NextMarker</tt> from
--   the current page’s response.
[$sel:marker:ListCachePolicies'] :: ListCachePolicies -> Maybe Text

-- | The maximum number of cache policies that you want in the response.
[$sel:maxItems:ListCachePolicies'] :: ListCachePolicies -> Maybe Text

-- | A filter to return only the specified kinds of cache policies. Valid
--   values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>managed</tt> – Returns only the managed policies created by
--   Amazon Web Services.</li>
--   <li><tt>custom</tt> – Returns only the custom policies created in your
--   account.</li>
--   </ul>

--   omitted.

-- | Gets the code of a CloudFront function. To get configuration
--   information and metadata about a function, use
--   <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.
--   
--   To get a function’s code, you must provide the function’s name and
--   stage. To get these values, you can use <tt>ListFunctions</tt>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.GetFunction

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newGetFunction</a> smart constructor.
data GetFunction
GetFunction' :: Maybe FunctionStage -> Text -> GetFunction

-- | The function’s stage, either <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or <tt>LIVE</tt>.
[$sel:stage:GetFunction'] :: GetFunction -> Maybe FunctionStage

-- | The name of the function whose code you are getting.
[$sel:name:GetFunction'] :: GetFunction -> Text

-- | Create a value of <a>GetFunction</a> with all optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:stage:GetFunction'</a>, <a>getFunction_stage</a> - The
--   function’s stage, either <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or <tt>LIVE</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:name:GetFunction'</a>, <a>getFunction_name</a> - The name of
--   the function whose code you are getting.
newGetFunction :: Text -> GetFunction

-- | The function’s stage, either <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> or <tt>LIVE</tt>.
getFunction_stage :: Lens' GetFunction (Maybe FunctionStage)

-- | The name of the function whose code you are getting.
getFunction_name :: Lens' GetFunction Text

--   function.
[$sel:eTag:GetFunctionResponse'] :: GetFunctionResponse -> Maybe Text

-- | The content type (media type) of the response.
[$sel:contentType:GetFunctionResponse'] :: GetFunctionResponse -> Maybe Text

-- | The response's http status code.

-- | Create a value of <a>GetFunctionResponse</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.

-- | Gets a cache policy configuration.
--   
--   To get a cache policy configuration, you must provide the policy’s
--   identifier. If the cache policy is attached to a distribution’s cache
--   behavior, you can get the policy’s identifier using
--   <tt>ListDistributions</tt> or <tt>GetDistribution</tt>. If the cache
--   policy is not attached to a cache behavior, you can get the identifier
--   using <tt>ListCachePolicies</tt>.

-- | Gets a cache policy, including the following metadata:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The policy’s identifier.</li>
--   <li>The date and time when the policy was last modified.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   To get a cache policy, you must provide the policy’s identifier. If
--   the cache policy is attached to a distribution’s cache behavior, you
--   can get the policy’s identifier using <tt>ListDistributions</tt> or
--   <tt>GetDistribution</tt>. If the cache policy is not attached to a
--   cache behavior, you can get the identifier using
--   <tt>ListCachePolicies</tt>.

--   <tt>ListCachePolicies</tt>.

-- | Create a value of <a>GetCachePolicy</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.

-- | Delete a streaming distribution. To delete an RTMP distribution using
--   the CloudFront API, perform the following steps.
--   
--   <b>To delete an RTMP distribution using the CloudFront API</b>:
--   
--   <ol>
--   <li>Disable the RTMP distribution.</li>
--   <li>Submit a <tt>GET Streaming Distribution Config</tt> request to get
--   the current configuration and the <tt>Etag</tt> header for the
--   distribution.</li>
--   <li>Update the XML document that was returned in the response to your
--   <tt>GET Streaming Distribution Config</tt> request to change the value
--   of <tt>Enabled</tt> to <tt>false</tt>.</li>
--   <li>Submit a <tt>PUT Streaming Distribution Config</tt> request to
--   update the configuration for your distribution. In the request body,
--   include the XML document that you updated in Step 3. Then set the
--   value of the HTTP <tt>If-Match</tt> header to the value of the
--   <tt>ETag</tt> header that CloudFront returned when you submitted the
--   <tt>GET Streaming Distribution Config</tt> request in Step 2.</li>
--   <li>Review the response to the <tt>PUT Streaming Distribution
--   Config</tt> request to confirm that the distribution was successfully
--   disabled.</li>
--   <li>Submit a <tt>GET Streaming Distribution Config</tt> request to
--   confirm that your changes have propagated. When propagation is
--   complete, the value of <tt>Status</tt> is <tt>Deployed</tt>.</li>
--   <li>Submit a <tt>DELETE Streaming Distribution</tt> request. Set the
--   value of the HTTP <tt>If-Match</tt> header to the value of the
--   <tt>ETag</tt> header that CloudFront returned when you submitted the
--   <tt>GET Streaming Distribution Config</tt> request in Step 2.</li>
--   <li>Review the response to your <tt>DELETE Streaming Distribution</tt>
--   request to confirm that the distribution was successfully
--   deleted.</li>
--   </ol>
--   
--   For information about deleting a distribution using the CloudFront
--   console, see <a>Deleting a Distribution</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteStreamingDistribution

-- | The request to delete a streaming distribution.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newDeleteStreamingDistribution</a> smart constructor.
data DeleteStreamingDistribution
DeleteStreamingDistribution' :: Maybe Text -> Text -> DeleteStreamingDistribution

-- | The value of the <tt>ETag</tt> header that you received when you
--   disabled the streaming distribution. For example:
--   <tt>E2QWRUHAPOMQZL</tt>.
[$sel:ifMatch:DeleteStreamingDistribution'] :: DeleteStreamingDistribution -> Maybe Text

-- | The distribution ID.
[$sel:id:DeleteStreamingDistribution'] :: DeleteStreamingDistribution -> Text

-- | Create a value of <a>DeleteStreamingDistribution</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:ifMatch:DeleteStreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>deleteStreamingDistribution_ifMatch</a> - The value of the
--   <tt>ETag</tt> header that you received when you disabled the streaming
--   distribution. For example: <tt>E2QWRUHAPOMQZL</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:DeleteStreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>deleteStreamingDistribution_id</a> - The distribution ID.
newDeleteStreamingDistribution :: Text -> DeleteStreamingDistribution

-- | The value of the <tt>ETag</tt> header that you received when you
--   disabled the streaming distribution. For example:
--   <tt>E2QWRUHAPOMQZL</tt>.
deleteStreamingDistribution_ifMatch :: Lens' DeleteStreamingDistribution (Maybe Text)

-- | The distribution ID.
deleteStreamingDistribution_id :: Lens' DeleteStreamingDistribution Text

--   constructor.
data DeleteStreamingDistributionResponse
DeleteStreamingDistributionResponse' :: DeleteStreamingDistributionResponse

--   optional fields omitted.

--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.

--   provide at least one. If you provide both, CloudFront uses the name to

-- | Deletes a key group.
--   
--   You cannot delete a key group that is referenced in a cache behavior.
--   First update your distributions to remove the key group from all cache
--   behaviors, then delete the key group.
--   
--   To delete a key group, you must provide the key group’s identifier and
--   version. To get these values, use <tt>ListKeyGroups</tt> followed by
--   <tt>GetKeyGroup</tt> or <tt>GetKeyGroupConfig</tt>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteKeyGroup

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newDeleteKeyGroup</a> smart constructor.

DeleteKeyGroup' :: Maybe Text -> Text -> DeleteKeyGroup

-- | The version of the key group that you are deleting. The version is the
--   key group’s <tt>ETag</tt> value. To get the <tt>ETag</tt>, use
--   <tt>GetKeyGroup</tt> or <tt>GetKeyGroupConfig</tt>.
[$sel:ifMatch:DeleteKeyGroup'] :: DeleteKeyGroup -> Maybe Text

-- | The identifier of the key group that you are deleting. To get the
--   identifier, use <tt>ListKeyGroups</tt>.
[$sel:id:DeleteKeyGroup'] :: DeleteKeyGroup -> Text

--   omitted.

--   fields.

--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:ifMatch:DeleteKeyGroup'</a>, <a>deleteKeyGroup_ifMatch</a> -
--   The version of the key group that you are deleting. The version is the
--   key group’s <tt>ETag</tt> value. To get the <tt>ETag</tt>, use
--   <tt>GetKeyGroup</tt> or <tt>GetKeyGroupConfig</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:DeleteKeyGroup'</a>, <a>deleteKeyGroup_id</a> - The
--   identifier of the key group that you are deleting. To get the
--   identifier, use <tt>ListKeyGroups</tt>.

-- | The version of the key group that you are deleting. The version is the

-- | Deletes a CloudFront function.
--   
--   You cannot delete a function if it’s associated with a cache behavior.
--   First, update your distributions to remove the function association
--   from all cache behaviors, then delete the function.
--   
--   To delete a function, you must provide the function’s name and version
--   (<tt>ETag</tt> value). To get these values, you can use
--   <tt>ListFunctions</tt> and <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteFunction

--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:

--   name of the function that you are deleting.

-- | Delete a distribution.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteDistribution

-- | This action deletes a web distribution. To delete a web distribution
--   using the CloudFront API, perform the following steps.
--   
--   <b>To delete a web distribution using the CloudFront API:</b>
--   
--   <ol>
--   <li>Disable the web distribution</li>
--   <li>Submit a <tt>GET Distribution Config</tt> request to get the
--   current configuration and the <tt>Etag</tt> header for the
--   distribution.</li>
--   <li>Update the XML document that was returned in the response to your
--   <tt>GET Distribution Config</tt> request to change the value of
--   <tt>Enabled</tt> to <tt>false</tt>.</li>
--   <li>Submit a <tt>PUT Distribution Config</tt> request to update the
--   configuration for your distribution. In the request body, include the
--   XML document that you updated in Step 3. Set the value of the HTTP
--   <tt>If-Match</tt> header to the value of the <tt>ETag</tt> header that
--   CloudFront returned when you submitted the <tt>GET Distribution
--   Config</tt> request in Step 2.</li>
--   <li>Review the response to the <tt>PUT Distribution Config</tt>
--   request to confirm that the distribution was successfully
--   disabled.</li>
--   <li>Submit a <tt>GET Distribution</tt> request to confirm that your
--   changes have propagated. When propagation is complete, the value of
--   <tt>Status</tt> is <tt>Deployed</tt>.</li>
--   <li>Submit a <tt>DELETE Distribution</tt> request. Set the value of
--   the HTTP <tt>If-Match</tt> header to the value of the <tt>ETag</tt>
--   header that CloudFront returned when you submitted the <tt>GET
--   Distribution Config</tt> request in Step 6.</li>
--   <li>Review the response to your <tt>DELETE Distribution</tt> request
--   to confirm that the distribution was successfully deleted.</li>
--   </ol>
--   
--   For information about deleting a distribution using the CloudFront
--   console, see <a>Deleting a Distribution</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newDeleteDistribution</a> smart constructor.
data DeleteDistribution
DeleteDistribution' :: Maybe Text -> Text -> DeleteDistribution

-- | The value of the <tt>ETag</tt> header that you received when you
--   disabled the distribution. For example: <tt>E2QWRUHAPOMQZL</tt>.
[$sel:ifMatch:DeleteDistribution'] :: DeleteDistribution -> Maybe Text

-- | The distribution ID.
[$sel:id:DeleteDistribution'] :: DeleteDistribution -> Text

-- | Create a value of <a>DeleteDistribution</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:ifMatch:DeleteDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>deleteDistribution_ifMatch</a> - The value of the <tt>ETag</tt>
--   header that you received when you disabled the distribution. For
--   example: <tt>E2QWRUHAPOMQZL</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:DeleteDistribution'</a>, <a>deleteDistribution_id</a> - The
--   distribution ID.
newDeleteDistribution :: Text -> DeleteDistribution

-- | The value of the <tt>ETag</tt> header that you received when you
--   disabled the distribution. For example: <tt>E2QWRUHAPOMQZL</tt>.
deleteDistribution_ifMatch :: Lens' DeleteDistribution (Maybe Text)

-- | The distribution ID.
deleteDistribution_id :: Lens' DeleteDistribution Text

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newDeleteDistributionResponse</a> smart constructor.
data DeleteDistributionResponse
DeleteDistributionResponse' :: DeleteDistributionResponse

-- | Create a value of <a>DeleteDistributionResponse</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
newDeleteDistributionResponse :: DeleteDistributionResponse
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteDistribution.DeleteDistribution
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteDistribution.DeleteDistribution
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteDistribution.DeleteDistribution
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteDistribution.DeleteDistribution
instance GHC.Generics.Generic Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteDistribution.DeleteDistributionResponse
instance GHC.Show.Show Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteDistribution.DeleteDistributionResponse
instance GHC.Read.Read Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteDistribution.DeleteDistributionResponse
instance GHC.Classes.Eq Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteDistribution.DeleteDistributionResponse
instance Network.AWS.Types.AWSRequest Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteDistribution.DeleteDistribution
instance Control.DeepSeq.NFData Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteDistribution.DeleteDistributionResponse
instance Data.Hashable.Class.Hashable Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteDistribution.DeleteDistribution

-- | Deletes a cache policy.
--   
--   You cannot delete a cache policy if it’s attached to a cache behavior.
--   First update your distributions to remove the cache policy from all
--   cache behaviors, then delete the cache policy.
--   
--   To delete a cache policy, you must provide the policy’s identifier and
--   version. To get these values, you can use <tt>ListCachePolicies</tt>
--   or <tt>GetCachePolicy</tt>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.DeleteCachePolicy

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newDeleteCachePolicy</a> smart constructor.

-- | Creates an origin request policy.
--   
--   After you create an origin request policy, you can attach it to one or
--   more cache behaviors. When it’s attached to a cache behavior, the
--   origin request policy determines the values that CloudFront includes
--   in requests that it sends to the origin. Each request that CloudFront
--   sends to the origin includes the following:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The request body and the URL path (without the domain name) from
--   the viewer request.</li>
--   <li>The headers that CloudFront automatically includes in every origin
--   request, including <tt>Host</tt>, <tt>User-Agent</tt>, and
--   <tt>X-Amz-Cf-Id</tt>.</li>
--   <li>All HTTP headers, cookies, and URL query strings that are
--   specified in the cache policy or the origin request policy. These can
--   include items from the viewer request and, in the case of headers,
--   additional ones that are added by CloudFront.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   CloudFront sends a request when it can’t find a valid object in its
--   cache that matches the request. If you want to send values to the
--   origin and also include them in the cache key, use
--   <tt>CachePolicy</tt>.
--   
--   For more information about origin request policies, see <a>Controlling
--   origin requests</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.CreateOriginRequestPolicy

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newCreateOriginRequestPolicy</a> smart constructor.
data CreateOriginRequestPolicy
CreateOriginRequestPolicy' :: OriginRequestPolicyConfig -> CreateOriginRequestPolicy

-- | An origin request policy configuration.
[$sel:originRequestPolicyConfig:CreateOriginRequestPolicy'] :: CreateOriginRequestPolicy -> OriginRequestPolicyConfig

-- | Create a value of <a>CreateOriginRequestPolicy</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:originRequestPolicyConfig:CreateOriginRequestPolicy'</a>,
--   <a>createOriginRequestPolicy_originRequestPolicyConfig</a> - An origin
--   request policy configuration.
newCreateOriginRequestPolicy :: OriginRequestPolicyConfig -> CreateOriginRequestPolicy

-- | An origin request policy configuration.
createOriginRequestPolicy_originRequestPolicyConfig :: Lens' CreateOriginRequestPolicy OriginRequestPolicyConfig

-- | Creates a key group that you can use with <a>CloudFront signed URLs
--   and signed cookies</a>.
--   
--   To create a key group, you must specify at least one public key for
--   the key group. After you create a key group, you can reference it from
--   one or more cache behaviors. When you reference a key group in a cache
--   behavior, CloudFront requires signed URLs or signed cookies for all
--   requests that match the cache behavior. The URLs or cookies must be
--   signed with a private key whose corresponding public key is in the key
--   group. The signed URL or cookie contains information about which
--   public key CloudFront should use to verify the signature. For more
--   information, see <a>Serving private content</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.CreateKeyGroup

-- | Creates a CloudFront function.
--   
--   To create a function, you provide the function code and some
--   configuration information about the function. The response contains an
--   Amazon Resource Name (ARN) that uniquely identifies the function.
--   
--   When you create a function, it’s in the <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> stage. In
--   this stage, you can test the function with <tt>TestFunction</tt>, and
--   update it with <tt>UpdateFunction</tt>.
--   
--   When you’re ready to use your function with a CloudFront distribution,
--   use <tt>PublishFunction</tt> to copy the function from the
--   <tt>DEVELOPMENT</tt> stage to <tt>LIVE</tt>. When it’s live, you can
--   attach the function to a distribution’s cache behavior, using the
--   function’s ARN.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.CreateFunction

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newCreateFunction</a> smart constructor.
data CreateFunction
CreateFunction' :: Text -> FunctionConfig -> Sensitive Base64 -> CreateFunction

-- | Configuration information about the function, including an optional
--   comment and the function’s runtime.

-- | The function code. For more information about writing a CloudFront
--   function, see <a>Writing function code for CloudFront Functions</a> in
--   the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:functionCode:CreateFunction'] :: CreateFunction -> Sensitive Base64

-- | Create a value of <a>CreateFunction</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--

--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:

--   to identify the function.
--   
--   <a>$sel:functionConfig:CreateFunction'</a>,
--   <a>createFunction_functionConfig</a> - Configuration information about
--   the function, including an optional comment and the function’s
--   runtime.
--   
--   <a>$sel:functionCode:CreateFunction'</a>,
--   <a>createFunction_functionCode</a> - The function code. For more
--   information about writing a CloudFront function, see <a>Writing
--   function code for CloudFront Functions</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.-- -- <i>Note:</i> This <tt>Lens</tt>
--   automatically encodes and decodes Base64 data. -- The underlying
--   isomorphism will encode to Base64 representation during --

-- | Creates a new web distribution. You create a CloudFront distribution
--   to tell CloudFront where you want content to be delivered from, and
--   the details about how to track and manage content delivery. Send a
--   <tt>POST</tt> request to the <tt>/CloudFront API
--   version/distribution</tt>/<tt>distribution ID</tt> resource.

--   when you create a distribution. When you update your distribution by
--   using <a>UpdateDistribution</a>, follow the steps included in the
--   documentation to get the current configuration and then make your
--   updates. This helps to make sure that you include all of the required
--   fields. To view a summary, see <a>Required Fields for Create

-- | Creates a new origin access identity. If you're using Amazon S3 for
--   your origin, you can use an origin access identity to require users to
--   access your content using a CloudFront URL instead of the Amazon S3
--   URL. For more information about how to use origin access identities,
--   see <a>Serving Private Content through CloudFront</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.CreateCloudFrontOriginAccessIdentity

-- | The request to create a new origin access identity (OAI). An origin
--   access identity is a special CloudFront user that you can associate
--   with Amazon S3 origins, so that you can secure all or just some of
--   your Amazon S3 content. For more information, see <a>Restricting
--   Access to Amazon S3 Content by Using an Origin Access Identity</a> in
--   the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.

-- | Creates a cache policy.
--   
--   After you create a cache policy, you can attach it to one or more
--   cache behaviors. When it’s attached to a cache behavior, the cache
--   policy determines the following:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The values that CloudFront includes in the <i>cache key</i>. These
--   values can include HTTP headers, cookies, and URL query strings.
--   CloudFront uses the cache key to find an object in its cache that it
--   can return to the viewer.</li>
--   <li>The default, minimum, and maximum time to live (TTL) values that
--   you want objects to stay in the CloudFront cache.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   The headers, cookies, and query strings that are included in the cache
--   key are automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to
--   the origin. CloudFront sends a request when it can’t find an object in
--   its cache that matches the request’s cache key. If you want to send
--   values to the origin but <i>not</i> include them in the cache key, use
--   <tt>OriginRequestPolicy</tt>.
--   
--   For more information about cache policies, see <a>Controlling the
--   cache key</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.CreateCachePolicy

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newCreateCachePolicy</a> smart constructor.
data CreateCachePolicy
CreateCachePolicy' :: CachePolicyConfig -> CreateCachePolicy

-- | A cache policy configuration.
[$sel:cachePolicyConfig:CreateCachePolicy'] :: CreateCachePolicy -> CachePolicyConfig

-- | Create a value of <a>CreateCachePolicy</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:cachePolicyConfig:CreateCachePolicy'</a>,
--   <a>createCachePolicy_cachePolicyConfig</a> - A cache policy
--   configuration.
newCreateCachePolicy :: CachePolicyConfig -> CreateCachePolicy

-- | A cache policy configuration.
createCachePolicy_cachePolicyConfig :: Lens' CreateCachePolicy CachePolicyConfig

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newCreateCachePolicyResponse</a> smart constructor.
data CreateCachePolicyResponse

-- | Create a value of <a>CreateCachePolicyResponse</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.

--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.

--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:cachePolicy:CreateCachePolicyResponse'</a>,
--   <a>createCachePolicyResponse_cachePolicy</a> - A cache policy.
--   
--   <a>$sel:eTag:CreateCachePolicyResponse'</a>,
--   <a>createCachePolicyResponse_eTag</a> - The current version of the
--   cache policy.
--   
--   <a>$sel:location:CreateCachePolicyResponse'</a>,
--   <a>createCachePolicyResponse_location</a> - The fully qualified URI of
--   the cache policy just created.
--   
--   <a>$sel:httpStatus:CreateCachePolicyResponse'</a>,
--   <a>createCachePolicyResponse_httpStatus</a> - The response's http
--   status code.
newCreateCachePolicyResponse :: Int -> CreateCachePolicyResponse

createCachePolicyResponse_cachePolicy :: Lens' CreateCachePolicyResponse (Maybe CachePolicy)

createCachePolicyResponse_eTag :: Lens' CreateCachePolicyResponse (Maybe Text)

-- | Associates an alias (also known as a CNAME or an alternate domain
--   name) with a CloudFront distribution.
--   
--   With this operation you can move an alias that’s already in use on a
--   CloudFront distribution to a different distribution in one step. This
--   prevents the downtime that could occur if you first remove the alias
--   from one distribution and then separately add the alias to another
--   distribution.
--   
--   To use this operation to associate an alias with a distribution, you
--   provide the alias and the ID of the target distribution for the alias.
--   For more information, including how to set up the target distribution,
--   prerequisites that you must complete, and other restrictions, see
--   <a>Moving an alternate domain name to a different distribution</a> in
--   the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.AssociateAlias

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newAssociateAlias</a> smart constructor.
data AssociateAlias
AssociateAlias' :: Text -> Text -> AssociateAlias

-- | The ID of the distribution that you’re associating the alias with.
[$sel:targetDistributionId:AssociateAlias'] :: AssociateAlias -> Text

-- | The alias (also known as a CNAME) to add to the target distribution.
[$sel:alias:AssociateAlias'] :: AssociateAlias -> Text

-- | Create a value of <a>AssociateAlias</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:targetDistributionId:AssociateAlias'</a>,
--   <a>associateAlias_targetDistributionId</a> - The ID of the
--   distribution that you’re associating the alias with.
--   
--   <a>$sel:alias:AssociateAlias'</a>, <a>associateAlias_alias</a> - The
--   alias (also known as a CNAME) to add to the target distribution.
newAssociateAlias :: Text -> Text -> AssociateAlias

-- | The ID of the distribution that you’re associating the alias with.
associateAlias_targetDistributionId :: Lens' AssociateAlias Text

-- | The alias (also known as a CNAME) to add to the target distribution.
associateAlias_alias :: Lens' AssociateAlias Text

--   fields omitted.

--   fields.

-- | Updates a cache policy configuration.
--   
--   When you update a cache policy configuration, all the fields are
--   updated with the values provided in the request. You cannot update
--   some fields independent of others. To update a cache policy
--   configuration:
--   
--   <ol>
--   <li>Use <tt>GetCachePolicyConfig</tt> to get the current
--   configuration.</li>
--   <li>Locally modify the fields in the cache policy configuration that
--   you want to update.</li>
--   <li>Call <tt>UpdateCachePolicy</tt> by providing the entire cache
--   policy configuration, including the fields that you modified and those
--   that you didn’t.</li>
--   </ol>

-- | Updates the configuration for a web distribution.
--   
--   When you update a distribution, there are more required fields than
--   when you create a distribution. When you update your distribution by
--   using this API action, follow the steps here to get the current
--   configuration and then make your updates, to make sure that you
--   include all of the required fields. To view a summary, see <a>Required
--   Fields for Create Distribution and Update Distribution</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   The update process includes getting the current distribution
--   configuration, updating the XML document that is returned to make your
--   changes, and then submitting an <tt>UpdateDistribution</tt> request to
--   make the updates.
--   
--   For information about updating a distribution using the CloudFront
--   console instead, see <a>Creating a Distribution</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <b>To update a web distribution using the CloudFront API</b>
--   
--   <ol>
--   <li>Submit a <a>GetDistributionConfig</a> request to get the current
--   configuration and an <tt>Etag</tt> header for the distribution.If you
--   update the distribution again, you must get a new <tt>Etag</tt>
--   header.</li>
--   <li>Update the XML document that was returned in the response to your
--   <tt>GetDistributionConfig</tt> request to include your changes.When
--   you edit the XML file, be aware of the following:<ul><li>You must
--   strip out the ETag parameter that is returned.</li><li>Additional
--   fields are required when you update a distribution. There may be
--   fields included in the XML file for features that you haven't
--   configured for your distribution. This is expected and required to
--   successfully update the distribution.</li><li>You can't change the
--   value of <tt>CallerReference</tt>. If you try to change this value,
--   CloudFront returns an <tt>IllegalUpdate</tt> error.</li><li>The new
--   configuration replaces the existing configuration; the values that you
--   specify in an <tt>UpdateDistribution</tt> request are not merged into
--   your existing configuration. When you add, delete, or replace values
--   in an element that allows multiple values (for example,
--   <tt>CNAME</tt>), you must specify all of the values that you want to
--   appear in the updated distribution. In addition, you must update the
--   corresponding <tt>Quantity</tt> element.</li></ul></li>
--   <li>Submit an <tt>UpdateDistribution</tt> request to update the
--   configuration for your distribution:<ul><li>In the request body,
--   include the XML document that you updated in Step 2. The request body
--   must include an XML document with a <tt>DistributionConfig</tt>
--   element.</li><li>Set the value of the HTTP <tt>If-Match</tt> header to
--   the value of the <tt>ETag</tt> header that CloudFront returned when
--   you submitted the <tt>GetDistributionConfig</tt> request in Step
--   1.</li></ul></li>
--   <li>Review the response to the <tt>UpdateDistribution</tt> request to
--   confirm that the configuration was successfully updated.</li>
--   <li>Optional: Submit a <a>GetDistribution</a> request to confirm that
--   your changes have propagated. When propagation is complete, the value
--   of <tt>Status</tt> is <tt>Deployed</tt>.</li>
--   </ol>
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.UpdateDistribution

-- | The request to update a distribution.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newUpdateDistribution</a> smart constructor.
data UpdateDistribution
UpdateDistribution' :: Maybe Text -> DistributionConfig -> Text -> UpdateDistribution

-- | Updates a CloudFront function.
--   
--   You can update a function’s code or the comment that describes the
--   function. You cannot update a function’s name.
--   
--   To update a function, you provide the function’s name and version
--   (<tt>ETag</tt> value) along with the updated function code. To get the
--   name and version, you can use <tt>ListFunctions</tt> and
--   <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.UpdateFunction

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newUpdateFunction</a> smart constructor.
data UpdateFunction
UpdateFunction' :: Text -> FunctionConfig -> Sensitive Base64 -> Text -> UpdateFunction

-- | The current version (<tt>ETag</tt> value) of the function that you are
--   updating, which you can get using <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.
[$sel:ifMatch:UpdateFunction'] :: UpdateFunction -> Text

--   function, see <a>Writing function code for CloudFront Functions</a> in
--   the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:functionCode:UpdateFunction'] :: UpdateFunction -> Sensitive Base64

-- | The name of the function that you are updating.
[$sel:name:UpdateFunction'] :: UpdateFunction -> Text

-- | Create a value of <a>UpdateFunction</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.

--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--

--   updating, which you can get using <tt>DescribeFunction</tt>.

--   <a>updateFunction_functionConfig</a> - Configuration information about
--   the function.

--   <a>updateFunction_functionCode</a> - The function code. For more
--   information about writing a CloudFront function, see <a>Writing
--   function code for CloudFront Functions</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.-- -- <i>Note:</i> This <tt>Lens</tt>
--   automatically encodes and decodes Base64 data. -- The underlying
--   isomorphism will encode to Base64 representation during --
--   serialisation, and decode from Base64 representation during

--   unencoded data.

-- | Updates a key group.
--   
--   When you update a key group, all the fields are updated with the
--   values provided in the request. You cannot update some fields
--   independent of others. To update a key group:
--   
--   <ol>
--   <li>Get the current key group with <tt>GetKeyGroup</tt> or
--   <tt>GetKeyGroupConfig</tt>.</li>
--   <li>Locally modify the fields in the key group that you want to
--   update. For example, add or remove public key IDs.</li>
--   <li>Call <tt>UpdateKeyGroup</tt> with the entire key group object,
--   including the fields that you modified and those that you didn’t.</li>
--   </ol>
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.UpdateKeyGroup

--

--   identifier of the key group that you are updating.

-- | Updates a real-time log configuration.
--   
--   When you update a real-time log configuration, all the parameters are
--   updated with the values provided in the request. You cannot update
--   some parameters independent of others. To update a real-time log
--   configuration:
--   
--   <ol>
--   <li>Call <tt>GetRealtimeLogConfig</tt> to get the current real-time
--   log configuration.</li>
--   <li>Locally modify the parameters in the real-time log configuration
--   that you want to update.</li>
--   <li>Call this API (<tt>UpdateRealtimeLogConfig</tt>) by providing the
--   entire real-time log configuration, including the parameters that you
--   modified and those that you didn’t.</li>
--   </ol>
--   
--   You cannot update a real-time log configuration’s <tt>Name</tt> or
--   <tt>ARN</tt>.
module Network.AWS.CloudFront.UpdateRealtimeLogConfig

-- | <i>See:</i> <a>newUpdateRealtimeLogConfig</a> smart constructor.

[$sel:arn:UpdateRealtimeLogConfig'] :: UpdateRealtimeLogConfig -> Maybe Text

-- | The sampling rate for this real-time log configuration. The sampling
--   rate determines the percentage of viewer requests that are represented
--   in the real-time log data. You must provide an integer between 1 and
--   100, inclusive.
[$sel:samplingRate:UpdateRealtimeLogConfig'] :: UpdateRealtimeLogConfig -> Maybe Integer

-- | The name for this real-time log configuration.
[$sel:name:UpdateRealtimeLogConfig'] :: UpdateRealtimeLogConfig -> Maybe Text

--   are sending real-time log data.

-- | A list of fields to include in each real-time log record.
--   
--   For more information about fields, see <a>Real-time log configuration
--   fields</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
[$sel:fields:UpdateRealtimeLogConfig'] :: UpdateRealtimeLogConfig -> Maybe [Text]

-- | Create a value of <a>UpdateRealtimeLogConfig</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.

-- | A domain name associated with a distribution.
aliasICPRecordal_cname :: Lens' AliasICPRecordal (Maybe Text)

-- | The Internet Content Provider (ICP) recordal status for a CNAME. The
--   ICPRecordalStatus is set to APPROVED for all CNAMEs (aliases) in
--   regions outside of China.
--   
--   The status values returned are the following:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><b>APPROVED</b> indicates that the associated CNAME has a valid
--   ICP recordal number. Multiple CNAMEs can be associated with a
--   distribution, and CNAMEs can correspond to different ICP recordals. To
--   be marked as APPROVED, that is, valid to use with China region, a
--   CNAME must have one ICP recordal number associated with it.</li>
--   <li><b>SUSPENDED</b> indicates that the associated CNAME does not have
--   a valid ICP recordal number.</li>
--   <li><b>PENDING</b> indicates that CloudFront can't determine the ICP
--   recordal status of the CNAME associated with the distribution because
--   there was an error in trying to determine the status. You can try
--   again to see if the error is resolved in which case CloudFront returns
--   an APPROVED or SUSPENDED status.</li>
--   </ul>
aliasICPRecordal_iCPRecordalStatus :: Lens' AliasICPRecordal (Maybe ICPRecordalStatus)

--   to associate with this distribution.

--   this distribution.
aliases_quantity :: Lens' Aliases Int

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use the
--   <tt>MaxTTL</tt> field in a cache policy instead of this field. For

--   managed cache policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   The maximum amount of time that you want objects to stay in CloudFront
--   caches before CloudFront forwards another request to your origin to
--   determine whether the object has been updated. The value that you
--   specify applies only when your origin adds HTTP headers such as
--   <tt>Cache-Control max-age</tt>, <tt>Cache-Control s-maxage</tt>, and
--   <tt>Expires</tt> to objects. For more information, see <a>Managing How
--   Long Content Stays in an Edge Cache (Expiration)</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
cacheBehavior_maxTTL :: Lens' CacheBehavior (Maybe Integer)

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use the
--   <tt>MinTTL</tt> field in a cache policy instead of this field. For
--   more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> or <a>Using the
--   managed cache policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   The minimum amount of time that you want objects to stay in CloudFront
--   caches before CloudFront forwards another request to your origin to
--   determine whether the object has been updated. For more information,
--   see <a>Managing How Long Content Stays in an Edge Cache
--   (Expiration)</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   You must specify <tt>0</tt> for <tt>MinTTL</tt> if you configure
--   CloudFront to forward all headers to your origin (under
--   <tt>Headers</tt>, if you specify <tt>1</tt> for <tt>Quantity</tt> and
--   <tt>*</tt> for <tt>Name</tt>).
cacheBehavior_minTTL :: Lens' CacheBehavior (Maybe Integer)

-- | Whether you want CloudFront to automatically compress certain files
--   for this cache behavior. If so, specify true; if not, specify false.
