--   <tt>true</tt>, this element is present and contains the value you can
--   use for the <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter to continue listing your
--   distributions where they left off.
--   
--   <a>$sel:marker:DistributionList'</a>, <a>distributionList_marker</a> -
--   The value you provided for the <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter.
--   
--   <a>$sel:maxItems:DistributionList'</a>,
--   <a>distributionList_maxItems</a> - The value you provided for the
--   <tt>MaxItems</tt> request parameter.
--   
--   <a>$sel:isTruncated:DistributionList'</a>,
--   <a>distributionList_isTruncated</a> - A flag that indicates whether
--   more distributions remain to be listed. If your results were
--   truncated, you can make a follow-up pagination request using the
--   <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter to retrieve more distributions in
--   the list.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:DistributionList'</a>,
--   <a>distributionList_quantity</a> - The number of distributions that
--   were created by the current account.
newDistributionList :: Text -> Int -> Bool -> Int -> DistributionList

-- | A summary of the information about a CloudFront distribution.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newDistributionSummary</a> smart constructor.
data DistributionSummary
DistributionSummary' :: Maybe OriginGroups -> Maybe [AliasICPRecordal] -> Text -> Text -> Text -> ISO8601 -> Text -> Aliases -> Origins -> DefaultCacheBehavior -> CacheBehaviors -> CustomErrorResponses -> Text -> PriceClass -> Bool -> ViewerCertificate -> Restrictions -> Text -> HttpVersion -> Bool -> DistributionSummary

-- | Create a value of <a>DistributionSummary</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:originGroups:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_originGroups</a> - A complex type that contains
--   information about origin groups for this distribution.
--   
--   <a>$sel:aliasICPRecordals:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_aliasICPRecordals</a> - Amazon Web Services
--   services in China customers must file for an Internet Content Provider
--   (ICP) recordal if they want to serve content publicly on an alternate
--   domain name, also known as a CNAME, that they've added to CloudFront.
--   AliasICPRecordal provides the ICP recordal status for CNAMEs
--   associated with distributions.
--   
--   For more information about ICP recordals, see <a>Signup, Accounts, and
--   Credentials</a> in <i>Getting Started with Amazon Web Services
--   services in China</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:DistributionSummary'</a>, <a>distributionSummary_id</a> -
--   The identifier for the distribution. For example:
--   <tt>EDFDVBD632BHDS5</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:arn:DistributionSummary'</a>, <a>distributionSummary_arn</a> -
--   The ARN (Amazon Resource Name) for the distribution. For example:
--   <tt>arn:aws:cloudfront::123456789012:distribution/EDFDVBD632BHDS5</tt>,
--   where <tt>123456789012</tt> is your account ID.
--   
--   <a>$sel:status:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_status</a> - The current status of the
--   distribution. When the status is <tt>Deployed</tt>, the distribution's
--   information is propagated to all CloudFront edge locations.
--   
--   <a>$sel:lastModifiedTime:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_lastModifiedTime</a> - The date and time the
--   distribution was last modified.
--   
--   <a>$sel:domainName:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_domainName</a> - The domain name that
--   corresponds to the distribution, for example,
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:aliases:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_aliases</a> - A complex type that contains
--   information about CNAMEs (alternate domain names), if any, for this
--   distribution.
--   
--   <a>$sel:origins:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_origins</a> - A complex type that contains
--   information about origins for this distribution.
--   
--   <a>$sel:defaultCacheBehavior:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_defaultCacheBehavior</a> - A complex type that
--   describes the default cache behavior if you don't specify a
--   <tt>CacheBehavior</tt> element or if files don't match any of the
--   values of <tt>PathPattern</tt> in <tt>CacheBehavior</tt> elements. You
--   must create exactly one default cache behavior.
--   
--   <a>$sel:cacheBehaviors:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_cacheBehaviors</a> - A complex type that
--   contains zero or more <tt>CacheBehavior</tt> elements.
--   
--   <a>$sel:customErrorResponses:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_customErrorResponses</a> - A complex type that
--   contains zero or more <tt>CustomErrorResponses</tt> elements.
--   
--   <a>$sel:comment:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_comment</a> - The comment originally specified
--   when this distribution was created.
--   
--   <a>$sel:priceClass:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_priceClass</a> - A complex type that contains
--   information about price class for this streaming distribution.
--   
--   <a>$sel:enabled:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_enabled</a> - Whether the distribution is
--   enabled to accept user requests for content.
--   
--   <a>$sel:viewerCertificate:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_viewerCertificate</a> - A complex type that
--   determines the distribution’s SSL/TLS configuration for communicating
--   with viewers.
--   
--   <a>$sel:restrictions:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_restrictions</a> - A complex type that
--   identifies ways in which you want to restrict distribution of your
--   content.
--   
--   <a>$sel:webACLId:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_webACLId</a> - The Web ACL Id (if any)
--   associated with the distribution.
--   
--   <a>$sel:httpVersion:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_httpVersion</a> - Specify the maximum HTTP
--   version that you want viewers to use to communicate with CloudFront.
--   The default value for new web distributions is <tt>http2</tt>. Viewers
--   that don't support <tt>HTTP/2</tt> will automatically use an earlier
--   version.
--   
--   <a>$sel:isIPV6Enabled:DistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>distributionSummary_isIPV6Enabled</a> - Whether CloudFront responds
--   to IPv6 DNS requests with an IPv6 address for your distribution.
newDistributionSummary :: Text -> Text -> Text -> UTCTime -> Text -> Aliases -> Origins -> DefaultCacheBehavior -> CacheBehaviors -> CustomErrorResponses -> Text -> PriceClass -> Bool -> ViewerCertificate -> Restrictions -> Text -> HttpVersion -> Bool -> DistributionSummary

--   fields that match the patterns.

--   beginning characters followed by a wildcard (*). You can't overlap
--   field patterns. For example, you can't have both ABC* and AB*. Note
--   that field patterns are case-sensitive.
newEncryptionEntity :: Text -> Text -> FieldPatterns -> EncryptionEntity

data FieldPatterns

--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.

--   The number of field-level encryption field patterns.
newFieldPatterns :: Int -> FieldPatterns

-- | This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy or
--   an origin request policy instead of this field.
--   
--   If you want to include values in the cache key, use a cache policy.
--   For more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to send values to the origin but not include them in the
--   cache key, use an origin request policy. For more information, see
--   <a>Creating origin request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   A complex type that specifies how CloudFront handles query strings,
--   cookies, and HTTP headers.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newForwardedValues</a> smart constructor.
data ForwardedValues
ForwardedValues' :: Maybe QueryStringCacheKeys -> Maybe Headers -> Bool -> CookiePreference -> ForwardedValues

-- | Create a value of <a>ForwardedValues</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:queryStringCacheKeys:ForwardedValues'</a>,
--   <a>forwardedValues_queryStringCacheKeys</a> - This field is
--   deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy or an origin
--   request policy instead of this field.
--   
--   If you want to include query strings in the cache key, use a cache
--   policy. For more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> in
--   the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to send query strings to the origin but not include them
--   in the cache key, use an origin request policy. For more information,
--   see <a>Creating origin request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   A complex type that contains information about the query string
--   parameters that you want CloudFront to use for caching for this cache
--   behavior.
--   
--   <a>$sel:headers:ForwardedValues'</a>, <a>forwardedValues_headers</a> -
--   This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy or
--   an origin request policy instead of this field.
--   
--   If you want to include headers in the cache key, use a cache policy.
--   For more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to send headers to the origin but not include them in the
--   cache key, use an origin request policy. For more information, see
--   <a>Creating origin request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   A complex type that specifies the <tt>Headers</tt>, if any, that you
--   want CloudFront to forward to the origin for this cache behavior
--   (whitelisted headers). For the headers that you specify, CloudFront
--   also caches separate versions of a specified object that is based on
--   the header values in viewer requests.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Caching Content Based on Request
--   Headers</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:queryString:ForwardedValues'</a>,
--   <a>forwardedValues_queryString</a> - This field is deprecated. We
--   recommend that you use a cache policy or an origin request policy
--   instead of this field.
--   
--   If you want to include query strings in the cache key, use a cache
--   policy. For more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> in
--   the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to send query strings to the origin but not include them
--   in the cache key, use an origin request policy. For more information,
--   see <a>Creating origin request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   Indicates whether you want CloudFront to forward query strings to the
--   origin that is associated with this cache behavior and cache based on
--   the query string parameters. CloudFront behavior depends on the value
--   of <tt>QueryString</tt> and on the values that you specify for
--   <tt>QueryStringCacheKeys</tt>, if any:
--   
--   If you specify true for <tt>QueryString</tt> and you don't specify any
--   values for <tt>QueryStringCacheKeys</tt>, CloudFront forwards all
--   query string parameters to the origin and caches based on all query
--   string parameters. Depending on how many query string parameters and
--   values you have, this can adversely affect performance because
--   CloudFront must forward more requests to the origin.
--   
--   If you specify true for <tt>QueryString</tt> and you specify one or
--   more values for <tt>QueryStringCacheKeys</tt>, CloudFront forwards all
--   query string parameters to the origin, but it only caches based on the
--   query string parameters that you specify.
--   
--   If you specify false for <tt>QueryString</tt>, CloudFront doesn't
--   forward any query string parameters to the origin, and doesn't cache
--   based on query string parameters.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Configuring CloudFront to Cache Based on
--   Query String Parameters</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:cookies:ForwardedValues'</a>, <a>forwardedValues_cookies</a> -
--   This field is deprecated. We recommend that you use a cache policy or
--   an origin request policy instead of this field.
--   
--   If you want to include cookies in the cache key, use a cache policy.
--   For more information, see <a>Creating cache policies</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you want to send cookies to the origin but not include them in the
--   cache key, use an origin request policy. For more information, see
--   <a>Creating origin request policies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   A complex type that specifies whether you want CloudFront to forward
--   cookies to the origin and, if so, which ones. For more information
--   about forwarding cookies to the origin, see <a>How CloudFront
--   Forwards, Caches, and Logs Cookies</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.
newForwardedValues :: Bool -> CookiePreference -> ForwardedValues

-- | A CloudFront function that is associated with a cache behavior in a
--   CloudFront distribution.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newFunctionAssociation</a> smart constructor.
data FunctionAssociation
FunctionAssociation' :: Text -> EventType -> FunctionAssociation

-- | Create a value of <a>FunctionAssociation</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:functionARN:FunctionAssociation'</a>,
--   <a>functionAssociation_functionARN</a> - The Amazon Resource Name
--   (ARN) of the function.
--   
--   <a>$sel:eventType:FunctionAssociation'</a>,
--   <a>functionAssociation_eventType</a> - The event type of the function,
--   either <tt>viewer-request</tt> or <tt>viewer-response</tt>. You cannot
--   use origin-facing event types (<tt>origin-request</tt> and
--   <tt>origin-response</tt>) with a CloudFront function.
newFunctionAssociation :: Text -> EventType -> FunctionAssociation

-- | A list of CloudFront functions that are associated with a cache

-- | A complex type that controls the countries in which your content is
--   distributed. CloudFront determines the location of your users using
--   <tt>MaxMind</tt> GeoIP databases.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newGeoRestriction</a> smart constructor.
data GeoRestriction
GeoRestriction' :: Maybe [Text] -> GeoRestrictionType -> Int -> GeoRestriction

-- | Create a value of <a>GeoRestriction</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:GeoRestriction'</a>, <a>geoRestriction_items</a> - A
--   complex type that contains a <tt>Location</tt> element for each
--   country in which you want CloudFront either to distribute your content
--   (<tt>whitelist</tt>) or not distribute your content
--   (<tt>blacklist</tt>).
--   
--   The <tt>Location</tt> element is a two-letter, uppercase country code
--   for a country that you want to include in your <tt>blacklist</tt> or
--   <tt>whitelist</tt>. Include one <tt>Location</tt> element for each
--   country.
--   
--   CloudFront and <tt>MaxMind</tt> both use <tt>ISO 3166</tt> country
--   codes. For the current list of countries and the corresponding codes,
--   see <tt>ISO 3166-1-alpha-2</tt> code on the /International
--   Organization for Standardization/ website. You can also refer to the
--   country list on the CloudFront console, which includes both country
--   names and codes.
--   
--   <a>$sel:restrictionType:GeoRestriction'</a>,
--   <a>geoRestriction_restrictionType</a> - The method that you want to
--   use to restrict distribution of your content by country:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt>: No geo restriction is enabled, meaning access to
--   content is not restricted by client geo location.</li>
--   <li><tt>blacklist</tt>: The <tt>Location</tt> elements specify the
--   countries in which you don't want CloudFront to distribute your
--   content.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt>: The <tt>Location</tt> elements specify the
--   countries in which you want CloudFront to distribute your
--   content.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:GeoRestriction'</a>, <a>geoRestriction_quantity</a> -
--   When geo restriction is <tt>enabled</tt>, this is the number of
--   countries in your <tt>whitelist</tt> or <tt>blacklist</tt>. Otherwise,
--   when it is not enabled, <tt>Quantity</tt> is <tt>0</tt>, and you can
--   omit <tt>Items</tt>.
newGeoRestriction :: GeoRestrictionType -> Int -> GeoRestriction

data Headers
Headers' :: Maybe [Text] -> Int -> Headers

--   header names.

--   <a>$sel:quantity:Headers'</a>, <a>headers_quantity</a> - The number of
--   header names in the <tt>Items</tt> list.
newHeaders :: Int -> Headers

--   for the invalidation request. For example: <tt>IDFDVBD632BHDS5</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:status:Invalidation'</a>, <a>invalidation_status</a> - The
--   status of the invalidation request. When the invalidation batch is
--   finished, the status is <tt>Completed</tt>.

--   <a>$sel:createTime:Invalidation'</a>, <a>invalidation_createTime</a> -

newInvalidation :: Text -> Text -> UTCTime -> InvalidationBatch -> Invalidation

-- | An invalidation batch.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newInvalidationBatch</a> smart constructor.
data InvalidationBatch
InvalidationBatch' :: Paths -> Text -> InvalidationBatch

-- | Create a value of <a>InvalidationBatch</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:paths:InvalidationBatch'</a>, <a>invalidationBatch_paths</a> -
--   A complex type that contains information about the objects that you
--   want to invalidate. For more information, see <a>Specifying the
--   Objects to Invalidate</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:callerReference:InvalidationBatch'</a>,
--   <a>invalidationBatch_callerReference</a> - A value that you specify to
--   uniquely identify an invalidation request. CloudFront uses the value
--   to prevent you from accidentally resubmitting an identical request.
--   Whenever you create a new invalidation request, you must specify a new
--   value for <tt>CallerReference</tt> and change other values in the
--   request as applicable. One way to ensure that the value of
--   <tt>CallerReference</tt> is unique is to use a <tt>timestamp</tt>, for
--   example, <tt>20120301090000</tt>.
--   
--   If you make a second invalidation request with the same value for
--   <tt>CallerReference</tt>, and if the rest of the request is the same,
--   CloudFront doesn't create a new invalidation request. Instead,
--   CloudFront returns information about the invalidation request that you
--   previously created with the same <tt>CallerReference</tt>.
--   
--   If <tt>CallerReference</tt> is a value you already sent in a previous
--   invalidation batch request but the content of any <tt>Path</tt> is
--   different from the original request, CloudFront returns an
--   <tt>InvalidationBatchAlreadyExists</tt> error.
newInvalidationBatch :: Paths -> Text -> InvalidationBatch

-- | The <tt>InvalidationList</tt> complex type describes the list of
--   invalidation objects. For more information about invalidation, see
--   <a>Invalidating Objects (Web Distributions Only)</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.

--   for each invalidation batch created by the current account.
--   
--   <a>$sel:nextMarker:InvalidationList'</a>,
--   <a>invalidationList_nextMarker</a> - If <tt>IsTruncated</tt> is
--   <tt>true</tt>, this element is present and contains the value that you
--   can use for the <tt>Marker</tt> request parameter to continue listing
--   your invalidation batches where they left off.

--   more invalidation batch requests remain to be listed. If your results

--   batches in the list.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:InvalidationList'</a>,
--   <a>invalidationList_quantity</a> - The number of invalidation batches
--   that were created by the current account.
newInvalidationList :: Text -> Int -> Bool -> Int -> InvalidationList

-- | A complex type that contains a Lambda@Edge function association.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newLambdaFunctionAssociation</a> smart constructor.
data LambdaFunctionAssociation
LambdaFunctionAssociation' :: Maybe Bool -> Text -> EventType -> LambdaFunctionAssociation

-- | Create a value of <a>LambdaFunctionAssociation</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:includeBody:LambdaFunctionAssociation'</a>,
--   <a>lambdaFunctionAssociation_includeBody</a> - A flag that allows a
--   Lambda@Edge function to have read access to the body content. For more
--   information, see <a>Accessing the Request Body by Choosing the Include
--   Body Option</a> in the Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide.
--   
--   <a>$sel:lambdaFunctionARN:LambdaFunctionAssociation'</a>,
--   <a>lambdaFunctionAssociation_lambdaFunctionARN</a> - The ARN of the
--   Lambda@Edge function. You must specify the ARN of a function version;
--   you can't specify an alias or $LATEST.
--   
--   <a>$sel:eventType:LambdaFunctionAssociation'</a>,
--   <a>lambdaFunctionAssociation_eventType</a> - Specifies the event type
--   that triggers a Lambda@Edge function invocation. You can specify the
--   following values:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>viewer-request</tt>: The function executes when CloudFront
--   receives a request from a viewer and before it checks to see whether
--   the requested object is in the edge cache.</li>
--   <li><tt>origin-request</tt>: The function executes only when
--   CloudFront sends a request to your origin. When the requested object
--   is in the edge cache, the function doesn't execute.</li>
--   <li><tt>origin-response</tt>: The function executes after CloudFront
--   receives a response from the origin and before it caches the object in
--   the response. When the requested object is in the edge cache, the
--   function doesn't execute.</li>
--   <li><tt>viewer-response</tt>: The function executes before CloudFront
--   returns the requested object to the viewer. The function executes
--   regardless of whether the object was already in the edge cache.If the
--   origin returns an HTTP status code other than HTTP 200 (OK), the
--   function doesn't execute.</li>
--   </ul>
newLambdaFunctionAssociation :: Text -> EventType -> LambdaFunctionAssociation

-- | A complex type that specifies a list of Lambda@Edge functions
--   associations for a cache behavior.
--   
--   If you want to invoke one or more Lambda@Edge functions triggered by
--   requests that match the <tt>PathPattern</tt> of the cache behavior,
--   specify the applicable values for <tt>Quantity</tt> and
--   <tt>Items</tt>. Note that there can be up to 4
--   <tt>LambdaFunctionAssociation</tt> items in this list (one for each
--   possible value of <tt>EventType</tt>) and each <tt>EventType</tt> can
--   be associated with only one function.
--   
--   If you don't want to invoke any Lambda@Edge functions for the requests
--   that match <tt>PathPattern</tt>, specify <tt>0</tt> for
--   <tt>Quantity</tt> and omit <tt>Items</tt>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newLambdaFunctionAssociations</a> smart constructor.
data LambdaFunctionAssociations
LambdaFunctionAssociations' :: Maybe [LambdaFunctionAssociation] -> Int -> LambdaFunctionAssociations

-- | Create a value of <a>LambdaFunctionAssociations</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:LambdaFunctionAssociations'</a>,
--   <a>lambdaFunctionAssociations_items</a> - <b>Optional</b>: A complex
--   type that contains <tt>LambdaFunctionAssociation</tt> items for this
--   cache behavior. If <tt>Quantity</tt> is <tt>0</tt>, you can omit
--   <tt>Items</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:LambdaFunctionAssociations'</a>,
--   <a>lambdaFunctionAssociations_quantity</a> - The number of Lambda@Edge
--   function associations for this cache behavior.
newLambdaFunctionAssociations :: Int -> LambdaFunctionAssociations

-- | A complex type that controls whether access logs are written for the
--   distribution.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newLoggingConfig</a> smart constructor.
data LoggingConfig
LoggingConfig' :: Bool -> Bool -> Text -> Text -> LoggingConfig

-- | Create a value of <a>LoggingConfig</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:enabled:LoggingConfig'</a>, <a>loggingConfig_enabled</a> -
--   Specifies whether you want CloudFront to save access logs to an Amazon
--   S3 bucket. If you don't want to enable logging when you create a
--   distribution or if you want to disable logging for an existing
--   distribution, specify <tt>false</tt> for <tt>Enabled</tt>, and specify
--   empty <tt>Bucket</tt> and <tt>Prefix</tt> elements. If you specify
--   <tt>false</tt> for <tt>Enabled</tt> but you specify values for
--   <tt>Bucket</tt>, <tt>prefix</tt>, and <tt>IncludeCookies</tt>, the
--   values are automatically deleted.
--   
--   <a>$sel:includeCookies:LoggingConfig'</a>,
--   <a>loggingConfig_includeCookies</a> - Specifies whether you want
--   CloudFront to include cookies in access logs, specify <tt>true</tt>
--   for <tt>IncludeCookies</tt>. If you choose to include cookies in logs,
--   CloudFront logs all cookies regardless of how you configure the cache
--   behaviors for this distribution. If you don't want to include cookies
--   when you create a distribution or if you want to disable include
--   cookies for an existing distribution, specify <tt>false</tt> for
--   <tt>IncludeCookies</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:bucket:LoggingConfig'</a>, <a>loggingConfig_bucket</a> - The
--   Amazon S3 bucket to store the access logs in, for example,
--   <tt>myawslogbucket.s3.amazonaws.com</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:prefix:LoggingConfig'</a>, <a>loggingConfig_prefix</a> - An
--   optional string that you want CloudFront to prefix to the access log
--   <tt>filenames</tt> for this distribution, for example,
--   <tt>myprefix/</tt>. If you want to enable logging, but you don't want
--   to specify a prefix, you still must include an empty <tt>Prefix</tt>
--   element in the <tt>Logging</tt> element.
newLoggingConfig :: Bool -> Bool -> Text -> Text -> LoggingConfig

-- | An origin.
--   
--   An origin is the location where content is stored, and from which
--   CloudFront gets content to serve to viewers. To specify an origin:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>Use <tt>S3OriginConfig</tt> to specify an Amazon S3 bucket that is
--   not configured with static website hosting.</li>
--   <li>Use <tt>CustomOriginConfig</tt> to specify all other kinds of
--   origins, including:<ul><li>An Amazon S3 bucket that is configured with
--   static website hosting</li><li>An Elastic Load Balancing load
--   balancer</li><li>An AWS Elemental MediaPackage endpoint</li><li>An AWS
--   Elemental MediaStore container</li><li>Any other HTTP server, running
--   on an Amazon EC2 instance or any other kind of host</li></ul></li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For the current maximum number of origins that you can specify per
--   distribution, see <a>General Quotas on Web Distributions</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i> (quotas were formerly
--   referred to as limits).
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newOrigin</a> smart constructor.
data Origin
Origin' :: Maybe CustomHeaders -> Maybe CustomOriginConfig -> Maybe Int -> Maybe Int -> Maybe S3OriginConfig -> Maybe Text -> Maybe OriginShield -> Text -> Text -> Origin

-- | Create a value of <a>Origin</a> with all optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:customHeaders:Origin'</a>, <a>origin_customHeaders</a> - A
--   list of HTTP header names and values that CloudFront adds to the
--   requests that it sends to the origin.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Adding Custom Headers to Origin
--   Requests</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:customOriginConfig:Origin'</a>,
--   <a>origin_customOriginConfig</a> - Use this type to specify an origin
--   that is not an Amazon S3 bucket, with one exception. If the Amazon S3
--   bucket is configured with static website hosting, use this type. If
--   the Amazon S3 bucket is not configured with static website hosting,
--   use the <tt>S3OriginConfig</tt> type instead.
--   
--   <a>$sel:connectionTimeout:Origin'</a>, <a>origin_connectionTimeout</a>
--   - The number of seconds that CloudFront waits when trying to establish
--   a connection to the origin. The minimum timeout is 1 second, the
--   maximum is 10 seconds, and the default (if you don’t specify
--   otherwise) is 10 seconds.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Origin Connection Timeout</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:connectionAttempts:Origin'</a>,
--   <a>origin_connectionAttempts</a> - The number of times that CloudFront
--   attempts to connect to the origin. The minimum number is 1, the
--   maximum is 3, and the default (if you don’t specify otherwise) is 3.
--   
--   For a custom origin (including an Amazon S3 bucket that’s configured
--   with static website hosting), this value also specifies the number of
--   times that CloudFront attempts to get a response from the origin, in
--   the case of an <a>Origin Response Timeout</a>.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Origin Connection Attempts</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:s3OriginConfig:Origin'</a>, <a>origin_s3OriginConfig</a> - Use
--   this type to specify an origin that is an Amazon S3 bucket that is not
--   configured with static website hosting. To specify any other type of
--   origin, including an Amazon S3 bucket that is configured with static
--   website hosting, use the <tt>CustomOriginConfig</tt> type instead.
--   
--   <a>$sel:originPath:Origin'</a>, <a>origin_originPath</a> - An optional
--   path that CloudFront appends to the origin domain name when CloudFront
--   requests content from the origin.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Origin Path</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:originShield:Origin'</a>, <a>origin_originShield</a> -
--   CloudFront Origin Shield. Using Origin Shield can help reduce the load
--   on your origin.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Using Origin Shield</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:Origin'</a>, <a>origin_id</a> - A unique identifier for the
--   origin. This value must be unique within the distribution.
--   
--   Use this value to specify the <tt>TargetOriginId</tt> in a
--   <tt>CacheBehavior</tt> or <tt>DefaultCacheBehavior</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:domainName:Origin'</a>, <a>origin_domainName</a> - The domain
--   name for the origin.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Origin Domain Name</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
newOrigin :: Text -> Text -> Origin

-- | An origin group includes two origins (a primary origin and a second
--   origin to failover to) and a failover criteria that you specify. You
--   create an origin group to support origin failover in CloudFront. When
--   you create or update a distribution, you can specifiy the origin group
--   instead of a single origin, and CloudFront will failover from the
--   primary origin to the second origin under the failover conditions that
--   you've chosen.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newOriginGroup</a> smart constructor.
data OriginGroup
OriginGroup' :: Text -> OriginGroupFailoverCriteria -> OriginGroupMembers -> OriginGroup

-- | Create a value of <a>OriginGroup</a> with all optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.

--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:OriginGroup'</a>, <a>originGroup_id</a> - The origin
--   group's ID.
--   
--   <a>$sel:failoverCriteria:OriginGroup'</a>,
--   <a>originGroup_failoverCriteria</a> - A complex type that contains
--   information about the failover criteria for an origin group.
--   
--   <a>$sel:members:OriginGroup'</a>, <a>originGroup_members</a> - A
--   complex type that contains information about the origins in an origin
--   group.
newOriginGroup :: Text -> OriginGroupFailoverCriteria -> OriginGroupMembers -> OriginGroup

-- | A complex data type that includes information about the failover

--   CloudFront will failover from the primary origin to the second origin.

newOriginGroupFailoverCriteria :: StatusCodes -> OriginGroupFailoverCriteria

-- | An origin request policy.
--   
--   When it’s attached to a cache behavior, the origin request policy
--   determines the values that CloudFront includes in requests that it
--   sends to the origin. Each request that CloudFront sends to the origin
--   includes the following:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The request body and the URL path (without the domain name) from
--   the viewer request.</li>
--   <li>The headers that CloudFront automatically includes in every origin
--   request, including <tt>Host</tt>, <tt>User-Agent</tt>, and
--   <tt>X-Amz-Cf-Id</tt>.</li>
--   <li>All HTTP headers, cookies, and URL query strings that are
--   specified in the cache policy or the origin request policy. These can
--   include items from the viewer request and, in the case of headers,
--   additional ones that are added by CloudFront.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   CloudFront sends a request when it can’t find an object in its cache
--   that matches the request. If you want to send values to the origin and
--   also include them in the cache key, use <tt>CachePolicy</tt>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newOriginRequestPolicy</a> smart constructor.
data OriginRequestPolicy
OriginRequestPolicy' :: Text -> ISO8601 -> OriginRequestPolicyConfig -> OriginRequestPolicy

-- | Create a value of <a>OriginRequestPolicy</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:OriginRequestPolicy'</a>, <a>originRequestPolicy_id</a> -
--   The unique identifier for the origin request policy.
--   
--   <a>$sel:lastModifiedTime:OriginRequestPolicy'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicy_lastModifiedTime</a> - The date and time when
--   the origin request policy was last modified.
--   
--   <a>$sel:originRequestPolicyConfig:OriginRequestPolicy'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicy_originRequestPolicyConfig</a> - The origin
--   request policy configuration.
newOriginRequestPolicy :: Text -> UTCTime -> OriginRequestPolicyConfig -> OriginRequestPolicy

-- | An origin request policy configuration.
--   
--   This configuration determines the values that CloudFront includes in
--   requests that it sends to the origin. Each request that CloudFront
--   sends to the origin includes the following:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The request body and the URL path (without the domain name) from
--   the viewer request.</li>
--   <li>The headers that CloudFront automatically includes in every origin
--   request, including <tt>Host</tt>, <tt>User-Agent</tt>, and
--   <tt>X-Amz-Cf-Id</tt>.</li>
--   <li>All HTTP headers, cookies, and URL query strings that are
--   specified in the cache policy or the origin request policy. These can
--   include items from the viewer request and, in the case of headers,
--   additional ones that are added by CloudFront.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   CloudFront sends a request when it can’t find an object in its cache
--   that matches the request. If you want to send values to the origin and
--   also include them in the cache key, use <tt>CachePolicy</tt>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newOriginRequestPolicyConfig</a> smart constructor.
data OriginRequestPolicyConfig
OriginRequestPolicyConfig' :: Maybe Text -> Text -> OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig -> OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig -> OriginRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig -> OriginRequestPolicyConfig

-- | Create a value of <a>OriginRequestPolicyConfig</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:comment:OriginRequestPolicyConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyConfig_comment</a> - A comment to describe the
--   origin request policy. The comment cannot be longer than 128
--   characters.
--   
--   <a>$sel:name:OriginRequestPolicyConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyConfig_name</a> - A unique name to identify the
--   origin request policy.
--   
--   <a>$sel:headersConfig:OriginRequestPolicyConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyConfig_headersConfig</a> - The HTTP headers to
--   include in origin requests. These can include headers from viewer
--   requests and additional headers added by CloudFront.
--   
--   <a>$sel:cookiesConfig:OriginRequestPolicyConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyConfig_cookiesConfig</a> - The cookies from
--   viewer requests to include in origin requests.
--   
--   <a>$sel:queryStringsConfig:OriginRequestPolicyConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyConfig_queryStringsConfig</a> - The URL query
--   strings from viewer requests to include in origin requests.
newOriginRequestPolicyConfig :: Text -> OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig -> OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig -> OriginRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig -> OriginRequestPolicyConfig

-- | An object that determines whether any cookies in viewer requests (and
--   if so, which cookies) are included in requests that CloudFront sends
--   to the origin.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newOriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig</a> smart
--   constructor.
data OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig
OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig' :: Maybe CookieNames -> OriginRequestPolicyCookieBehavior -> OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig

-- | Create a value of <a>OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig</a> with all
--   optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:cookies:OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyCookiesConfig_cookies</a> - Undocumented member.
--   
--   <a>$sel:cookieBehavior:OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyCookiesConfig_cookieBehavior</a> - Determines
--   whether cookies in viewer requests are included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – Cookies in viewer requests are not included in
--   requests that CloudFront sends to the origin. Even when this field is
--   set to <tt>none</tt>, any cookies that are listed in a
--   <tt>CachePolicy</tt> <i>are</i> included in origin requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The cookies in viewer requests that are
--   listed in the <tt>CookieNames</tt> type are included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>all</tt> – All cookies in viewer requests are included in
--   requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   </ul>
newOriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig :: OriginRequestPolicyCookieBehavior -> OriginRequestPolicyCookiesConfig

-- | An object that determines whether any HTTP headers (and if so, which
--   headers) are included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newOriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig</a> smart
--   constructor.
data OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig
OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig' :: Maybe Headers -> OriginRequestPolicyHeaderBehavior -> OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig

-- | Create a value of <a>OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig</a> with all
--   optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:headers:OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyHeadersConfig_headers</a> - Undocumented member.
--   
--   <a>$sel:headerBehavior:OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyHeadersConfig_headerBehavior</a> - Determines
--   whether any HTTP headers are included in requests that CloudFront
--   sends to the origin. Valid values are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – HTTP headers are not included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin. Even when this field is set to
--   <tt>none</tt>, any headers that are listed in a <tt>CachePolicy</tt>
--   <i>are</i> included in origin requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The HTTP headers that are listed in the
--   <tt>Headers</tt> type are included in requests that CloudFront sends
--   to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>allViewer</tt> – All HTTP headers in viewer requests are
--   included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>allViewerAndWhitelistCloudFront</tt> – All HTTP headers in
--   viewer requests and the additional CloudFront headers that are listed
--   in the <tt>Headers</tt> type are included in requests that CloudFront
--   sends to the origin. The additional headers are added by
--   CloudFront.</li>
--   </ul>
newOriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig :: OriginRequestPolicyHeaderBehavior -> OriginRequestPolicyHeadersConfig

--   <i>See:</i> <a>newOriginRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig</a> smart

data OriginRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig
OriginRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig' :: Maybe QueryStringNames -> OriginRequestPolicyQueryStringBehavior -> OriginRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig

-- | Create a value of <a>OriginRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig</a> with
--   all optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:queryStrings:OriginRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig_queryStrings</a> - Contains a
--   list of the query strings in viewer requests that are included in
--   requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.
--   
--   
--   <a>$sel:queryStringBehavior:OriginRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig'</a>,
--   <a>originRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig_queryStringBehavior</a> -
--   Determines whether any URL query strings in viewer requests are
--   included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin. Valid values
--   are:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>none</tt> – Query strings in viewer requests are not included
--   in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin. Even when this field
--   is set to <tt>none</tt>, any query strings that are listed in a
--   <tt>CachePolicy</tt> <i>are</i> included in origin requests.</li>
--   <li><tt>whitelist</tt> – The query strings in viewer requests that are
--   listed in the <tt>QueryStringNames</tt> type are included in requests
--   that CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   <li><tt>all</tt> – All query strings in viewer requests are included
--   in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.</li>
--   </ul>
newOriginRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig :: OriginRequestPolicyQueryStringBehavior -> OriginRequestPolicyQueryStringsConfig

-- | CloudFront Origin Shield.
--   
--   Using Origin Shield can help reduce the load on your origin. For more
--   information, see <a>Using Origin Shield</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newOriginShield</a> smart constructor.

--   <a>$sel:originShieldRegion:OriginShield'</a>,
--   <a>originShield_originShieldRegion</a> - The Region for Origin Shield.
--   
--   Specify the Region that has the lowest latency to your origin. To
--   specify a region, use the region code, not the region name. For
--   example, specify the US East (Ohio) region as <tt>us-east-2</tt>.
--   
--   When you enable CloudFront Origin Shield, you must specify the Region
--   for Origin Shield. For the list of Regions that you can specify, and
--   for help choosing the best Region for your origin, see <a>Choosing the
--   Region for Origin Shield</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:enabled:OriginShield'</a>, <a>originShield_enabled</a> - A
--   flag that specifies whether Origin Shield is enabled.
--   
--   When it’s enabled, CloudFront routes all requests through Origin
--   Shield, which can help protect your origin. When it’s disabled,
--   CloudFront might send requests directly to your origin from multiple
--   edge locations or regional edge caches.
newOriginShield :: Bool -> OriginShield

-- | This object determines the values that CloudFront includes in the
--   cache key. These values can include HTTP headers, cookies, and URL
--   query strings. CloudFront uses the cache key to find an object in its
--   cache that it can return to the viewer.
--   
--   The headers, cookies, and query strings that are included in the cache
--   key are automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to
--   the origin. CloudFront sends a request when it can’t find an object in
--   its cache that matches the request’s cache key. If you want to send
--   values to the origin but <i>not</i> include them in the cache key, use
--   <tt>OriginRequestPolicy</tt>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newParametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin</a> smart
--   constructor.
data ParametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin
ParametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin' :: Maybe Bool -> Bool -> CachePolicyHeadersConfig -> CachePolicyCookiesConfig -> CachePolicyQueryStringsConfig -> ParametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin

-- | Create a value of <a>ParametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin</a> with
--   all optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   
--   <a>$sel:enableAcceptEncodingBrotli:ParametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin'</a>,
--   <a>parametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin_enableAcceptEncodingBrotli</a>
--   - A flag that can affect whether the <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt> HTTP
--   header is included in the cache key and included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin.
--   
--   This field is related to the <tt>EnableAcceptEncodingGzip</tt> field.
--   If one or both of these fields is <tt>true</tt> <i>and</i> the viewer
--   request includes the <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt> header, then CloudFront
--   does the following:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>Normalizes the value of the viewer’s <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt>
--   header</li>
--   <li>Includes the normalized header in the cache key</li>
--   <li>Includes the normalized header in the request to the origin, if a
--   request is necessary</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Compression support</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you set this value to <tt>true</tt>, and this cache behavior also
--   has an origin request policy attached, do not include the
--   <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt> header in the origin request policy.
--   CloudFront always includes the <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt> header in
--   origin requests when the value of this field is <tt>true</tt>, so
--   including this header in an origin request policy has no effect.
--   
--   If both of these fields are <tt>false</tt>, then CloudFront treats the
--   <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt> header the same as any other HTTP header in
--   the viewer request. By default, it’s not included in the cache key and
--   it’s not included in origin requests. In this case, you can manually
--   add <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt> to the headers whitelist like any other
--   HTTP header.
--   
--   
--   <a>$sel:enableAcceptEncodingGzip:ParametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin'</a>,
--   <a>parametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin_enableAcceptEncodingGzip</a>
--   - A flag that can affect whether the <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt> HTTP
--   header is included in the cache key and included in requests that
--   CloudFront sends to the origin.
--   
--   This field is related to the <tt>EnableAcceptEncodingBrotli</tt>
--   field. If one or both of these fields is <tt>true</tt> <i>and</i> the
--   viewer request includes the <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt> header, then
--   CloudFront does the following:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>Normalizes the value of the viewer’s <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt>
--   header</li>
--   <li>Includes the normalized header in the cache key</li>
--   <li>Includes the normalized header in the request to the origin, if a
--   request is necessary</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Compression support</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   If you set this value to <tt>true</tt>, and this cache behavior also
--   has an origin request policy attached, do not include the
--   <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt> header in the origin request policy.
--   CloudFront always includes the <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt> header in
--   origin requests when the value of this field is <tt>true</tt>, so
--   including this header in an origin request policy has no effect.
--   
--   If both of these fields are <tt>false</tt>, then CloudFront treats the
--   <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt> header the same as any other HTTP header in
--   the viewer request. By default, it’s not included in the cache key and
--   it’s not included in origin requests. In this case, you can manually
--   add <tt>Accept-Encoding</tt> to the headers whitelist like any other
--   HTTP header.
--   
--   <a>$sel:headersConfig:ParametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin'</a>,
--   <a>parametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin_headersConfig</a> - An
--   object that determines whether any HTTP headers (and if so, which
--   headers) are included in the cache key and automatically included in
--   requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.
--   
--   <a>$sel:cookiesConfig:ParametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin'</a>,
--   <a>parametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin_cookiesConfig</a> - An
--   object that determines whether any cookies in viewer requests (and if
--   so, which cookies) are included in the cache key and automatically
--   included in requests that CloudFront sends to the origin.
--   
--   
--   <a>$sel:queryStringsConfig:ParametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin'</a>,
--   <a>parametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin_queryStringsConfig</a> -
--   An object that determines whether any URL query strings in viewer
--   requests (and if so, which query strings) are included in the cache
--   key and automatically included in requests that CloudFront sends to
--   the origin.
newParametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin :: Bool -> CachePolicyHeadersConfig -> CachePolicyCookiesConfig -> CachePolicyQueryStringsConfig -> ParametersInCacheKeyAndForwardedToOrigin

-- | A real-time log configuration.

data RealtimeLogConfig

-- | Create a value of <a>RealtimeLogConfig</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:arn:RealtimeLogConfig'</a>, <a>realtimeLogConfig_arn</a> - The
--   Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of this real-time log configuration.
--   
--   <a>$sel:name:RealtimeLogConfig'</a>, <a>realtimeLogConfig_name</a> -
--   The unique name of this real-time log configuration.
--   
--   <a>$sel:samplingRate:RealtimeLogConfig'</a>,
--   <a>realtimeLogConfig_samplingRate</a> - The sampling rate for this
--   real-time log configuration. The sampling rate determines the
--   percentage of viewer requests that are represented in the real-time
--   log data. The sampling rate is an integer between 1 and 100,
--   inclusive.
--   
--   <a>$sel:endPoints:RealtimeLogConfig'</a>,
--   <a>realtimeLogConfig_endPoints</a> - Contains information about the
--   Amazon Kinesis data stream where you are sending real-time log data
--   for this real-time log configuration.

--   an API response, the fields are provided in the same order in which
--   they are sent to the Amazon Kinesis data stream.

--   For more information about fields, see <a>Real-time log configuration
--   fields</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.

-- | A complex type that contains information about the Amazon S3 bucket
--   from which you want CloudFront to get your media files for
--   distribution.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newS3Origin</a> smart constructor.
data S3Origin
S3Origin' :: Text -> Text -> S3Origin

-- | Create a value of <a>S3Origin</a> with all optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--

--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:

--   name of the Amazon S3 origin.

--   <a>s3Origin_originAccessIdentity</a> - The CloudFront origin access
--   identity to associate with the distribution. Use an origin access
--   identity to configure the distribution so that end users can only
--   access objects in an Amazon S3 bucket through CloudFront.
--   
--   If you want end users to be able to access objects using either the
--   CloudFront URL or the Amazon S3 URL, specify an empty
--   <tt>OriginAccessIdentity</tt> element.
--   
--   To delete the origin access identity from an existing distribution,
--   update the distribution configuration and include an empty
--   <tt>OriginAccessIdentity</tt> element.
--   
--   To replace the origin access identity, update the distribution
--   configuration and specify the new origin access identity.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Using an Origin Access Identity to
--   Restrict Access to Your Amazon S3 Content</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
newS3Origin :: Text -> Text -> S3Origin

-- | A streaming distribution tells CloudFront where you want RTMP content
--   to be delivered from, and the details about how to track and manage
--   content delivery.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newStreamingDistribution</a> smart constructor.
data StreamingDistribution
StreamingDistribution' :: Maybe ISO8601 -> Text -> Text -> Text -> Text -> ActiveTrustedSigners -> StreamingDistributionConfig -> StreamingDistribution

-- | Create a value of <a>StreamingDistribution</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--

--   <a>streamingDistribution_lastModifiedTime</a> - The date and time that
--   the distribution was last modified.
--   
--   <a>$sel:id:StreamingDistribution'</a>, <a>streamingDistribution_id</a>
--   - The identifier for the RTMP distribution. For example:
--   <tt>EGTXBD79EXAMPLE</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:arn:StreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistribution_arn</a> - The ARN (Amazon Resource Name) for
--   the distribution. For example:
--   <tt>arn:aws:cloudfront::123456789012:distribution/EDFDVBD632BHDS5</tt>,
--   where <tt>123456789012</tt> is your account ID.
--   
--   <a>$sel:status:StreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistribution_status</a> - The current status of the RTMP
--   distribution. When the status is <tt>Deployed</tt>, the distribution's
--   information is propagated to all CloudFront edge locations.
--   
--   <a>$sel:domainName:StreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistribution_domainName</a> - The domain name that
--   corresponds to the streaming distribution, for example,
--   <tt>s5c39gqb8ow64r.cloudfront.net</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:activeTrustedSigners:StreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistribution_activeTrustedSigners</a> - A complex type
--   that lists the accounts, if any, that you included in the
--   <tt>TrustedSigners</tt> complex type for this distribution. These are
--   the accounts that you want to allow to create signed URLs for private
--   content.
--   
--   The <tt>Signer</tt> complex type lists the account number of the
--   trusted signer or <tt>self</tt> if the signer is the account that
--   created the distribution. The <tt>Signer</tt> element also includes
--   the IDs of any active CloudFront key pairs that are associated with
--   the trusted signer's account. If no <tt>KeyPairId</tt> element appears
--   for a <tt>Signer</tt>, that signer can't create signed URLs.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Serving Private Content through
--   CloudFront</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:streamingDistributionConfig:StreamingDistribution'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistribution_streamingDistributionConfig</a> - The current
--   configuration information for the RTMP distribution.
newStreamingDistribution :: Text -> Text -> Text -> Text -> ActiveTrustedSigners -> StreamingDistributionConfig -> StreamingDistribution

--   
--   <a>$sel:enabled:StreamingDistributionConfig'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistributionConfig_enabled</a> - Whether the streaming
--   distribution is enabled to accept user requests for content.

--   Name) for the streaming distribution. For example:
--   <tt>arn:aws:cloudfront::123456789012:streaming-distribution/EDFDVBD632BHDS5</tt>,

--   <a>$sel:trustedSigners:StreamingDistributionSummary'</a>,

--   that specifies the accounts, if any, that you want to allow to create
--   signed URLs for private content. If you want to require signed URLs in
--   requests for objects in the target origin that match the
--   <tt>PathPattern</tt> for this cache behavior, specify <tt>true</tt>
--   for <tt>Enabled</tt>, and specify the applicable values for
--   <tt>Quantity</tt> and <tt>Items</tt>.If you don't want to require
--   signed URLs in requests for objects that match <tt>PathPattern</tt>,
--   specify <tt>false</tt> for <tt>Enabled</tt> and <tt>0</tt> for
--   <tt>Quantity</tt>. Omit <tt>Items</tt>. To add, change, or remove one
--   or more trusted signers, change <tt>Enabled</tt> to <tt>true</tt> (if
--   it's currently <tt>false</tt>), change <tt>Quantity</tt> as
--   applicable, and specify all of the trusted signers that you want to
--   include in the updated distribution.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Serving Private Content through
--   CloudFront</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:comment:StreamingDistributionSummary'</a>,

--   specified when this distribution was created.
--   
--   <a>$sel:priceClass:StreamingDistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistributionSummary_priceClass</a> - A complex type that
--   contains information about price class for this streaming
--   distribution.
--   
--   <a>$sel:enabled:StreamingDistributionSummary'</a>,
--   <a>streamingDistributionSummary_enabled</a> - Whether the distribution
--   is enabled to accept end user requests for content.
newStreamingDistributionSummary :: Text -> Text -> Text -> UTCTime -> Text -> S3Origin -> Aliases -> TrustedSigners -> Text -> PriceClass -> Bool -> StreamingDistributionSummary

--   streaming distribution.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newStreamingLoggingConfig</a> smart constructor.
data StreamingLoggingConfig

-- | Create a value of <a>StreamingLoggingConfig</a> with all optional
--   fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:enabled:StreamingLoggingConfig'</a>,
--   <a>streamingLoggingConfig_enabled</a> - Specifies whether you want
--   CloudFront to save access logs to an Amazon S3 bucket. If you don't
--   want to enable logging when you create a streaming distribution or if
--   you want to disable logging for an existing streaming distribution,
--   specify <tt>false</tt> for <tt>Enabled</tt>, and specify <tt>empty
--   Bucket</tt> and <tt>Prefix</tt> elements. If you specify
--   <tt>false</tt> for <tt>Enabled</tt> but you specify values for
--   <tt>Bucket</tt> and <tt>Prefix</tt>, the values are automatically
--   deleted.

--   <a>streamingLoggingConfig_prefix</a> - An optional string that you
--   want CloudFront to prefix to the access log filenames for this
--   streaming distribution, for example, <tt>myprefix/</tt>. If you want
--   to enable logging, but you don't want to specify a prefix, you still
--   must include an empty <tt>Prefix</tt> element in the <tt>Logging</tt>
--   element.
newStreamingLoggingConfig :: Bool -> Text -> Text -> StreamingLoggingConfig

-- | A complex type that contains <tt>Tag</tt> key and <tt>Tag</tt> value.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newTag</a> smart constructor.
data Tag
Tag' :: Maybe Text -> Text -> Tag

-- | Create a value of <a>Tag</a> with all optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:value:Tag'</a>, <a>tag_value</a> - A string that contains an
--   optional <tt>Tag</tt> value.
--   
--   The string length should be between 0 and 256 characters. Valid
--   characters include <tt>a-z</tt>, <tt>A-Z</tt>, <tt>0-9</tt>, space,
--   and the special characters <tt>_ - . : / = + @</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:key:Tag'</a>, <a>tag_key</a> - A string that contains
--   <tt>Tag</tt> key.
--   
--   The string length should be between 1 and 128 characters. Valid
--   characters include <tt>a-z</tt>, <tt>A-Z</tt>, <tt>0-9</tt>, space,
--   and the special characters <tt>_ - . : / = + @</tt>.
newTag :: Text -> Tag

-- | A complex type that contains zero or more <tt>Tag</tt> elements.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newTagKeys</a> smart constructor.
data TagKeys
TagKeys' :: Maybe [Text] -> TagKeys

-- | Create a value of <a>TagKeys</a> with all optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:TagKeys'</a>, <a>tagKeys_items</a> - A complex type that
--   contains <tt>Tag</tt> key elements.
newTagKeys :: TagKeys

-- | A complex type that contains zero or more <tt>Tag</tt> elements.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newTags</a> smart constructor.
data Tags
Tags' :: Maybe [Tag] -> Tags

-- | Create a value of <a>Tags</a> with all optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:Tags'</a>, <a>tags_items</a> - A complex type that
--   contains <tt>Tag</tt> elements.
newTags :: Tags

-- | Contains the result of testing a CloudFront function with
--   <tt>TestFunction</tt>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newTestResult</a> smart constructor.
data TestResult
TestResult' :: Maybe Text -> Maybe [Text] -> Maybe Text -> Maybe FunctionSummary -> Maybe Text -> TestResult

-- | Create a value of <a>TestResult</a> with all optional fields omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:computeUtilization:TestResult'</a>,
--   <a>testResult_computeUtilization</a> - The amount of time that the
--   function took to run as a percentage of the maximum allowed time. For
--   example, a compute utilization of 35 means that the function completed
--   in 35% of the maximum allowed time.
--   
--   <a>$sel:functionExecutionLogs:TestResult'</a>,
--   <a>testResult_functionExecutionLogs</a> - Contains the log lines that
--   the function wrote (if any) when running the test.
--   
--   <a>$sel:functionOutput:TestResult'</a>,
--   <a>testResult_functionOutput</a> - The event object returned by the
--   function. For more information about the structure of the event
--   object, see <a>Event object structure</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront
--   Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:functionSummary:TestResult'</a>,
--   <a>testResult_functionSummary</a> - Contains configuration information
--   and metadata about the CloudFront function that was tested.
--   
--   <a>$sel:functionErrorMessage:TestResult'</a>,
--   <a>testResult_functionErrorMessage</a> - If the result of testing the
--   function was an error, this field contains the error message.
newTestResult :: TestResult

-- | A list of key groups whose public keys CloudFront can use to verify
--   the signatures of signed URLs and signed cookies.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newTrustedKeyGroups</a> smart constructor.
data TrustedKeyGroups
TrustedKeyGroups' :: Maybe [Text] -> Bool -> Int -> TrustedKeyGroups

-- | Create a value of <a>TrustedKeyGroups</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:TrustedKeyGroups'</a>, <a>trustedKeyGroups_items</a> - A
--   list of key groups identifiers.
--   
--   <a>$sel:enabled:TrustedKeyGroups'</a>, <a>trustedKeyGroups_enabled</a>
--   - This field is <tt>true</tt> if any of the key groups in the list
--   have public keys that CloudFront can use to verify the signatures of
--   signed URLs and signed cookies. If not, this field is <tt>false</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:TrustedKeyGroups'</a>,
--   <a>trustedKeyGroups_quantity</a> - The number of key groups in the
--   list.
newTrustedKeyGroups :: Bool -> Int -> TrustedKeyGroups

-- | A list of accounts whose public keys CloudFront can use to verify the
--   signatures of signed URLs and signed cookies.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newTrustedSigners</a> smart constructor.
data TrustedSigners
TrustedSigners' :: Maybe [Text] -> Bool -> Int -> TrustedSigners

-- | Create a value of <a>TrustedSigners</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:items:TrustedSigners'</a>, <a>trustedSigners_items</a> - A
--   list of account identifiers.
--   
--   <a>$sel:enabled:TrustedSigners'</a>, <a>trustedSigners_enabled</a> -
--   This field is <tt>true</tt> if any of the accounts have public keys
--   that CloudFront can use to verify the signatures of signed URLs and
--   signed cookies. If not, this field is <tt>false</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:quantity:TrustedSigners'</a>, <a>trustedSigners_quantity</a> -
--   The number of accounts in the list.
newTrustedSigners :: Bool -> Int -> TrustedSigners

-- | A complex type that determines the distribution’s SSL/TLS
--   configuration for communicating with viewers.
--   
--   If the distribution doesn’t use <tt>Aliases</tt> (also known as
--   alternate domain names or CNAMEs)—that is, if the distribution uses
--   the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>—set
--   <tt>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</tt> to <tt>true</tt> and leave all
--   other fields empty.
--   
--   If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), use the fields in this type to specify the following
--   settings:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>Which viewers the distribution accepts HTTPS connections from:
--   only viewers that support <a>server name indication (SNI)</a>
--   (recommended), or all viewers including those that don’t support
--   SNI.<ul><li>To accept HTTPS connections from only viewers that support
--   SNI, set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to <tt>sni-only</tt>. This is
--   recommended. Most browsers and clients support SNI.</li><li>To accept
--   HTTPS connections from all viewers, including those that don’t support
--   SNI, set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to <tt>vip</tt>. This is not
--   recommended, and results in additional monthly charges from
--   CloudFront.</li></ul></li>
--   <li>The minimum SSL/TLS protocol version that the distribution can use
--   to communicate with viewers. To specify a minimum version, choose a
--   value for <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt>. For more information, see
--   <a>Security Policy</a> in the <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer
--   Guide</i>.</li>
--   <li>The location of the SSL/TLS certificate, <a>Certificate Manager
--   (ACM)</a> (recommended) or <a>Identity and Access Management
--   (IAM)</a>. You specify the location by setting a value in one of the
--   following fields (not
--   both):<ul><li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li><li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li></ul></li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   All distributions support HTTPS connections from viewers. To require
--   viewers to use HTTPS only, or to redirect them from HTTP to HTTPS, use
--   <tt>ViewerProtocolPolicy</tt> in the <tt>CacheBehavior</tt> or
--   <tt>DefaultCacheBehavior</tt>. To specify how CloudFront should use
--   SSL/TLS to communicate with your custom origin, use
--   <tt>CustomOriginConfig</tt>.
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Using HTTPS with CloudFront</a> and
--   <a>Using Alternate Domain Names and HTTPS</a> in the <i>Amazon
--   CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   <i>See:</i> <a>newViewerCertificate</a> smart constructor.
data ViewerCertificate
ViewerCertificate' :: Maybe SSLSupportMethod -> Maybe Text -> Maybe CertificateSource -> Maybe MinimumProtocolVersion -> Maybe Text -> Maybe Text -> Maybe Bool -> ViewerCertificate

-- | Create a value of <a>ViewerCertificate</a> with all optional fields
--   omitted.
--   
--   Use <a>generic-lens</a> or <a>optics</a> to modify other optional
--   fields.
--   
--   The following record fields are available, with the corresponding
--   lenses provided for backwards compatibility:
--   
--   <a>$sel:sSLSupportMethod:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_sSLSupportMethod</a> - If the distribution uses
--   <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or CNAMEs), specify which
--   viewers the distribution accepts HTTPS connections from.
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>sni-only</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections
--   from only viewers that support <a>server name indication (SNI)</a>.
--   This is recommended. Most browsers and clients support SNI.</li>
--   <li><tt>vip</tt> – The distribution accepts HTTPS connections from all
--   viewers including those that don’t support SNI. This is not
--   recommended, and results in additional monthly charges from
--   CloudFront.</li>
--   <li><tt>static-ip</tt> - Do not specify this value unless your
--   distribution has been enabled for this feature by the CloudFront team.
--   If you have a use case that requires static IP addresses for a
--   distribution, contact CloudFront through the <a>Amazon Web Services
--   Support Center</a>.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, don’t set a value for this
--   field.
--   
--   <a>$sel:aCMCertificateArn:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_aCMCertificateArn</a> - If the distribution uses
--   <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS
--   certificate is stored in <a>Certificate Manager (ACM)</a>, provide the
--   Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the ACM certificate. CloudFront only
--   supports ACM certificates in the US East (N. Virginia) Region
--   (<tt>us-east-1</tt>).
--   
--   If you specify an ACM certificate ARN, you must also specify values
--   for <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:certificateSource:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_certificateSource</a> - This field is deprecated.
--   Use one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   <a>$sel:minimumProtocolVersion:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_minimumProtocolVersion</a> - If the distribution
--   uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or CNAMEs), specify the
--   security policy that you want CloudFront to use for HTTPS connections
--   with viewers. The security policy determines two settings:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>The minimum SSL/TLS protocol that CloudFront can use to
--   communicate with viewers.</li>
--   <li>The ciphers that CloudFront can use to encrypt the content that it
--   returns to viewers.</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   For more information, see <a>Security Policy</a> and <a>Supported
--   Protocols and Ciphers Between Viewers and CloudFront</a> in the
--   <i>Amazon CloudFront Developer Guide</i>.
--   
--   On the CloudFront console, this setting is called <b>Security
--   Policy</b>.
--   
--   When you’re using SNI only (you set <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt> to
--   <tt>sni-only</tt>), you must specify <tt>TLSv1</tt> or higher.
--   
--   If the distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt> (you set
--   <tt>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</tt> to <tt>true</tt>), CloudFront
--   automatically sets the security policy to <tt>TLSv1</tt> regardless of
--   the value that you set here.
--   
--   <a>$sel:certificate:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_certificate</a> - This field is deprecated. Use
--   one of the following fields instead:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><pre>ACMCertificateArn</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>IAMCertificateId</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>CloudFrontDefaultCertificate</pre></li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   <a>$sel:iAMCertificateId:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_iAMCertificateId</a> - If the distribution uses
--   <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or CNAMEs) and the SSL/TLS
--   certificate is stored in <a>Identity and Access Management (IAM)</a>,
--   provide the ID of the IAM certificate.
--   
--   If you specify an IAM certificate ID, you must also specify values for
--   <tt>MinimumProtocolVersion</tt> and <tt>SSLSupportMethod</tt>.
--   
--   <a>$sel:cloudFrontDefaultCertificate:ViewerCertificate'</a>,
--   <a>viewerCertificate_cloudFrontDefaultCertificate</a> - If the
--   distribution uses the CloudFront domain name such as
--   <tt>d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net</tt>, set this field to
--   <tt>true</tt>.
--   
--   If the distribution uses <tt>Aliases</tt> (alternate domain names or
--   CNAMEs), set this field to <tt>false</tt> and specify values for the
--   following fields:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li><tt>ACMCertificateArn</tt> or <tt>IAMCertificateId</tt> (specify a
--   value for one, not both)</li>
--   <li><pre>MinimumProtocolVersion</pre></li>
--   <li><pre>SSLSupportMethod</pre></li>
--   </ul>
newViewerCertificate :: ViewerCertificate
